ep.

The distributional gap between real and simulated user behaviors in the paper is illustrated by the UMAP projections and first principal component histograms. The `Gemini 3.1 Pro` simulator overlaps more closely with real users compared to the `Llama-3.1-8B-Instruct` simulator.

The distributional gap between real and simulated user behaviors in the paper 2605.07847v1 is large, as revealed by a systematic evaluation of 24 LLM-based user simulators across coding and writing tasks. This gap indicates that most simulators behave similarly but do not fully capture the diversity and nuances of real users' behaviors.

The distributional gap between real and simulated user behaviors in the paper is significant, as evidenced by high classification accuracies ranging from 90.92% to 99.63% when using L2-regularized logistic regression classifiers trained on embeddings of real and simulated users. However, the comparison of behavior distributions among simulators shows that many simulators behave similarly to each other, with 30% of pairwise comparisons having JS divergence less than 0.10. Simulators from the same family are the most similar, achieving the lowest scores in the dataset.

The distributional gap between real and simulated user behaviors in paper 2605.07847v1 refers to the difference measured by the authors using a method they introduced, which validated through human studies and ablations. This gap is large and varies across model families, scales, and behavioral facets.

