**6.3** **Linear Classification**","[{'id': 'retrieved-1', 'title': 'GraphRAG Candidate', 'snippet': 'The distributional gap between real and simulated user behaviors in the paper is significant. The simpler representations, such as raw conversations and user utterances only, produce low divergences across all simulators, suggesting that simulators closely match real users on one task. However, this similarity is an artifact of surface-level features like lexical and semantic overlap rather than reflecting behavioral patterns. By using behavioral descriptions, much larger and more meaningful gaps are revealed, confirming the necessity of this step.', 'score': 95.0, 'metadata': {'candidate_answer': 'The distributional gap between real and simulated user behaviors in the paper is significant. The simpler representations, such as raw conversations and user utterances only, produce low divergences across all simulators, suggesting that simulators closely match real users on one task. However, this similarity is an artifact of surface-level features like lexical and semantic overlap rather than reflecting behavioral patterns. By using behavioral descriptions, much larger and more meaningful gaps are revealed, confirming the necessity of this step.', 'score': 95}}, {'id': 'retrieved-2', 'title': 'GraphRAG Candidate', 'snippet': 'The distributional gap between real and simulated user behaviors in the paper is illustrated by the UMAP projections and first principal component histograms. The `Gemini 3.1 Pro` simulator overlaps more closely with real users compared to the `Llama-3.1-8B-Instruct` simulator.', 'score': 95.0, 'metadata': {'candidate_answer': 'The distributional gap between real and simulated user behaviors in the paper is illustrated by the UMAP projections and first principal component histograms. The `Gemini 3.1 Pro` simulator overlaps more closely with real users compared to the `Llama-3.1-8B-Instruct` simulator.', 'score': 95}}, {'id': 'retrieved-3', 'title': 'GraphRAG Candidate', 'snippet': ""The distributional gap between real and simulated user behaviors in the paper 2605.07847v1 is large, as revealed by a systematic evaluation of 24 LLM-based user simulators across coding and writing tasks. This gap indicates that most simulators behave similarly but do not fully capture the diversity and nuances of real users' behaviors."", 'score': 95.0, 'metadata': {'candidate_answer': ""The distributional gap between real and simulated user behaviors in the paper 2605.07847v1 is large, as revealed by a systematic evaluation of 24 LLM-based user simulators across coding and writing tasks. This gap indicates that most simulators behave similarly but do not fully capture the diversity and nuances of real users' behaviors."", 'score': 95}}, {'id': 'retrieved-4', 'title': 'GraphRAG Candidate', 'snippet': 'The distributional gap between real and simulated user behaviors in the paper is significant, as evidenced by high classification accuracies ranging from 90.92% to 99.63% when using L2-regularized logistic regression classifiers trained on embeddings of real and simulated users. However, the comparison of behavior distributions among simulators shows that many simulators behave similarly to each other, with 30% of pairwise comparisons having JS divergence less than 0.10. Simulators from the same family are the most similar, achieving the lowest scores in the dataset.', 'score': 95.0, 'metadata': {'candidate_answer': 'The distributional gap between real and simulated user behaviors in the paper is significant, as evidenced by high classification accuracies ranging from 90.92% to 99.63% when using L2-regularized logistic regression classifiers trained on embeddings of real and simulated users. However, the comparison of behavior distributions among simulators shows that many simulators behave similarly to each other, with 30% of pairwise comparisons having JS divergence less than 0.10. Simulators from the same family are the most similar, achieving the lowest scores in the dataset.', 'score': 95}}, {'id': 'retrieved-5', 'title': 'GraphRAG Candidate', 'snippet': 'The distributional gap between real and simulated user behaviors in paper 2605.07847v1 refers to the difference measured by the authors using a method they introduced, which validated through human studies and ablations. This gap is large and varies across model families, scales, and behavioral facets.', 'score': 95.0, 'metadata': {'candidate_answer': 'The distributional gap between real and simulated user behaviors in paper 2605.07847v1 refers to the difference measured by the authors using a method they introduced, which validated through human studies and ablations. This gap is large and varies across model families, scales, and behavioral facets.', 'score': 95}}, {'id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_17', 'title': '2605.07847v1_chunk_17', 'snippet': '7\n\n\nTable 3: The distributional gap between real and simulated user behaviors when combining pairs\nof simulators. When generating conversations, we randomly sample which LLM serves as the\nuser simulator. We report forward KL divergence (KL ), backward KL divergence (KL bwd ), and\nJensen–Shannon divergence (JS) across coding and writing tasks. "" indicates higher is better and #\nindicates lower is better. Darker blue indicates closer behavioral distribution to real users. Subscripts\nshow the change relative to the better of the two individual simulators\n\n\n**Coding** **Writing**\n\n\n**User Simulator** KL KL bwd JS # KL KL bwd JS #\n\n\n: : : : : :\n\n\n**el** **s** ed **al** ucinted\n\n\n**el** **s**\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_8)\n\n: : : : : :\n\n\n**el** **s** ed **al** ucinted\n\n\n**el** **s**\n\n\n\n: : : : : :\n\n\n**el** **s** ed **al** ucinted\n\n\n**el** **s**\n\n\n\n`gemma-4-31B-it` + `Claude Haiku 4.5` .364 _↑_ : .345 _↑_ : .346 _↑_ : .562 _↑_ : .568 _↑_ : .572 _↑_ :\n\n\n`gemma-4-26B-A4B-it` (0 _._ 15), `gemma-4-E2B-it` (0 _._ 15), and `Qwen3.5-35B-A3B` (0 _._ 15). A few\nsimulators stand out and demonstrate behaviors that diverge from the rest. These include `UserLM-8b`,\nwhich has the highest mean pairwise JS score of 0 _._ 41, followed by `GPT-5.4 mini` with a score of\n0 _._ 33. Pairwise JS scores are consistently higher for writing than coding, which aligns with our main\nresults, where the divergences from real users were also higher for writing.\n\n\n**7.2** **Can we Combine User Simulators to Reduce the Gap With Real Users?**\n\n\nSince our pairwise analysis shows that some user simulators behave distinctly from each other, we\ntest whether combining pairs can reduce the gap to real users by randomly sampling which simulator\ngenerates each conversation. Table 3 reports the results.', 'score': None, 'metadata': {'vertex_id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_17', 'snippets': ['7\n\n\nTable 3: The distributional gap between real and simulated user behaviors when combining pairs\nof simulators. When generating conversations, we randomly sample which LLM serves as the\nuser simulator. We report forward KL divergence (KL ), backward KL divergence (KL bwd ), and\nJensen–Shannon divergence (JS) across coding and writing tasks. "" indicates higher is better and #\nindicates lower is better. Darker blue indicates closer behavioral distribution to real users. Subscripts\nshow the change relative to the better of the two individual simulators\n\n\n**Coding** **Writing**\n\n\n**User Simulator** KL KL bwd JS # KL KL bwd JS #\n\n\n: : : : : :\n\n\n**el** **s** ed **al** ucinted\n\n\n**el** **s**\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_8)\n\n: : : : : :\n\n\n**el** **s** ed **al** ucinted\n\n\n**el** **s**\n\n\n\n: : : : : :\n\n\n**el** **s** ed **al** ucinted\n\n\n**el** **s**\n\n\n\n`gemma-4-31B-it` + `Claude Haiku 4.5` .364 _↑_ : .345 _↑_ : .346 _↑_ : .562 _↑_ : .568 _↑_ : .572 _↑_ :\n\n\n`gemma-4-26B-A4B-it` (0 _._ 15), `gemma-4-E2B-it` (0 _._ 15), and `Qwen3.5-35B-A3B` (0 _._ 15). A few\nsimulators stand out and demonstrate behaviors that diverge from the rest. These include `UserLM-8b`,\nwhich has the highest mean pairwise JS score of 0 _._ 41, followed by `GPT-5.4 mini` with a score of\n0 _._ 33. Pairwise JS scores are consistently higher for writing than coding, which aligns with our main\nresults, where the divergences from real users were also higher for writing.\n\n\n**7.2** **Can we Combine User Simulators to Reduce the Gap With Real Users?**\n\n\nSince our pairwise analysis shows that some user simulators behave distinctly from each other, we\ntest whether combining pairs can reduce the gap to real users by randomly sampling which simulator\ngenerates each conversation. Table 3 reports the results.']}}, {'id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_14', 'title': '2605.07847v1_chunk_14', 'snippet': '**User Behavior Descriptions.** We use an LLM to generate\nuser behavior descriptions for each conversation to isolate user\nbehavioral patterns and abstract away irrelevant surface-level\nfeatures from the raw conversation history. To validate that\nthis step is necessary, we compare against two simpler rep\nFigure 2: Scatter plot of classifica\nresentations: the raw conversations and user utterances only.\n\ntion accuracy and Jensen–Shannon\n\nTable 10 (Appendix G) reports the full results for all simulators\n\nDivergence (JS) for all simulators\n\nacross both tasks. These simpler representations produce low\n\nacross coding and writing tasks.\n\ndivergences across all simulators, which would suggest that\n\nEach point represents one simulator\n\nsimulators closely match real users. However, this similarity is on one task.\nan artifact of surface-level features such as lexical and semantic\noverlap, rather than reflecting behavioral patterns. Our behavioral descriptions, by contrast, reveal\nmuch larger and more meaningful gaps, confirming that this step is necessary.\n\n\n**Embedding Models.** User behavior descriptions are embedded using `Qwen3-Embedding-8B` . To\nverify that our results are robust across embedding models, we repeat our experiments using two\nother embedding models: `e5-large-v2` [57] and `BGE-small-en-v1.5` [60]. We apply z-score\nnormalization to metric values within each dataset and then compute the Spearman rank correlation\nbetween simulator rankings produced by each pair of embedding models. Table 2 report the results,\nand Figure 15 (Appendix G) provide scatter plot visualizations. Simulator rankings are largely\npreserved across different embedding models.', 'score': None, 'metadata': {'vertex_id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_14', 'snippets': ['**User Behavior Descriptions.** We use an LLM to generate\nuser behavior descriptions for each conversation to isolate user\nbehavioral patterns and abstract away irrelevant surface-level\nfeatures from the raw conversation history. To validate that\nthis step is necessary, we compare against two simpler rep\nFigure 2: Scatter plot of classifica\nresentations: the raw conversations and user utterances only.\n\ntion accuracy and Jensen–Shannon\n\nTable 10 (Appendix G) reports the full results for all simulators\n\nDivergence (JS) for all simulators\n\nacross both tasks. These simpler representations produce low\n\nacross coding and writing tasks.\n\ndivergences across all simulators, which would suggest that\n\nEach point represents one simulator\n\nsimulators closely match real users. However, this similarity is on one task.\nan artifact of surface-level features such as lexical and semantic\noverlap, rather than reflecting behavioral patterns. Our behavioral descriptions, by contrast, reveal\nmuch larger and more meaningful gaps, confirming that this step is necessary.\n\n\n**Embedding Models.** User behavior descriptions are embedded using `Qwen3-Embedding-8B` . To\nverify that our results are robust across embedding models, we repeat our experiments using two\nother embedding models: `e5-large-v2` [57] and `BGE-small-en-v1.5` [60]. We apply z-score\nnormalization to metric values within each dataset and then compute the Spearman rank correlation\nbetween simulator rankings produced by each pair of embedding models. Table 2 report the results,\nand Figure 15 (Appendix G) provide scatter plot visualizations. Simulator rankings are largely\npreserved across different embedding models.']}}, {'id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_0', 'title': '2605.07847v1_chunk_0', 'snippet': '**Shuhaib Mehri** _[♠]_ **Philippe Laban** _[♢]_ **Sumuk Shashidhar** _[♠]_ **Marwa Abdulhai** [⋆]\n\n**Sergey Levine** [⋆] **Michel Galley** _[♢]_ **Dilek Hakkani-Tür** _[♠]_\n\n_♠_ University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign _♢_ Microsoft Research\n⋆University of California, Berkeley', 'score': None, 'metadata': {'vertex_id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_0', 'snippets': ['\n**Shuhaib Mehri** _[♠]_ **Philippe Laban** _[♢]_ **Sumuk Shashidhar** _[♠]_ **Marwa Abdulhai** [⋆]\n\n**Sergey Levine** [⋆] **Michel Galley** _[♢]_ **Dilek Hakkani-Tür** _[♠]_\n\n_♠_ University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign _♢_ Microsoft Research\n⋆University of California, Berkeley\n\n']}}, {'id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_3', 'title': '2605.07847v1_chunk_3', 'snippet': '![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_2)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n||||\n|---|---|---|\n|Qu|a|ntiz|\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_3)\n\nFigure 1: Our method extracts representations of user behavior from real and simulated conversations, then quantizes them via _k_ -means to get discrete behavioral distributions for real ( _P_ [ˆ] ) and\nsimulated users ( _Q_ [ˆ] ). UMAP projections [30] and first principal component histograms illustrate the\ndistributional gap for two simulators on the coding task: `Gemini 3.1 Pro` overlaps real users more\nclosely compared to `Llama-3.1-8B-Instruct` .\n\n\nPreprint.\n\n\n**1** **Introduction**\n\n\nThe role of user simulators is to model the diverse behaviors of real users, providing a scalable\nmeans to train and evaluate AI systems on the interactions that they encounter in real-world settings\n\n[26, 14, 39, 45]. Recent works build user simulators by training Large Language Models (LLMs)\nto generate responses that resemble those of real users [33, 16, 58]. Yet real users exhibit a broad,\nheterogeneous distribution of behaviors [65, 66, 28]. For example, some users tend to underspecify\ntheir requests, while others fully specify every constraint. The extent to which user simulators capture\nthis distribution has not been measured.\n\n\nA user simulator can fail to capture the distribution of real users in two ways: by demonstrating\nbehaviors that real users rarely exhibit (low prec **i** son), or by failing to demonstrate behaviors that real\nusers do exhibit (low reca **l** ), mirroring precision and recall metrics for generative models [ 46, 23, 11].\nThese failure modes bias training and evaluation, and yield assistants that struggle to generalize to\nthe diverse behaviors of real users [52].', 'score': None, 'metadata': {'vertex_id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_3', 'snippets': ['![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_2)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n||||\n|---|---|---|\n|Qu|a|ntiz|\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_3)\n\nFigure 1: Our method extracts representations of user behavior from real and simulated conversations, then quantizes them via _k_ -means to get discrete behavioral distributions for real ( _P_ [ˆ] ) and\nsimulated users ( _Q_ [ˆ] ). UMAP projections [30] and first principal component histograms illustrate the\ndistributional gap for two simulators on the coding task: `Gemini 3.1 Pro` overlaps real users more\nclosely compared to `Llama-3.1-8B-Instruct` .\n\n\nPreprint.\n\n\n**1** **Introduction**\n\n\nThe role of user simulators is to model the diverse behaviors of real users, providing a scalable\nmeans to train and evaluate AI systems on the interactions that they encounter in real-world settings\n\n[26, 14, 39, 45]. Recent works build user simulators by training Large Language Models (LLMs)\nto generate responses that resemble those of real users [33, 16, 58]. Yet real users exhibit a broad,\nheterogeneous distribution of behaviors [65, 66, 28]. For example, some users tend to underspecify\ntheir requests, while others fully specify every constraint. The extent to which user simulators capture\nthis distribution has not been measured.\n\n\nA user simulator can fail to capture the distribution of real users in two ways: by demonstrating\nbehaviors that real users rarely exhibit (low prec **i** son), or by failing to demonstrate behaviors that real\nusers do exhibit (low reca **l** ), mirroring precision and recall metrics for generative models [ 46, 23, 11].\nThese failure modes bias training and evaluation, and yield assistants that struggle to generalize to\nthe diverse behaviors of real users [52].']}}, {'id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_4', 'title': '2605.07847v1_chunk_4', 'snippet': 'We introduce a method to compare the distributions of user behaviors in real and simulated conversations, illustrated in Figure 1. For each conversation, we extract a representation of the user’s\nbehavior by using an LLM to generate a description along six behavioral facets (such as how they\nmake requests or what dialog acts they perform) and then embedding it into a shared semantic space.\nNext, we quantize these representations into discrete distributions over user behavior modes by\nclustering [46, 41]. Finally, we measure the gap between the real and simulated distributions using\ndivergence-based metrics. We confirm that our method captures meaningful behavioral distributions\nand is robust to the choice of embedding model and clustering algorithm through a human study and\nvalidation studies.\n\n\nWe provide the first systematic evaluation of 24 LLM-based user simulators across coding and writing\ntasks, including 7 closed-source LLMs, 15 open-source LLMs, and 2 trained simulators. Our results\nreveal a large distributional gap from real users, and surface insights across model families, scales, and\nbehavioral facets. Pairwise comparisons between simulators show that most behave similarly, while a\nfew stand apart. Combining behaviorally complementary simulators brings the resulting distribution\ncloser to real users than either simulator on its own. Lastly, a TF-IDF analysis of the clusters provides\ninterpretable insights into behaviors that user simulators capture, miss, and hallucinate.', 'score': None, 'metadata': {'vertex_id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_4', 'snippets': ['We introduce a method to compare the distributions of user behaviors in real and simulated conversations, illustrated in Figure 1. For each conversation, we extract a representation of the user’s\nbehavior by using an LLM to generate a description along six behavioral facets (such as how they\nmake requests or what dialog acts they perform) and then embedding it into a shared semantic space.\nNext, we quantize these representations into discrete distributions over user behavior modes by\nclustering [46, 41]. Finally, we measure the gap between the real and simulated distributions using\ndivergence-based metrics. We confirm that our method captures meaningful behavioral distributions\nand is robust to the choice of embedding model and clustering algorithm through a human study and\nvalidation studies.\n\n\nWe provide the first systematic evaluation of 24 LLM-based user simulators across coding and writing\ntasks, including 7 closed-source LLMs, 15 open-source LLMs, and 2 trained simulators. Our results\nreveal a large distributional gap from real users, and surface insights across model families, scales, and\nbehavioral facets. Pairwise comparisons between simulators show that most behave similarly, while a\nfew stand apart. Combining behaviorally complementary simulators brings the resulting distribution\ncloser to real users than either simulator on its own. Lastly, a TF-IDF analysis of the clusters provides\ninterpretable insights into behaviors that user simulators capture, miss, and hallucinate.']}}, {'id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_1', 'title': '2605.07847v1_chunk_1', 'snippet': '```\n             mehri2@illinois.edu\n\n```', 'score': None, 'metadata': {'vertex_id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_1', 'snippets': ['```\n             mehri2@illinois.edu\n\n```\n']}}, {'id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_16', 'title': '2605.07847v1_chunk_16', 'snippet': '**6.3** **Linear Classification**\n\n\nWe validate that our user behavior representation embeddings encode meaningful differences between\nreal and simulated users by training a linear classifier. For each simulator, we construct a dataset\nof 5,000 real and 5,000 simulated embeddings, and then train an L2-regularized logistic regression\nclassifier to classify embeddings as real or simulated. We average results over 5 stratified random\n80/20 train-test splits. The classification accuracies across simulators are consistently high, ranging\nfrom 90.92% to 99.63%, and also correlate strongly with our distributional metrics (Figure 2). This\nconfirms that the embeddings encode meaningful differences between real and simulated users. The\nfull accuracy scores and correlations for all metrics are presented in Appendix H.\n\n\n**7** **Discussion**\n\n\n**7.1** **How Do User Behavior Distributions Compare Among Simulators?**\n\n\nOur main results show that the distributional gap to real users varies across simulators. This raises a\nnatural question: how do the behviorl d **a** rbuon of user **ist** imulator compare to each other? **s** To\ninvestigate this, we pool the user behavior representations across all 24 simulators, quantize them\ninto distributions, and compute the JS divergence between all pairs. Figure 3 reports the results.\n\n\nMany simulators behave similarly to each other: 30% of the 552 pairwise comparisons have JS _<_\n0 _._ 10. Pairs from the same family tend to be the most similar, achieving the lowest scores in the\ndataset. The simulators with the lowest mean pairwise JS scores are `Qwen3.5-122B-A10B` (0 _._ 14),\n\n\n7', 'score': None, 'metadata': {'vertex_id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_16', 'snippets': ['**6.3** **Linear Classification**\n\n\nWe validate that our user behavior representation embeddings encode meaningful differences between\nreal and simulated users by training a linear classifier. For each simulator, we construct a dataset\nof 5,000 real and 5,000 simulated embeddings, and then train an L2-regularized logistic regression\nclassifier to classify embeddings as real or simulated. We average results over 5 stratified random\n80/20 train-test splits. The classification accuracies across simulators are consistently high, ranging\nfrom 90.92% to 99.63%, and also correlate strongly with our distributional metrics (Figure 2). This\nconfirms that the embeddings encode meaningful differences between real and simulated users. The\nfull accuracy scores and correlations for all metrics are presented in Appendix H.\n\n\n**7** **Discussion**\n\n\n**7.1** **How Do User Behavior Distributions Compare Among Simulators?**\n\n\nOur main results show that the distributional gap to real users varies across simulators. This raises a\nnatural question: how do the behviorl d **a** rbuon of user **ist** imulator compare to each other? **s** To\ninvestigate this, we pool the user behavior representations across all 24 simulators, quantize them\ninto distributions, and compute the JS divergence between all pairs. Figure 3 reports the results.\n\n\nMany simulators behave similarly to each other: 30% of the 552 pairwise comparisons have JS _<_\n0 _._ 10. Pairs from the same family tend to be the most similar, achieving the lowest scores in the\ndataset. The simulators with the lowest mean pairwise JS scores are `Qwen3.5-122B-A10B` (0 _._ 14),\n\n\n7']}}, {'id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_5', 'title': '2605.07847v1_chunk_5', 'snippet': 'Our work advances toward user simulators that faithfully represent the diversity of real users with the\nfollowing contributions: (1) We introduce a method for measuring the distributional gap between\nreal and simulated user behaviors, validated through a human study and ablations; (2) Our analysis\nof 7 closed-source LLMs, 15 open-source LLMs and 2 trained simulators on coding and writing\ntasks reveals a large distributional gap from real users that varies across model families, scales, and\nbehavioral facets; (3) We show that combining behaviorally complementary simulators brings the\nresulting distribution closer to real users than either simulator on its own; (4) We present a TF-IDF\nanalysis of behavior clusters that surfaces interpretable insights into behaviors that simulators capture,\nmiss, and hallucinate.\n\n\n**2** **Problem Formulation**\n\n\nIn this section, we formalize the problem of evaluating how well a user simulator captures the\ndistribution of real user behaviors. Let _P_ denote the distribution of real user behaviors, and _Q_ denote\nthe distribution of simulated user behaviors. Our objective is to measure the gap between _P_ and _Q_ .\n\n\nIn practice, _P_ and _Q_ are not directly observable. Instead, we access them through datasets of\nconversations, where each conversation is a sequence C n = ( _u_ 1 _, a_ 1 _, . . ., u_ n _, a_ n ), with _u_ i and _a_\ndenoting the user and assistant utterances at turn _i_ . We use D real [, a dataset of real user-assistant]\nconversations, as samples from _P_ .', 'score': None, 'metadata': {'vertex_id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_5', 'snippets': ['Our work advances toward user simulators that faithfully represent the diversity of real users with the\nfollowing contributions: (1) We introduce a method for measuring the distributional gap between\nreal and simulated user behaviors, validated through a human study and ablations; (2) Our analysis\nof 7 closed-source LLMs, 15 open-source LLMs and 2 trained simulators on coding and writing\ntasks reveals a large distributional gap from real users that varies across model families, scales, and\nbehavioral facets; (3) We show that combining behaviorally complementary simulators brings the\nresulting distribution closer to real users than either simulator on its own; (4) We present a TF-IDF\nanalysis of behavior clusters that surfaces interpretable insights into behaviors that simulators capture,\nmiss, and hallucinate.\n\n\n**2** **Problem Formulation**\n\n\nIn this section, we formalize the problem of evaluating how well a user simulator captures the\ndistribution of real user behaviors. Let _P_ denote the distribution of real user behaviors, and _Q_ denote\nthe distribution of simulated user behaviors. Our objective is to measure the gap between _P_ and _Q_ .\n\n\nIn practice, _P_ and _Q_ are not directly observable. Instead, we access them through datasets of\nconversations, where each conversation is a sequence C n = ( _u_ 1 _, a_ 1 _, . . ., u_ n _, a_ n ), with _u_ i and _a_\ndenoting the user and assistant utterances at turn _i_ . We use D real [, a dataset of real user-assistant]\nconversations, as samples from _P_ .']}}, {'id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_2', 'title': '2605.07847v1_chunk_2', 'snippet': '**Code** : `[https://github.com/shuhaibm/UserBehavioralDivergence](https://github.com/shuhaibm/UserBehavioralDivergence)`\n\n\n**Abstract**\n\n\nAs user simulators are increasingly used for interactive training and evaluation\nof AI assistants, it is essential that they represent the diverse behaviors of real\nusers. While existing works train user simulators to generate human-like responses,\nwhether they capture the broad and heterogeneous distribution of real user behaviors\nremains an open question. In this work, we introduce a method to measure the\ndistributional gap between real and simulated user behaviors, validated through a\nhuman study and ablations. Given a dataset of real and simulated conversations, our\nmethod extracts representations of user behavior from each conversation, quantizes\nthem into discrete distributions via clustering, then computes divergence metrics.\nWe provide the first systematic evaluation of 24 LLM-based user simulators on\ncoding and writing tasks, and reveal a large distributional gap from real users that\nvaries across model families, scales, and behavioral facets. Pairwise comparisons\nshow that most simulators behave similarly, while a few stand apart. Combining\nbehaviorally complementary simulators brings the resulting distribution closer to\nreal users compared to either simulator on its own. Finally, a TF-IDF analysis of\nthe clusters surfaces interpretable patterns of behaviors that simulators capture,\nmiss, and hallucinate.\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_1)\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_2)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n||||\n|---|---|---|\n|Qu|a|ntiz|\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_3)', 'score': None, 'metadata': {'vertex_id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_2', 'snippets': ['**Code** : `[https://github.com/shuhaibm/UserBehavioralDivergence](https://github.com/shuhaibm/UserBehavioralDivergence)`\n\n\n**Abstract**\n\n\nAs user simulators are increasingly used for interactive training and evaluation\nof AI assistants, it is essential that they represent the diverse behaviors of real\nusers. While existing works train user simulators to generate human-like responses,\nwhether they capture the broad and heterogeneous distribution of real user behaviors\nremains an open question. In this work, we introduce a method to measure the\ndistributional gap between real and simulated user behaviors, validated through a\nhuman study and ablations. Given a dataset of real and simulated conversations, our\nmethod extracts representations of user behavior from each conversation, quantizes\nthem into discrete distributions via clustering, then computes divergence metrics.\nWe provide the first systematic evaluation of 24 LLM-based user simulators on\ncoding and writing tasks, and reveal a large distributional gap from real users that\nvaries across model families, scales, and behavioral facets. Pairwise comparisons\nshow that most simulators behave similarly, while a few stand apart. Combining\nbehaviorally complementary simulators brings the resulting distribution closer to\nreal users compared to either simulator on its own. Finally, a TF-IDF analysis of\nthe clusters surfaces interpretable patterns of behaviors that simulators capture,\nmiss, and hallucinate.\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_1)\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_2)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n||||\n|---|---|---|\n|Qu|a|ntiz|\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_3)']}}, {'id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_15', 'title': '2605.07847v1_chunk_15', 'snippet': '**Clustering Algorithms.** We obtain discrete distributions of user behavior by clustering our embeddings using _k_ -means with _k_ = 500. To verify that our method is robust to the clustering algorithm,\nwe repeat our experiments using Gaussian Mixture Models and Agglomerative Clustering. Similar\nto the embedding model ablation, we compute the Spearman rank correlations between simulator\nrankings produced by each pair of clustering algorithms. Our results in Table 2 demonstrate that\nsimulator rankings are nearly identical across all pairs ( _ρ_ � 0 _._ 96 ), and scatter plot visualizations are\nprovided in Figure 15 (Appendix G).\n\n\n6\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_6)\n\n�\n\n\n**-en** 3Emb **d** Qwig8B **-l** sma\n\n**-en** 3Emb **d** Qwig8B **-e** 5\n\n**-l** BGEsmaenv1.5 **-e** 5\n\n\nK-Means **a** u **s**\n\nK-Means lom **eg**\n\nG **a** u **s** lom **eg**\n\n\n�\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_7)\n\n**a** **ist** **s**\n\n\n\nFigure 3: Pairwise Jensen–Shannon divergence between the behavior distributions of 24 user simulators across coding (lower triangle) and writing tasks (upper triangle), ordered by descending mean\npairwise JS divergence. Many simulators demonstrate similar behavioral distributions (lighter cells)\nwhile a few stand out (darker cells).\n\n\n**6.3** **Linear Classification**', 'score': None, 'metadata': {'vertex_id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_15', 'snippets': ['**Clustering Algorithms.** We obtain discrete distributions of user behavior by clustering our embeddings using _k_ -means with _k_ = 500. To verify that our method is robust to the clustering algorithm,\nwe repeat our experiments using Gaussian Mixture Models and Agglomerative Clustering. Similar\nto the embedding model ablation, we compute the Spearman rank correlations between simulator\nrankings produced by each pair of clustering algorithms. Our results in Table 2 demonstrate that\nsimulator rankings are nearly identical across all pairs ( _ρ_ � 0 _._ 96 ), and scatter plot visualizations are\nprovided in Figure 15 (Appendix G).\n\n\n6\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_6)\n\n�\n\n\n**-en** 3Emb **d** Qwig8B **-l** sma\n\n**-en** 3Emb **d** Qwig8B **-e** 5\n\n**-l** BGEsmaenv1.5 **-e** 5\n\n\nK-Means **a** u **s**\n\nK-Means lom **eg**\n\nG **a** u **s** lom **eg**\n\n\n�\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_7)\n\n**a** **ist** **s**\n\n\n\nFigure 3: Pairwise Jensen–Shannon divergence between the behavior distributions of 24 user simulators across coding (lower triangle) and writing tasks (upper triangle), ordered by descending mean\npairwise JS divergence. Many simulators demonstrate similar behavioral distributions (lighter cells)\nwhile a few stand out (darker cells).\n\n\n**6.3** **Linear Classification**']}}]","['GraphRAG Candidate', 'GraphRAG Candidate', 'GraphRAG Candidate', 'GraphRAG Candidate', 'GraphRAG Candidate', '2605.07847v1_chunk_17', '2605.07847v1_chunk_14', '2605.07847v1_chunk_0', '2605.07847v1_chunk_3', '2605.07847v1_chunk_4', '2605.07847v1_chunk_1', '2605.07847v1_chunk_16', '2605.07847v1_chunk_5', '2605.07847v1_chunk_2', '2605.07847v1_chunk_15']",14,3588,128,142,38623.113597000156,0.06533999976090854,0.0,38623.17965300008,graph,15,0.0,"{'response': ""The distributional gap between real and simulated user behaviors in paper 2605.07847v1 is significant, as revealed by a systematic evaluation of 24 LLM-based user simulators across coding and writing tasks. This gap indicates that most simulators behave similarly but do not fully capture the diversity and nuances of real users' behaviors. The simpler representations produce low divergences, suggesting surface-level similarities rather than capturing behavioral patterns. By using more detailed behavioral descriptions, much larger gaps are revealed. High classification accuracies ranging from 90.92% to 99.63% when using L2-regularized logistic regression classifiers trained on embeddings of real and simulated users further validate this gap. The `Gemini 3.1 Pro` simulator overlaps more closely with real users compared to the `Llama-3.1-8B-Instruct` simulator, as illustrated by UMAP projections and first principal component histograms."", 'retrieved': [{'candidate_answer': 'The distributional gap between real and simulated user behaviors in the paper is significant. The simpler representations, such as raw conversations and user utterances only, produce low divergences across all simulators, suggesting that simulators closely match real users on one task. However, this similarity is an artifact of surface-level features like lexical and semantic overlap rather than reflecting behavioral patterns. By using behavioral descriptions, much larger and more meaningful gaps are revealed, confirming the necessity of this step.', 'score': 95}, {'candidate_answer': 'The distributional gap between real and simulated user behaviors in the paper is illustrated by the UMAP projections and first principal component histograms. The `Gemini 3.1 Pro` simulator overlaps more closely with real users compared to the `Llama-3.1-8B-Instruct` simulator.', 'score': 95}, {'candidate_answer': ""The distributional gap between real and simulated user behaviors in the paper 2605.07847v1 is large, as revealed by a systematic evaluation of 24 LLM-based user simulators across coding and writing tasks. This gap indicates that most simulators behave similarly but do not fully capture the diversity and nuances of real users' behaviors."", 'score': 95}, {'candidate_answer': 'The distributional gap between real and simulated user behaviors in the paper is significant, as evidenced by high classification accuracies ranging from 90.92% to 99.63% when using L2-regularized logistic regression classifiers trained on embeddings of real and simulated users. However, the comparison of behavior distributions among simulators shows that many simulators behave similarly to each other, with 30% of pairwise comparisons having JS divergence less than 0.10. Simulators from the same family are the most similar, achieving the lowest scores in the dataset.', 'score': 95}, {'candidate_answer': 'The distributional gap between real and simulated user behaviors in paper 2605.07847v1 refers to the difference measured by the authors using a method they introduced, which validated through human studies and ablations. This gap is large and varies across model families, scales, and behavioral facets.', 'score': 95}], 'verbose': {'selected_set': [{'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_15', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_4', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_5', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_14', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_1', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_0', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_3', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_2', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_16', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_17', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}], 'start_set': [{'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_5', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_16', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_2', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_17', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_4', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}], 'final_retrieval': {'2605.07847v1_chunk_17': ['7\n\n\nTable 3: The distributional gap between real and simulated user behaviors when combining pairs\nof simulators. When generating conversations, we randomly sample which LLM serves as the\nuser simulator. We report forward KL divergence (KL ), backward KL divergence (KL bwd ), and\nJensen–Shannon divergence (JS) across coding and writing tasks. "" indicates higher is better and #\nindicates lower is better. Darker blue indicates closer behavioral distribution to real users. Subscripts\nshow the change relative to the better of the two individual simulators\n\n\n**Coding** **Writing**\n\n\n**User Simulator** KL KL bwd JS # KL KL bwd JS #\n\n\n: : : : : :\n\n\n**el** **s** ed **al** ucinted\n\n\n**el** **s**\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_8)\n\n: : : : : :\n\n\n**el** **s** ed **al** ucinted\n\n\n**el** **s**\n\n\n\n: : : : : :\n\n\n**el** **s** ed **al** ucinted\n\n\n**el** **s**\n\n\n\n`gemma-4-31B-it` + `Claude Haiku 4.5` .364 _↑_ : .345 _↑_ : .346 _↑_ : .562 _↑_ : .568 _↑_ : .572 _↑_ :\n\n\n`gemma-4-26B-A4B-it` (0 _._ 15), `gemma-4-E2B-it` (0 _._ 15), and `Qwen3.5-35B-A3B` (0 _._ 15). A few\nsimulators stand out and demonstrate behaviors that diverge from the rest. These include `UserLM-8b`,\nwhich has the highest mean pairwise JS score of 0 _._ 41, followed by `GPT-5.4 mini` with a score of\n0 _._ 33. Pairwise JS scores are consistently higher for writing than coding, which aligns with our main\nresults, where the divergences from real users were also higher for writing.\n\n\n**7.2** **Can we Combine User Simulators to Reduce the Gap With Real Users?**\n\n\nSince our pairwise analysis shows that some user simulators behave distinctly from each other, we\ntest whether combining pairs can reduce the gap to real users by randomly sampling which simulator\ngenerates each conversation. Table 3 reports the results.'], '2605.07847v1_chunk_14': ['**User Behavior Descriptions.** We use an LLM to generate\nuser behavior descriptions for each conversation to isolate user\nbehavioral patterns and abstract away irrelevant surface-level\nfeatures from the raw conversation history. To validate that\nthis step is necessary, we compare against two simpler rep\nFigure 2: Scatter plot of classifica\nresentations: the raw conversations and user utterances only.\n\ntion accuracy and Jensen–Shannon\n\nTable 10 (Appendix G) reports the full results for all simulators\n\nDivergence (JS) for all simulators\n\nacross both tasks. These simpler representations produce low\n\nacross coding and writing tasks.\n\ndivergences across all simulators, which would suggest that\n\nEach point represents one simulator\n\nsimulators closely match real users. However, this similarity is on one task.\nan artifact of surface-level features such as lexical and semantic\noverlap, rather than reflecting behavioral patterns. Our behavioral descriptions, by contrast, reveal\nmuch larger and more meaningful gaps, confirming that this step is necessary.\n\n\n**Embedding Models.** User behavior descriptions are embedded using `Qwen3-Embedding-8B` . To\nverify that our results are robust across embedding models, we repeat our experiments using two\nother embedding models: `e5-large-v2` [57] and `BGE-small-en-v1.5` [60]. We apply z-score\nnormalization to metric values within each dataset and then compute the Spearman rank correlation\nbetween simulator rankings produced by each pair of embedding models. Table 2 report the results,\nand Figure 15 (Appendix G) provide scatter plot visualizations. Simulator rankings are largely\npreserved across different embedding models.'], '2605.07847v1_chunk_0': ['\n**Shuhaib Mehri** _[♠]_ **Philippe Laban** _[♢]_ **Sumuk Shashidhar** _[♠]_ **Marwa Abdulhai** [⋆]\n\n**Sergey Levine** [⋆] **Michel Galley** _[♢]_ **Dilek Hakkani-Tür** _[♠]_\n\n_♠_ University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign _♢_ Microsoft Research\n⋆University of California, Berkeley\n\n'], '2605.07847v1_chunk_3': ['![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_2)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n||||\n|---|---|---|\n|Qu|a|ntiz|\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_3)\n\nFigure 1: Our method extracts representations of user behavior from real and simulated conversations, then quantizes them via _k_ -means to get discrete behavioral distributions for real ( _P_ [ˆ] ) and\nsimulated users ( _Q_ [ˆ] ). UMAP projections [30] and first principal component histograms illustrate the\ndistributional gap for two simulators on the coding task: `Gemini 3.1 Pro` overlaps real users more\nclosely compared to `Llama-3.1-8B-Instruct` .\n\n\nPreprint.\n\n\n**1** **Introduction**\n\n\nThe role of user simulators is to model the diverse behaviors of real users, providing a scalable\nmeans to train and evaluate AI systems on the interactions that they encounter in real-world settings\n\n[26, 14, 39, 45]. Recent works build user simulators by training Large Language Models (LLMs)\nto generate responses that resemble those of real users [33, 16, 58]. Yet real users exhibit a broad,\nheterogeneous distribution of behaviors [65, 66, 28]. For example, some users tend to underspecify\ntheir requests, while others fully specify every constraint. The extent to which user simulators capture\nthis distribution has not been measured.\n\n\nA user simulator can fail to capture the distribution of real users in two ways: by demonstrating\nbehaviors that real users rarely exhibit (low prec **i** son), or by failing to demonstrate behaviors that real\nusers do exhibit (low reca **l** ), mirroring precision and recall metrics for generative models [ 46, 23, 11].\nThese failure modes bias training and evaluation, and yield assistants that struggle to generalize to\nthe diverse behaviors of real users [52].'], '2605.07847v1_chunk_4': ['We introduce a method to compare the distributions of user behaviors in real and simulated conversations, illustrated in Figure 1. For each conversation, we extract a representation of the user’s\nbehavior by using an LLM to generate a description along six behavioral facets (such as how they\nmake requests or what dialog acts they perform) and then embedding it into a shared semantic space.\nNext, we quantize these representations into discrete distributions over user behavior modes by\nclustering [46, 41]. Finally, we measure the gap between the real and simulated distributions using\ndivergence-based metrics. We confirm that our method captures meaningful behavioral distributions\nand is robust to the choice of embedding model and clustering algorithm through a human study and\nvalidation studies.\n\n\nWe provide the first systematic evaluation of 24 LLM-based user simulators across coding and writing\ntasks, including 7 closed-source LLMs, 15 open-source LLMs, and 2 trained simulators. Our results\nreveal a large distributional gap from real users, and surface insights across model families, scales, and\nbehavioral facets. Pairwise comparisons between simulators show that most behave similarly, while a\nfew stand apart. Combining behaviorally complementary simulators brings the resulting distribution\ncloser to real users than either simulator on its own. Lastly, a TF-IDF analysis of the clusters provides\ninterpretable insights into behaviors that user simulators capture, miss, and hallucinate.'], '2605.07847v1_chunk_1': ['```\n             mehri2@illinois.edu\n\n```\n'], '2605.07847v1_chunk_16': ['**6.3** **Linear Classification**\n\n\nWe validate that our user behavior representation embeddings encode meaningful differences between\nreal and simulated users by training a linear classifier. For each simulator, we construct a dataset\nof 5,000 real and 5,000 simulated embeddings, and then train an L2-regularized logistic regression\nclassifier to classify embeddings as real or simulated. We average results over 5 stratified random\n80/20 train-test splits. The classification accuracies across simulators are consistently high, ranging\nfrom 90.92% to 99.63%, and also correlate strongly with our distributional metrics (Figure 2). This\nconfirms that the embeddings encode meaningful differences between real and simulated users. The\nfull accuracy scores and correlations for all metrics are presented in Appendix H.\n\n\n**7** **Discussion**\n\n\n**7.1** **How Do User Behavior Distributions Compare Among Simulators?**\n\n\nOur main results show that the distributional gap to real users varies across simulators. This raises a\nnatural question: how do the behviorl d **a** rbuon of user **ist** imulator compare to each other? **s** To\ninvestigate this, we pool the user behavior representations across all 24 simulators, quantize them\ninto distributions, and compute the JS divergence between all pairs. Figure 3 reports the results.\n\n\nMany simulators behave similarly to each other: 30% of the 552 pairwise comparisons have JS _<_\n0 _._ 10. Pairs from the same family tend to be the most similar, achieving the lowest scores in the\ndataset. The simulators with the lowest mean pairwise JS scores are `Qwen3.5-122B-A10B` (0 _._ 14),\n\n\n7'], '2605.07847v1_chunk_5': ['Our work advances toward user simulators that faithfully represent the diversity of real users with the\nfollowing contributions: (1) We introduce a method for measuring the distributional gap between\nreal and simulated user behaviors, validated through a human study and ablations; (2) Our analysis\nof 7 closed-source LLMs, 15 open-source LLMs and 2 trained simulators on coding and writing\ntasks reveals a large distributional gap from real users that varies across model families, scales, and\nbehavioral facets; (3) We show that combining behaviorally complementary simulators brings the\nresulting distribution closer to real users than either simulator on its own; (4) We present a TF-IDF\nanalysis of behavior clusters that surfaces interpretable insights into behaviors that simulators capture,\nmiss, and hallucinate.\n\n\n**2** **Problem Formulation**\n\n\nIn this section, we formalize the problem of evaluating how well a user simulator captures the\ndistribution of real user behaviors. Let _P_ denote the distribution of real user behaviors, and _Q_ denote\nthe distribution of simulated user behaviors. Our objective is to measure the gap between _P_ and _Q_ .\n\n\nIn practice, _P_ and _Q_ are not directly observable. Instead, we access them through datasets of\nconversations, where each conversation is a sequence C n = ( _u_ 1 _, a_ 1 _, . . ., u_ n _, a_ n ), with _u_ i and _a_\ndenoting the user and assistant utterances at turn _i_ . We use D real [, a dataset of real user-assistant]\nconversations, as samples from _P_ .'], '2605.07847v1_chunk_2': ['**Code** : `[https://github.com/shuhaibm/UserBehavioralDivergence](https://github.com/shuhaibm/UserBehavioralDivergence)`\n\n\n**Abstract**\n\n\nAs user simulators are increasingly used for interactive training and evaluation\nof AI assistants, it is essential that they represent the diverse behaviors of real\nusers. While existing works train user simulators to generate human-like responses,\nwhether they capture the broad and heterogeneous distribution of real user behaviors\nremains an open question. In this work, we introduce a method to measure the\ndistributional gap between real and simulated user behaviors, validated through a\nhuman study and ablations. Given a dataset of real and simulated conversations, our\nmethod extracts representations of user behavior from each conversation, quantizes\nthem into discrete distributions via clustering, then computes divergence metrics.\nWe provide the first systematic evaluation of 24 LLM-based user simulators on\ncoding and writing tasks, and reveal a large distributional gap from real users that\nvaries across model families, scales, and behavioral facets. Pairwise comparisons\nshow that most simulators behave similarly, while a few stand apart. Combining\nbehaviorally complementary simulators brings the resulting distribution closer to\nreal users compared to either simulator on its own. Finally, a TF-IDF analysis of\nthe clusters surfaces interpretable patterns of behaviors that simulators capture,\nmiss, and hallucinate.\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_1)\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_2)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n||||\n|---|---|---|\n|Qu|a|ntiz|\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_3)'], '2605.07847v1_chunk_15': ['**Clustering Algorithms.** We obtain discrete distributions of user behavior by clustering our embeddings using _k_ -means with _k_ = 500. To verify that our method is robust to the clustering algorithm,\nwe repeat our experiments using Gaussian Mixture Models and Agglomerative Clustering. Similar\nto the embedding model ablation, we compute the Spearman rank correlations between simulator\nrankings produced by each pair of clustering algorithms. Our results in Table 2 demonstrate that\nsimulator rankings are nearly identical across all pairs ( _ρ_ � 0 _._ 96 ), and scatter plot visualizations are\nprovided in Figure 15 (Appendix G).\n\n\n6\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_6)\n\n�\n\n\n**-en** 3Emb **d** Qwig8B **-l** sma\n\n**-en** 3Emb **d** Qwig8B **-e** 5\n\n**-l** BGEsmaenv1.5 **-e** 5\n\n\nK-Means **a** u **s**\n\nK-Means lom **eg**\n\nG **a** u **s** lom **eg**\n\n\n�\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_7)\n\n**a** **ist** **s**\n\n\n\nFigure 3: Pairwise Jensen–Shannon divergence between the behavior distributions of 24 user simulators across coding (lower triangle) and writing tasks (upper triangle), ordered by descending mean\npairwise JS divergence. Many simulators demonstrate similar behavioral distributions (lighter cells)\nwhile a few stand out (darker cells).\n\n\n**6.3** **Linear Classification**']}}}",,39.05579399141631,0.9014084507042254,0.03567447045707915,256.2857142857143,0.0,False,0.0,1.0,0.8666666666666667,0,0.0,0.05194805194805195,0.09090909090909091,0.5047701597213745,0.6657981872558594,0.5742083787918091,-0.0251223873347044,0.30802950263023376,0.12204441428184509,4.0,True,"The candidate answer accurately describes the distributional gap between real and simulated user behaviors in paper 2605.07847v1, citing relevant results from the paper. However, it does not fully capture the nuances of the comparison between simulators, specifically the observation that simulators from the same family are more similar to each other than to real users.",80.0,5.0,4.0,4.0,1.0,5.0
