preserved across different embedding models.","[{'id': 'retrieved-1', 'title': 'GraphRAG Candidate', 'snippet': 'Paper 2605.07847v1 represents and compares user behaviors by first concatenating descriptions across six behavioral facets into a single textual representation, then embedding these representations in a shared semantic space using a text embedding model. This process abstracts away surface-level signals to focus on behavioral patterns. Next, the paper quantizes the continuous vector representations of user behavior into low-dimensional discrete distributions through _k_-means clustering. These distributions capture how frequently different modes of user behavior occur in real and simulated conversations, allowing for meaningful comparisons between them.', 'score': 95.0, 'metadata': {'candidate_answer': 'Paper 2605.07847v1 represents and compares user behaviors by first concatenating descriptions across six behavioral facets into a single textual representation, then embedding these representations in a shared semantic space using a text embedding model. This process abstracts away surface-level signals to focus on behavioral patterns. Next, the paper quantizes the continuous vector representations of user behavior into low-dimensional discrete distributions through _k_-means clustering. These distributions capture how frequently different modes of user behavior occur in real and simulated conversations, allowing for meaningful comparisons between them.', 'score': 95}}, {'id': 'retrieved-2', 'title': 'GraphRAG Candidate', 'snippet': ""Paper 2605.07847v1 represents and compares user behaviors by evaluating the distributional gap between real and simulated user behaviors across coding and writing tasks. The comparison is made using various metrics such as KL divergence, forward KL, backward KL, MAU (mean absolute utility), JS (Jensen-Shannon) distance, etc., with 'Real U' indicating the actual user behavior and '[ D] sim' representing the simulated user behavior. Higher values in certain metrics indicate better performance of the real users compared to the simulations."", 'score': 95.0, 'metadata': {'candidate_answer': ""Paper 2605.07847v1 represents and compares user behaviors by evaluating the distributional gap between real and simulated user behaviors across coding and writing tasks. The comparison is made using various metrics such as KL divergence, forward KL, backward KL, MAU (mean absolute utility), JS (Jensen-Shannon) distance, etc., with 'Real U' indicating the actual user behavior and '[ D] sim' representing the simulated user behavior. Higher values in certain metrics indicate better performance of the real users compared to the simulations."", 'score': 95}}, {'id': 'retrieved-3', 'title': 'GraphRAG Candidate', 'snippet': ""Paper 2605.07847v1 represents and compares user behaviors through the use of embedding models and clustering algorithms, specifically k-means clustering. The study validates these representations using a 'odd-one-out' task where annotators are shown three behavior descriptions—two from the same cluster and one from a different cluster—and asked to identify which does not belong. Annotators correctly identified the odd-one-out 86.7% of the time on average, with high inter-annotator agreement (Fleiss’ κ = 0.74). This confirms that clusters capture meaningful behavioral similarity."", 'score': 95.0, 'metadata': {'candidate_answer': ""Paper 2605.07847v1 represents and compares user behaviors through the use of embedding models and clustering algorithms, specifically k-means clustering. The study validates these representations using a 'odd-one-out' task where annotators are shown three behavior descriptions—two from the same cluster and one from a different cluster—and asked to identify which does not belong. Annotators correctly identified the odd-one-out 86.7% of the time on average, with high inter-annotator agreement (Fleiss’ κ = 0.74). This confirms that clusters capture meaningful behavioral similarity."", 'score': 95}}, {'id': 'retrieved-4', 'title': 'GraphRAG Candidate', 'snippet': 'Paper 2605.07847v1 represents and compares user behaviors by generating user behavior representations for each conversation and quantizing them into discrete distributions using k-means clustering. This process allows conversations with similar user behaviors to be grouped together, providing a way to analyze and compare different patterns of user interactions. The paper also highlights that simulators approximate requests and context facets well but struggle with communication style, DAMSL, and SGD dialog acts, indicating areas where real users exhibit more diverse behavior than what can be captured by general-purpose language models.', 'score': 95.0, 'metadata': {'candidate_answer': 'Paper 2605.07847v1 represents and compares user behaviors by generating user behavior representations for each conversation and quantizing them into discrete distributions using k-means clustering. This process allows conversations with similar user behaviors to be grouped together, providing a way to analyze and compare different patterns of user interactions. The paper also highlights that simulators approximate requests and context facets well but struggle with communication style, DAMSL, and SGD dialog acts, indicating areas where real users exhibit more diverse behavior than what can be captured by general-purpose language models.', 'score': 95}}, {'id': 'retrieved-5', 'title': 'GraphRAG Candidate', 'snippet': 'Paper 2605.07847v1 represents and compares user behaviors by extracting a description of the user’s behavior along six facets from each conversation in both real and simulated datasets: Requests, Responses, Context, Communication Style, DAMSL Dialog Acts, and SGD Dialog Acts. These facets capture both conversation-level and utterance-level behaviors, allowing for detailed comparison between actual user interactions and those generated by the simulator.', 'score': 95.0, 'metadata': {'candidate_answer': 'Paper 2605.07847v1 represents and compares user behaviors by extracting a description of the user’s behavior along six facets from each conversation in both real and simulated datasets: Requests, Responses, Context, Communication Style, DAMSL Dialog Acts, and SGD Dialog Acts. These facets capture both conversation-level and utterance-level behaviors, allowing for detailed comparison between actual user interactions and those generated by the simulator.', 'score': 95}}, {'id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_7', 'title': '2605.07847v1_chunk_7', 'snippet': '- **Responses:** How users respond to the assistant. We consider their engagement levels [65, 66],\nhow they evaluate assistant outputs [50], the type of feedback they provide [51], and whether they\nintroduce new constraints or preferences across turns [32, 27].\n\n - **Context:** How users provide background information. We consider the type of context they\nprovide (e.g., domain knowledge, prior attempts, thought processes, personal background) [54],\nhow directly it relates to the user goal [31], whether context is front-loaded or revealed gradually\nacross turns [8], and whether it is volunteered proactively or elicited by the assistant [21, 59].\n\n - **Communication Style:** How users communicate stylistically. We consider their register and\nemotional tone, verbosity, message formatting (e.g., bullet points, markdown, prose), and social\nconventions such as politeness and pleasantries [39, 67, 33, 20, 67].\n\n - **DAMSL Dialog Acts:** Per-utterance analysis using the Dialog Act Markup in Several Layers\n(DAMSL) framework. It characterizes utterances across three aspects: information level (the\nsemantic content of the utterance), forward-looking function (its effect on subsequent dialog), and\nbackward-looking function (relation to prior discourse) [3].\n\n - **SGD Dialog Acts:** Per-utterance classification into one or more discrete dialog act labels adapted\nfrom the Schema-Guided Dialogue (SGD) dataset, such as inform, request, and affirm [44, 61].\n\n\nThese behavioral facets abstract away irrelevant features, enabling our comparisons to focus on\nbehavioral patterns rather than surface-level signals such as lexical similarity. The full prompts and\ncriteria are provided in Appendix B.', 'score': None, 'metadata': {'vertex_id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_7', 'snippets': ['- **Responses:** How users respond to the assistant. We consider their engagement levels [65, 66],\nhow they evaluate assistant outputs [50], the type of feedback they provide [51], and whether they\nintroduce new constraints or preferences across turns [32, 27].\n\n - **Context:** How users provide background information. We consider the type of context they\nprovide (e.g., domain knowledge, prior attempts, thought processes, personal background) [54],\nhow directly it relates to the user goal [31], whether context is front-loaded or revealed gradually\nacross turns [8], and whether it is volunteered proactively or elicited by the assistant [21, 59].\n\n - **Communication Style:** How users communicate stylistically. We consider their register and\nemotional tone, verbosity, message formatting (e.g., bullet points, markdown, prose), and social\nconventions such as politeness and pleasantries [39, 67, 33, 20, 67].\n\n - **DAMSL Dialog Acts:** Per-utterance analysis using the Dialog Act Markup in Several Layers\n(DAMSL) framework. It characterizes utterances across three aspects: information level (the\nsemantic content of the utterance), forward-looking function (its effect on subsequent dialog), and\nbackward-looking function (relation to prior discourse) [3].\n\n - **SGD Dialog Acts:** Per-utterance classification into one or more discrete dialog act labels adapted\nfrom the Schema-Guided Dialogue (SGD) dataset, such as inform, request, and affirm [44, 61].\n\n\nThese behavioral facets abstract away irrelevant features, enabling our comparisons to focus on\nbehavioral patterns rather than surface-level signals such as lexical similarity. The full prompts and\ncriteria are provided in Appendix B.']}}, {'id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_44', 'title': '2605.07847v1_chunk_44', 'snippet': '[57] and `BGE-small-en-v1.5` (BGE) [60]. (b) compares three clustering algorithms: _k_ -means\n(KM), Gaussian Mixture Models (GMM) and Agglomerative Clustering (Agg) ( _k_ =500).\n\n\n29\n\n\nTable 10: Ablation experiments for user behavior representation: the distributional gap between real\nand simulated user behaviors across coding and writing tasks when using the raw conversations,\nusser utterances only, and our behavioral descriptions. We report nearest neighbor cosine similarity\n(NN), forward KL divergence (KL ), backward KL divergence (KL bwd ), MAUVE (MAU), and\nJensen–Shannon divergence (JS). "" indicates higher is better and # indicates lower is better.\n\n\n**Coding** **Writing**\n\n\n**User Simulator** **Representation** **N** "" bwd ""MAU #JS **N** "" bwd ""MAU #JS\n\n\nd-SurcCl **o** s **e**\n\n\nRaw Conversation 0.742 0.056 0.060 0.862 0.054 0.737 0.300 0.305 0.165 0.282\n\nRaw User Utterances 0.721 0.071 0.077 0.798 0.070 0.724 0.267 0.277 0.219 0.249\n\nBehavioral Descriptions 0.872 0.261 0.265 0.223 0.248 0.900 0.482 0.489 0.030 0.479\n\n\nGPT-5.4 m **i** Raw Conversation 0.744 0.067 0.075 0.833 0.062 0.733 0.293 0.311 0.156 0.289\n\nRaw User Utterances 0.725 0.097 0.101 0.714 0.090 0.724 0.277 0.303 0.199 0.259\n\nBehavioral Descriptions 0.864 0.363 0.388 0.082 0.364 0.897 0.513 0.533 0.020 0.520\n\n\nGPT-5.4 **n** Raw Conversation 0.727 0.074 0.081 0.778 0.074 0.714 0.360 0.395 0.085 0.359\n\nRaw User Utterances 0.715 0.079 0.082 0.772 0.076 0.708 0.296 0.319 0.159 0.287\n\nBehavioral Descriptions 0.860 0.353 0.364 0.091 0.353 0.896 0.520 0.531 0.018 0.532\n\n\nClaude Haiku 4.5 Raw Conversation 0.733 0.044 0.041 0.910 0.042 0.712 0.357 0.371 0.096 0.345\n\nRaw User Utterances 0.709 0.072 0.072 0.793 0.071 0.698 0.353 0.372 0.105 0.335\n\nBehavioral 