` 0.820 0.433 0.410 0.049 0.424 0.847 0.566 0.581 0.011 0.588\n\n\nTrained Simulators']}}, {'id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_32', 'title': '2605.07847v1_chunk_32', 'snippet': '**n** . Learig\n\n\n14\n\n\n**A** **Limitations and Future Directions**\n\n\nWe make an effort to approximate the distribution of real user behaviors by grounding our evaluation\nin 10,000 real-world conversations between users and assistants across coding and writing tasks.\nHowever, there are some limitations to how well this references reflects user behaviors in the real\nworld. The conversations are drawn from a single source, WildChat [65], which was collected\nthrough a public chatbot interface hosted on Hugging Face Spaces. This likely skews the user\npopulation toward the IT/developer community and may not adequately represent other populations\nwho interact with LLMs in different settings. The evaluation also focuses on English conversations,\nwhich potentially underrepresents the linguistic, cultural, and regional diversity of user interactions\nwith LLMs across the world. Moreover, our analysis does not extend to tasks other than coding or\nwriting, where user behaviors may differ.\n\n\nOur method measures the distributional gap between real and simulated user behaviors by comparing\nthe behaviors demonstrated in real and simulated conversations. One limitation of our approach\nis that real conversations had ChatGPT/GPT-4 as the assistants, while our simulated conversations\nwere generated using Qwen3.5-122B-A10B as the assistant. The way that users behave is partly\nshaped by the assistant, so the measured gap may be affected by differences assistant behavior.\nAdditionally, simulated conversations were generated based on user goals that were extracted from\nreal conversations using GPT-4o. The user goal extraction process can be lossy, stripping context\nthe original user had. If user simulators were provided with this context, such as personas or prior\nexperience, it may help address the gap and enable them to more faithfully represent user behaviors.', 'score': None, 'metadata': {'vertex_id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_32', 'snippets': ['**n** . Learig\n\n\n14\n\n\n**A** **Limitations and Future Directions**\n\n\nWe make an effort to approximate the distribution of real user behaviors by grounding our evaluation\nin 10,000 real-world conversations between users and assistants across coding and writing tasks.\nHowever, there are some limitations to how well this references reflects user behaviors in the real\nworld. The conversations are drawn from a single source, WildChat [65], which was collected\nthrough a public chatbot interface hosted on Hugging Face Spaces. This likely skews the user\npopulation toward the IT/developer community and may not adequately represent other populations\nwho interact with LLMs in different settings. The evaluation also focuses on English conversations,\nwhich potentially underrepresents the linguistic, cultural, and regional diversity of user interactions\nwith LLMs across the world. Moreover, our analysis does not extend to tasks other than coding or\nwriting, where user behaviors may differ.\n\n\nOur method measures the distributional gap between real and simulated user behaviors by comparing\nthe behaviors demonstrated in real and simulated conversations. One limitation of our approach\nis that real conversations had ChatGPT/GPT-4 as the assistants, while our simulated conversations\nwere generated using Qwen3.5-122B-A10B as the assistant. The way that users behave is partly\nshaped by the assistant, so the measured gap may be affected by differences assistant behavior.\nAdditionally, simulated conversations were generated based on user goals that were extracted from\nreal conversations using GPT-4o. The user goal extraction process can be lossy, stripping context\nthe original user had. If user simulators were provided with this context, such as personas or prior\nexperience, it may help address the gap and enable them to more faithfully represent user behaviors.']}}, {'id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_6', 'title': '2605.07847v1_chunk_6', 'snippet': 'To sample from _Q_, we use an LLM to extract the user goal G (a description of the user’s overall objective) from each conversation in D real [and provide it to the user simulator. The simulator]\ngenerates utterances _u_ i conditioned on G and the conversation history C i _−_ 1, and a fixed assistant\ngenerates utterances _a_ i conditioned on the conversation history C i _−_ and _u_ i . Conversations terminate upon reaching a maximum length or when the simulator emits a termination signal (e.g.,\n`<|TERMINATE_CONVERSATION|>` ). The resulting conversations yield D sim [, our samples from] _[ Q]_ [.]\n\n\n2\n\n\nMeasuring the distributional gap between _P_ and _Q_ now reduces to comparing the user behaviors\nobserved in D real [with those generated by the user simulator in] [ D] sim [.]\n\n\n**3** **Method**\n\n\nWe present a three-stage method for measuring the distributional gap between the user behaviors in\nreal [and] [ D] sim [, illustrated in Figure 1: (1) Generating User Behavior Representations, (2) Quantizing]\ninto Behavioral Distributions, and (3) Measuring the Distributional Gap.\n\n\n**Step 1: Generating User Behavior Representations**\n\n\nThe first step is to extract a representation of the user’s behavior from each conversation in D real\nand D sim [. To do so, we first prompt an LLM to generate a description of the user’s behavior along]\nsix facets, grounded in established frameworks for analyzing user behavior [54, 3, 61, 19, 39]. The\nfirst four facets (Requests, Responses, Context, Communication Style) capture conversation-level\nbehaviors, while the last two (DAMSL and SGD Dialog Acts) capture utterance-level behaviors\nthrough dialog act annotation frameworks:\n\n\n - **Requests:** What types of requests users make to the assistant and how. We consider how explicit\nand specified each request is [54, 38, 4, 62], how the user goal is decomposed across turns [18, 19],\nand whether requests serve the primary goal or secondary functions [31].', 'score': None, 'metadata': {'vertex_id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_6', 'snippets': ['To sample from _Q_, we use an LLM to extract the user goal G (a description of the user’s overall objective) from each conversation in D real [and provide it to the user simulator. The simulator]\ngenerates utterances _u_ i conditioned on G and the conversation history C i _−_ 1, and a fixed assistant\ngenerates utterances _a_ i conditioned on the conversation history C i _−_ and _u_ i . Conversations terminate upon reaching a maximum length or when the simulator emits a termination signal (e.g.,\n`<|TERMINATE_CONVERSATION|>` ). The resulting conversations yield D sim [, our samples from] _[ Q]_ [.]\n\n\n2\n\n\nMeasuring the distributional gap between _P_ and _Q_ now reduces to comparing the user behaviors\nobserved in D real [with those generated by the user simulator in] [ D] sim [.]\n\n\n**3** **Method**\n\n\nWe present a three-stage method for measuring the distributional gap between the user behaviors in\nreal [and] [ D] sim [, illustrated in Figure 1: (1) Generating User Behavior Representations, (2) Quantizing]\ninto Behavioral Distributions, and (3) Measuring the Distributional Gap.\n\n\n**Step 1: Generating User Behavior Representations**\n\n\nThe first step is to extract a representation of the user’s behavior from each conversation in D real\nand D sim [. To do so, we first prompt an LLM to generate a description of the user’s behavior along]\nsix facets, grounded in established frameworks for analyzing user behavior [54, 3, 61, 19, 39]. The\nfirst four facets (Requests, Responses, Context, Communication Style) capture conversation-level\nbehaviors, while the last two (DAMSL and SGD Dialog Acts) capture utterance-level behaviors\nthrough dialog act annotation frameworks:\n\n\n - **Requests:** What types of requests users make to the assistant and how. We consider how explicit\nand specified each request is [54, 38, 4, 62], how the user goal is decomposed across turns [18, 19],\nand whether requests serve the primary goal or secondary functions [31].']}}, {'id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_43', 'title': '2605.07847v1_chunk_43', 'snippet': '`Llama-3.1-8B-Instruct` 0.918 0.958 0.597 0.006 0.657 0.905 0.799 0.606 0.005 0.672\n`gpt-oss-120b` 0.954 0.939 0.596 0.008 0.621 0.960 0.775 0.597 0.006 0.653\n`gpt-oss-20b` 0.942 0.960 0.605 0.006 0.655 0.971 0.807 0.597 0.005 0.665\n`gemma-4-31B-it` 0.893 0.989 0.632 0.005 0.670 0.887 0.831 0.607 0.005 0.680\n`gemma-4-26B-A4B-it` 0.923 0.957 0.608 0.006 0.658 0.898 0.828 0.604 0.005 0.676\n`gemma-4-E4B-it` 0.939 0.946 0.589 0.007 0.635 0.956 0.816 0.593 0.006 0.659\n`gemma-4-E2B-it` 0.921 0.965 0.614 0.006 0.658 0.932 0.796 0.602 0.005 0.671\n\n\nTrained Simulators\n\n\n`UserLM-8b` 0.986 0.802 0.517 0.023 0.505 0.992 0.504 0.430 0.037 0.454\n`humanlm-opinion` 0.964 0.905 0.595 0.011 0.591 0.987 0.648 0.525 0.015 0.554\n\n\n27\n\n\n**F** **Human Study Details**\n\n\n15 annotators were recruited for the human study. The annotators were graduate-level computer\nscience students with a background in natural language processing, recruiting through the university\nas volunteers. A screenshot of the instructions given to annotators is provided in Figure 14.\n\n\nFigure 14: Instructions provided to human annotators for the ""Odd-One-Out"" human study.\n\n\n28\n\n\n**G** **Ablation Results**\n\n\nFigure 15: Scatter plot visualization of Spearman rank correlation ( _ρ_ ) of simulator rankings across\ndifferent embedding models and clustering algorithms. Each point represents a simulator, with axes\nshowing its z-score normalized metric values under two variants. Points near the diagonal and high\n_ρ_ values indicate that the relative ordering of simulators is preserved across variants. each dataset.\n(a) compares three embedding models: `Qwen3-Embedding-8B` (Qwen3) [64], texttte5-large-v2 (E5)\