58 0.467 0.030 0.476 0.866 0.445 0.454 0.038 0.452\n`Llama-3.3-70B-Instruct` 0.839 0.402 0.385 0.068 0.386 0.858 0.498 0.510 0.023 0.506']}}, {'id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_14', 'title': '2605.07847v1_chunk_14', 'snippet': '**User Behavior Descriptions.** We use an LLM to generate\nuser behavior descriptions for each conversation to isolate user\nbehavioral patterns and abstract away irrelevant surface-level\nfeatures from the raw conversation history. To validate that\nthis step is necessary, we compare against two simpler rep\nFigure 2: Scatter plot of classifica\nresentations: the raw conversations and user utterances only.\n\ntion accuracy and Jensen–Shannon\n\nTable 10 (Appendix G) reports the full results for all simulators\n\nDivergence (JS) for all simulators\n\nacross both tasks. These simpler representations produce low\n\nacross coding and writing tasks.\n\ndivergences across all simulators, which would suggest that\n\nEach point represents one simulator\n\nsimulators closely match real users. However, this similarity is on one task.\nan artifact of surface-level features such as lexical and semantic\noverlap, rather than reflecting behavioral patterns. Our behavioral descriptions, by contrast, reveal\nmuch larger and more meaningful gaps, confirming that this step is necessary.\n\n\n**Embedding Models.** User behavior descriptions are embedded using `Qwen3-Embedding-8B` . To\nverify that our results are robust across embedding models, we repeat our experiments using two\nother embedding models: `e5-large-v2` [57] and `BGE-small-en-v1.5` [60]. We apply z-score\nnormalization to metric values within each dataset and then compute the Spearman rank correlation\nbetween simulator rankings produced by each pair of embedding models. Table 2 report the results,\nand Figure 15 (Appendix G) provide scatter plot visualizations. Simulator rankings are largely\npreserved across different embedding models.', 'score': None, 'metadata': {'vertex_id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_14', 'snippets': ['**User Behavior Descriptions.** We use an LLM to generate\nuser behavior descriptions for each conversation to isolate user\nbehavioral patterns and abstract away irrelevant surface-level\nfeatures from the raw conversation history. To validate that\nthis step is necessary, we compare against two simpler rep\nFigure 2: Scatter plot of classifica\nresentations: the raw conversations and user utterances only.\n\ntion accuracy and Jensen–Shannon\n\nTable 10 (Appendix G) reports the full results for all simulators\n\nDivergence (JS) for all simulators\n\nacross both tasks. These simpler representations produce low\n\nacross coding and writing tasks.\n\ndivergences across all simulators, which would suggest that\n\nEach point represents one simulator\n\nsimulators closely match real users. However, this similarity is on one task.\nan artifact of surface-level features such as lexical and semantic\noverlap, rather than reflecting behavioral patterns. Our behavioral descriptions, by contrast, reveal\nmuch larger and more meaningful gaps, confirming that this step is necessary.\n\n\n**Embedding Models.** User behavior descriptions are embedded using `Qwen3-Embedding-8B` . To\nverify that our results are robust across embedding models, we repeat our experiments using two\nother embedding models: `e5-large-v2` [57] and `BGE-small-en-v1.5` [60]. We apply z-score\nnormalization to metric values within each dataset and then compute the Spearman rank correlation\nbetween simulator rankings produced by each pair of embedding models. Table 2 report the results,\nand Figure 15 (Appendix G) provide scatter plot visualizations. Simulator rankings are largely\npreserved across different embedding models.']}}]","['GraphRAG Candidate', 'GraphRAG Candidate', 'GraphRAG Candidate', 'GraphRAG Candidate', 'GraphRAG Candidate', '2605.07847v1_chunk_7', '2605.07847v1_chunk_44', '2605.07847v1_chunk_8', '2605.07847v1_chunk_36', '2605.07847v1_chunk_30', '2605.07847v1_chunk_31', '2605.07847v1_chunk_42', '2605.07847v1_chunk_13', '2605.07847v1_chunk_12', '2605.07847v1_chunk_37', '2605.07847v1_chunk_32', '2605.07847v1_chunk_6', '2605.07847v1_chunk_43', '2605.07847v1_chunk_38', '2605.07847v1_chunk_14']",9,10790,155,164,111365.26507200005,0.07143299990275409,0.0,111365.33709399964,graph,20,0.0,"{'response': ""Paper 2605.07847v1 represents and compares user behaviors by first concatenating descriptions across six behavioral facets into a single textual representation, then embedding these representations in a shared semantic space using a text embedding model. This process abstracts away surface-level signals to focus on behavioral patterns. Next, the paper quantizes the continuous vector representations of user behavior into low-dimensional discrete distributions through _k_-means clustering. These distributions capture how frequently different modes of user behavior occur in real and simulated conversations, allowing for meaningful comparisons between them. Additionally, the study evaluates the distributional gap between real and simulated user behaviors across coding and writing tasks using various metrics such as KL divergence, forward KL, backward KL, MAU (mean absolute utility), JS (Jensen-Shannon) distance, etc., with 'Real U' indicating the actual user behavior and '[ D] sim' representing the simulated user behavior. Higher values in certain metrics indicate better performance of the real users compared to the simulations."", 'retrieved': [{'candidate_answer': 'Paper 2605.07847v1 represents and compares user behaviors by first concatenating descriptions across six behavioral facets into a single textual representation, then embedding these representations in a shared semantic space using a text embedding model. This process abstracts away surface-level signals to focus on behavioral patterns. Next, the paper quantizes the continuous vector representations of user behavior into low-dimensional discrete distributions through _k_-means clustering. These distributions capture how frequently different modes of user behavior occur in real and simulated conversations, allowing for meaningful comparisons between them.', 'score': 95}, {'candidate_answer': ""Paper 2605.07847v1 represents and compares user behaviors by evaluating the distributional gap between real and simulated user behaviors across coding and writing tasks. The comparison is made using various metrics such as KL divergence, forward KL, backward KL, MAU (mean absolute utility), JS (Jensen-Shannon) distance, etc., with 'Real U' indicating the actual user behavior and '[ D] sim' representing the simulated user behavior. Higher values in certain metrics indicate better performance of the real users compared to the simulations."", 'score': 95}, {'candidate_answer': ""Paper 2605.07847v1 represents and compares user behaviors through the use of embedding models and clustering algorithms, specifically k-means clustering. The study validates these representations using a 'odd-one-out' task where annotators are shown three behavior descriptions—two from the same cluster and one from a different cluster—and asked to identify which does not belong. Annotators correctly identified the odd-one-out 86.7% of the time on average, with high inter-annotator agreement (Fleiss’ κ = 0.74). This confirms that clusters capture meaningful behavioral similarity."", 'score': 95}, {'candidate_answer': 'Paper 2605.07847v1 represents and compares user behaviors by generating user behavior representations for each conversation and quantizing them into discrete distributions using k-means clustering. This process allows conversations with similar user behaviors to be grouped together, providing a way to analyze and compare different patterns of user interactions. The paper also highlights that simulators approximate requests and context facets well but struggle with communication style, DAMSL, and SGD dialog acts, indicating areas where real users exhibit more diverse behavior than what can be captured by general-purpose language models.', 'score': 95}, {'candidate_answer': 'Paper 2605.07847v1 represents and compares user behaviors by extracting a description of the user’s behavior along six facets from each conversation in both real and simulated datasets: Requests, Responses, Context, Communication Style, DAMSL Dialog Acts, and SGD Dialog Acts. These facets capture both conversation-level and utterance-level behaviors, allowing for detailed comparison between actual user interactions and those generated by the simulator.', 'score': 95}], 'verbose': {'selected_set': [{'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_14', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_43', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_36', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_7', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_6', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_8', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_37', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_31', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_38', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_32', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_30', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_44', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_42', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_12', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_13', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}], 'start_set': [{'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_32', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_38', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_14', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_44', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_8', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}], 'final_retrieval': {'2605.07847v1_chunk_7': ['- **Responses:** How users respond to the assistant. We consider their engagement levels [65, 66],\nhow they evaluate assistant outputs [50], the type of feedback they provide [51], and whether they\nintroduce new constraints or preferences across turns [32, 27].\n\n - **Context:** How users provide background information. We consider the type of context they\nprovide (e.g., domain knowledge, prior attempts, thought processes, personal background) [54],\nhow directly it relates to the user goal [31], whether context is front-loaded or revealed gradually\nacross turns [8], and whether it is volunteered proactively or elicited by the assistant [21, 59].\n\n - **Communication Style:** How users communicate stylistically. We consider their register and\nemotional tone, verbosity, message formatting (e.g., bullet points, markdown, prose), and social\nconventions such as politeness and pleasantries [39, 67, 33, 20, 67].\n\n - **DAMSL Dialog Acts:** Per-utterance analysis using the Dialog Act Markup in Several Layers\n(DAMSL) framework. It characterizes utterances across three aspects: information level (the\nsemantic content of the utterance), forward-looking function (its effect on subsequent dialog), and\nbackward-looking function (relation to prior discourse) [3].\n\n - **SGD Dialog Acts:** Per-utterance classification into one or more discrete dialog act labels adapted\nfrom the Schema-Guided Dialogue (SGD) dataset, such as inform, request, and affirm [44, 61].\n\n\nThese behavioral facets abstract away irrelevant features, enabling our comparisons to focus on\nbehavioral patterns rather than surface-level signals such as lexical similarity. The full prompts and\ncriteria are provided in Appendix B.'], '2605.07847v1_chunk_44': ['[57] and `BGE-small-en-v1.5` (BGE) [60]. (b) compares three clustering algorithms: _k_ -means\n(KM), Gaussian Mixture Models (GMM) and Agglomerative Clustering (Agg) ( _k_ =500).\n\n\n29\n\n\nTable 10: Ablation experiments for user behavior representation: the distributional gap between real\nand simulated user behaviors across coding and writing tasks when using the raw conversations,\nusser utterances only, and our behavioral descriptions. We report nearest neighbor cosine similarity\n(NN), forward KL divergence (KL ), backward KL divergence (KL bwd ), MAUVE (MAU), and\nJensen–Shannon divergence (JS). "" indicates higher is better and # indicates lower is better.\n\n\n**Coding** **Writing**\n\n\n**User Simulator** **Representation** **N** "" bwd ""MAU #JS **N** "" bwd ""MAU #JS\n\n\nd-SurcCl **o** s **e**\n\n\nRaw Conversation 0.742 0.056 0.060 0.862 0.054 0.737 0.300 0.305 0.165 0.282\n\nRaw User Utterances 0.721 0.071 0.077 0.798 0.070 0.724 0.267 0.277 0.219 0.249\n\nBehavioral Descriptions 0.872 0.261 0.265 0.223 0.248 0.900 0.482 0.489 0.030 0.479\n\n\nGPT-5.4 m **i** Raw Conversation 0.744 0.067 0.075 0.833 0.062 0.733 0.293 0.311 0.156 0.289\n\nRaw User Utterances 0.725 0.097 0.101 0.714 0.090 0.724 0.277 0.303 0.199 0.259\n\nBehavioral Descriptions 0.864 0.363 0.388 0.082 0.364 0.897 0.513 0.533 0.020 0.520\n\n\nGPT-5.4 **n** Raw Conversation 0.727 0.074 0.081 0.778 0.074 0.714 0.360 0.395 0.085 0.359\n\nRaw User Utterances 0.715 0.079 0.082 0.772 0.076 0.708 0.296 0.319 0.159 0.287\n\nBehavioral Descriptions 0.860 0.353 0.364 0.091 0.353 0.896 0.520 0.531 0.018 0.532\n\n\nClaude Haiku 4.5 Raw Conversation 0.733 0.044 0.041 0.910 0.042 0.712 0.357 0.371 0.096 0.345\n\nRaw User Utterances 0.709 0.072 0.072 0.793 0.071 0.698 0.353 0.372 0.105 0.335\n\nBehavioral Descriptions 0.851 0.438 0.430 0.048 0.427 0.873 0.605 0.608 0.009 0.613\n\n\n**i** Gemn 3.1 Pro Raw Conversation 0.747 0.059 0.058 0.843 0.059 0.734 0.323 0.334 0.120 0.319\n\nRaw User Utterances 0.712 0.120 0.126 0.635 0.109 0.710 0.317 0.329 0.155 0.290'], '2605.07847v1_chunk_8': ['These behavioral facets abstract away irrelevant features, enabling our comparisons to focus on\nbehavioral patterns rather than surface-level signals such as lexical similarity. The full prompts and\ncriteria are provided in Appendix B.\n\n\nFor each conversation, we concatenate descriptions across all six facets into a single textual representation of user behavior. Then, we embed each representation with a text embedding model, mapping\nbehaviors from D real [and] [ D] sim [into a shared semantic space. As Pimentel et al.][ [42]][ show, embeddings]\ncapture discourse- and coherence-level features while ignoring surface-level ones, making them\nwell-suited for representing user behaviors.\n\n\n**Step 2: Quantizing into Behavioral Distributions**\n\n\nThe user behavior representations for D real [and] [ D] sim [are finite sets of continuous, high-dimensional]\nvectors. This makes estimating divergences unreliable. Following the precision and recall framework\nof Sajjadi et al. [46] and the MAUVE methodology of Pillutla et al. [41], we employ a quantization\nstep to map the representations into low-dimensional discrete distributions of behaviors. We apply\n_k_ -means clustering to the set of user behavior representations from D real [and] [ D] sim [. Each of the] _[ k]_\nclusters groups representations with similar behavioral patterns, and thus represents a particular mode\nof user behavior. We obtain probability distributions _P_ [ˆ] and _Q_ [ˆ] over _c_ 2 f 1 _, . . ., k_, where _P_ [ˆ] ( _c_ )\nand _Q_ [ˆ] ( _c_ ) denote the fraction of representations from D real [and] [ D] sim [in cluster] _[ c]_ [. These distributions]\ncapture how frequently different user behavior modes occur in real and simulated conversations, and\nserve as estimates of _P_ and _Q_ .\n\n\n3\n\n\n**Step 3: Measuring the Distributional Gap**'], '2605.07847v1_chunk_36': ['`Claude Haiku 4.5` 0.798 0.293 0.289 0.171 0.279 0.831 0.513 0.521 0.022 0.512\n\n`Gemini 3.1 Pro` 0.820 0.131 0.134 0.570 0.126 0.858 0.376 0.372 0.090 0.354\n\n`Gemini 3 Flash` 0.808 0.228 0.211 0.308 0.208 0.844 0.466 0.462 0.043 0.436\n\n`Gemini 3.1 Flash-Lite` 0.801 0.254 0.243 0.237 0.241 0.845 0.456 0.454 0.040 0.445\n\n\nn-Sourc **e** Op\n\n\n`Qwen3.5-122B-A10B` 0.806 0.234 0.221 0.281 0.219 0.844 0.456 0.452 0.039 0.448\n`Qwen3.5-35B-A3B` 0.801 0.275 0.263 0.202 0.260 0.843 0.475 0.483 0.032 0.469\n`Qwen3.5-27B` 0.798 0.2