**8** **Related Work**


**User Simulation.** LLMs have demonstrated the ability to simulate believable human behavior,
and are increasingly used as user simulators for interactive evaluation [9, 53, 68, 5, 25], synthetic
data generation [10, 17, 43], and reinforcement learning [69, 59]. Across these applications, initial
approaches rely on prompting LLMs [9, 35, 36, 29, 43]. However, these prompt-based simulators
struggle to consistently adhere to assigned user goals or profiles, motivating recent methods that train
LLM-based user simulators with goal-tracking or persona-consistency objectives [31, 1]. In order to
build simulators that can faithfully represent real users, other works train LLMs with response-level
similarity objectives, such as supervised fine-tuning on real user data [33] or aligning latent reasoning
states through reinforcement learning [16, 58, 63].


**User Simulator Evaluation.** Recent works investigate how LLM-based user simulators compare
to real users. One direction compares assistant evaluations conducted with simulators against those
conducted with real users, finding that simulator-based evaluations are poor estimates of agent
performance and obscure demographic disparities [13, 48]. A second direction compares simulator
and human behaviors at the feature level, finding systematic divergence on lexical, syntactic, and
stylistic metrics [22, 67, 7].


Across both training and evaluation work, simulator fidelity is typically measured at the response or
feature level. While some works investigate simulating diverse user populations [28, 2, 17], ours is
the first to measure how well user simulators capture the distribution of real user behaviors. We do
this by extracting representations of user behavior that go beyond lexical or stylistic features, and
clustering them to compare the distributions of real and simulated user behaviors.

