avior representations along the R facet. **es** pon\n\n\n17\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_12)\n\n**t**\n\n\n\n**t**\n\n\n\nFigure 7: Prompt for extracting user behavior representations along the Con facet. ex **t**\n\n\n18\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_13)\n\n**niom** u\n\n\n\n**niom** u\n\n\n\nFigure 8: Prompt for extracting user behavior representations along the C **niom** ucat Style facet.\n\n\n19\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_14)\n\n\n\nFigure 9: Prompt for extracting user behavior representations along the DAMSL Dialog Acts facet.\n\n\n20\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_15)\n\n\n\n\n\nFigure 10: Prompt for extracting user behavior representations along the SGD Dialog Acts facet.\n\n\n21\n\n\n**C** **User Goal Classification**\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_16)\n\n\n\nFigure 11: Prompt for classifying user goals.\n\n\n22\n\n\n**D** **Conversation Generation Prompts**\n\n\n\n\n\nFigure 12: Assistant system prompt for conversation generation.\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_17)\n\n\n\n\n\nFigure 13: User simulator system prompt for conversation generation.\n\n\n23\n\n\n**E** **Results for Each User Behavior Facet**\n\n\nIn addition to the metrics defined in Section 3, all results in the Appendix include two complementary\nmetrics:']}}, {'id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_19', 'title': '2605.07847v1_chunk_19', 'snippet': '8\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_9)\n\n: : : : : :\n\n\n**el** **s** ed **al** ucinted\n\n\n**el** **s**\n\n\nif real users dominate, and h **al** ucinted if simulated users dominate. For each category, we extract\ndistinctive terms from the behavior descriptions in the top 100 clusters using TF-IDF over unigrams\nand bigrams. Each term is scored by its TF-IDF in the target category minus the average TF-IDF over\nthe other two. To reduce noise, we filter stopwords and meaningless terms (identified by an LLM),\nand require terms to appear in at least 50 descriptions.\n\n\nWe present our analysis for `Gemini 3.1 Pro` on the coding task. Figure 4 shows the word clouds for\neach category, and Appendix I presents the full table of top 50 terms for each category. We observe\nthe following across the three categories: W-capturd: terms reflect iterative problem-solving **el**\nbehaviors such as requesting alternatives, rejecting proposed solutions, and proactively identifying\nerrors (e.g., ""requesting alternative"", ""rejects proposed"", ""proactively corrects""); Mi terms **s** ed:\nreflect behaviors the simulator fails to reproduce: terse and compressed communication, transactional\nexchanges, authoritative directives (e.g., ""message terse"", ""authoritative"", ""transactional analytical"");\nH **al** ucinted: terms reflect overly enthusiastic behaviors such as excessive positivity and gratitude,\nand frequent greetings and farewells (e.g., ""friendliness"", ""thanks awesome"", ""formal pleasantries"").\n\n\n**8** **Related Work**', 'score': None, 'metadata': {'vertex_id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_19', 'snippets': ['8\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_9)\n\n: : : : : :\n\n\n**el** **s** ed **al** ucinted\n\n\n**el** **s**\n\n\nif real users dominate, and h **al** ucinted if simulated users dominate. For each category, we extract\ndistinctive terms from the behavior descriptions in the top 100 clusters using TF-IDF over unigrams\nand bigrams. Each term is scored by its TF-IDF in the target category minus the average TF-IDF over\nthe other two. To reduce noise, we filter stopwords and meaningless terms (identified by an LLM),\nand require terms to appear in at least 50 descriptions.\n\n\nWe present our analysis for `Gemini 3.1 Pro` on the coding task. Figure 4 shows the word clouds for\neach category, and Appendix I presents the full table of top 50 terms for each category. We observe\nthe following across the three categories: W-capturd: terms reflect iterative problem-solving **el**\nbehaviors such as requesting alternatives, rejecting proposed solutions, and proactively identifying\nerrors (e.g., ""requesting alternative"", ""rejects proposed"", ""proactively corrects""); Mi terms **s** ed:\nreflect behaviors the simulator fails to reproduce: terse and compressed communication, transactional\nexchanges, authoritative directives (e.g., ""message terse"", ""authoritative"", ""transactional analytical"");\nH **al** ucinted: terms reflect overly enthusiastic behaviors such as excessive positivity and gratitude,\nand frequent greetings and farewells (e.g., ""friendliness"", ""thanks awesome"", ""formal pleasantries"").\n\n\n**8** **Related Work**']}}, {'id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_1', 'title': '2605.07847v1_chunk_1', 'snippet': '```\n             mehri2@illinois.edu\n\n```', 'score': None, 'metadata': {'vertex_id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_1', 'snippets': ['```\n             mehri2@illinois.edu\n\n```\n']}}, {'id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_18', 'title': '2605.07847v1_chunk_18', 'snippet': 'First, we pair the simulators with the smallest distributional gap to real users: `Gemini 3.1 Pro` with\n`GPT-5.4`, and `gpt-oss-120b` with `gemma-4-31B-it` . Both pairs achieve smaller JS divergence\nthan either individual simulator on coding and writing. Next, we pair simulators that are behaviorally\ndistinct from others, `UserLM-8b` and `GPT-5.4 mini`, with each of `Gemini 3.1 Pro`, `GPT-5.4`,\n`gemma-4-31B-it`, and `gpt-oss-120b` . These improve over the individual simulators on writing\nand remain competitive on coding. Conversely, combining behaviorally similar simulators, such as\n`gemma-4-31B-it` and `Claude Haiku 4.5`, does not help.\n\n\nThese results suggest that combining behaviorally complementary simulators can reduce the distributional gap to real users. This combination strategy is conceptually similar to mixture-of-experts\n\n[49, 15] and assistant-side routing [37, 56, 34], and learning a router that selects the appropriate\nsimulator is a natural extension we leave to future work.\n\n\n**7.3** **Interpreting the Behavioral Clusters**\n\n\nFigure 4: Word clouds of w-capturd (green), **el** mi **s** ed (blue), and h **al** ucinted (red) behaviors for\n`Gemini 3.1 Pro` on coding based on a TF-IDF analysis on behavioral clusters.\n\n\nThe behavioral distributions reveal not only how much simulators diverge from real users, but which\nbehaviors they capture, miss, or hallucinate. We classify each cluster by the ratio of real to simulated\nconversations into three categories: w-capturd if real and simulated are roughly balanced, **el** mi **s**\n\n\n8\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_9)\n\n: : : : : :\n\n\n**el** **s** ed **al** ucinted\n\n\n**el** **s**', 'score': None, 'metadata': {'vertex_id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_18', 'snippets': ['First, we pair the simulators with the smallest distributional gap to real users: `Gemini 3.1 Pro` with\n`GPT-5.4`, and `gpt-oss-120b` with `gemma-4-31B-it` . Both pairs achieve smaller JS divergence\nthan either individual simulator on coding and writing. Next, we pair simulators that are behaviorally\ndistinct from others, `UserLM-8b` and `GPT-5.4 mini`, with each of `Gemini 3.1 Pro`, `GPT-5.4`,\n`gemma-4-31B-it`, and `gpt-oss-120b` . These improve over the individual simulators on writing\nand remain competitive on coding. Conversely, combining behaviorally similar simulators, such as\n`gemma-4-31B-it` and `Claude Haiku 4.5`, does not help.\n\n\nThese results suggest that combining behaviorally complementary simulators can reduce the distributional gap to real users. This combination strategy is conceptually similar to mixture-of-experts\n\n[49, 15] and assistant-side routing [37, 56, 34], and learning a router that selects the appropriate\nsimulator is a natural extension we leave to future work.\n\n\n**7.3** **Interpreting the Behavioral Clusters**\n\n\nFigure 4: Word clouds of w-capturd (green), **el** mi **s** ed (blue), and h **al** ucinted (red) behaviors for\n`Gemini 3.1 Pro` on coding based on a TF-IDF analysis on behavioral clusters.\n\n\nThe behavioral distributions reveal not only how much simulators diverge from real users, but which\nbehaviors they capture, miss, or hallucinate. We classify each cluster by the ratio of real to simulated\nconversations into three categories: w-capturd if real and simulated are roughly balanced, **el** mi **s**\n\n\n8\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_9)\n\n: : : : : :\n\n\n**el** **s** ed **al** ucinted\n\n\n**el** **s**']}}, {'id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_16', 'title': '2605.07847v1_chunk_16', 'snippet': '**6.3** **Linear Classification**\n\n\nWe validate that our user behavior representation embeddings encode meaningful differences between\nreal and simulated users by training a linear classifier. For each simulator, we construct a dataset\nof 5,000 real and 5,000 simulated embeddings, and then train an L2-regularized logistic regression\nclassifier to classify embeddings as real or simulated. We average results over 5 stratified random\n80/20 train-test splits. The classification accuracies across simulators are consistently high, ranging\nfrom 90.92% to 99.63%, and also correlate strongly with our distributional metrics (Figure 2). This\nconfirms that the embeddings encode meaningful differences between real and simulated users. The\nfull accuracy scores and correlations for all metrics are presented in Appendix H.\n\n\n**7** **Discussion**\n\n\n**7.1** **How Do User Behavior Distributions Compare Among Simulators?**\n\n\nOur main results show that the distributional gap to real users varies across simulators. This raises a\nnatural question: how do the behviorl d **a** rbuon of user **ist** imulator compare to each other? **s** To\ninvestigate this, we pool the user behavior representations across all 24 simulators, quantize them\ninto distributions, and compute the JS divergence between all pairs. Figure 3 reports the results.\n\n\nMany simulators behave similarly to each other: 30% of the 552 pairwise comparisons have JS _<_\n0 _._ 10. Pairs from the same family tend to be the most similar, achieving the lowest scores in the\ndataset. The simulators with the lowest mean pairwise JS scores are `Qwen3.5-122B-A10B` (0 _._ 14),\n\n\n7', 'score': None, 'metadata': {'vertex_id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_16', 'snippets': ['**6.3** **Linear Classification**\n\n\nWe validate that our user behavior representation embeddings encode meaningful differences between\nreal and simulated users by training a linear classifier. For each simulator, we construct a dataset\nof 5,000 real and 5,000 simulated embeddings, and then train an L2-regularized logistic regression\nclassifier to classify embeddings as real or simulated. We average results over 5 stratified random\n80/20 train-test splits. The classification accuracies across simulators are consistently high, ranging\nfrom 90.92% to 99.63%, and also correlate strongly with our distributional metrics (Figure 2). This\nconfirms that the embeddings encode meaningful differences between real and simulated users. The\nfull accuracy scores and correlations for all metrics are presented in Appendix H.\n\n\n**7** **Discussion**\n\n\n**7.1** **How Do User Behavior Distributions Compare Among Simulators?**\n\n\nOur main results show that the distributional gap to real users varies across simulators. This raises a\nnatural question: how do the behviorl d **a** rbuon of user **ist** imulator compare to each other? **s** To\ninvestigate this, we pool the user behavior representations across all 24 simulators, quantize them\ninto distributions, and compute the JS divergence between all pairs. Figure 3 reports the results.\n\n\nMany simulators behave similarly to each other: 30% of the 552 pairwise comparisons have JS _<_\n0 _._ 10. Pairs from the same family tend to be the most similar, achieving the lowest scores in the\ndataset. The simulators with the lowest mean pairwise JS scores are `Qwen3.5-122B-A10B` (0 _._ 14),\n\n\n7']}}, {'id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_20', 'title': '2605.07847v1_chunk_20', 'snippet': '**8** **Related Work**\n\n\n**User Simulation.** LLMs have demonstrated the ability to simulate believable human behavior,\nand are increasingly used as user simulators for interactive evaluation [9, 53, 68, 5, 25], synthetic\ndata generation [10, 17, 43], and reinforcement learning [69, 59]. Across these applications, initial\napproaches rely on prompting LLMs [9, 35, 36, 29, 43]. However, these prompt-based simulators\nstruggle to consistently adhere to assigned user goals or profiles, motivating recent methods that train\nLLM-based user simulators with goal-tracking or persona-consistency objectives [31, 1]. In order to\nbuild simulators that can faithfully represent real users, other works train LLMs with response-level\nsimilarity objectives, such as supervised fine-tuning on real user data [33] or aligning latent reasoning\nstates through reinforcement learning [16, 58, 63].\n\n\n**User Simulator Evaluation.** Recent works investigate how LLM-based user simulators compare\nto real users. One direction compares assistant evaluations conducted with simulators against those\nconducted with real users, finding that simulator-based evaluations are poor estimates of agent\nperformance and obscure demographic disparities [13, 48]. A second direction compares simulator\nand human behaviors at the feature level, finding systematic divergence on lexical, syntactic, and\nstylistic metrics [22, 67, 7].\n\n\nAcross both training and evaluation work, simulator fidelity is typically measured at the response or\nfeature level. While some works investigate simulating diverse user populations [28, 2, 17], ours is\nthe first to measure how well user simulators capture the distribution of real user behaviors. We do\nthis by extracting representations of user behavior that go beyond lexical or stylistic features, and\nclustering them to compare the distributions of real and simulated user behaviors.', 'score': None, 'metadata': {'vertex_id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_20', 'snippets': ['**8** **Related Work**\n\n\n**User Simulation.** LLMs have demonstrated the ability to simulate believable human behavior,\nand are increasingly used as user simulators for interactive evaluation [9, 53, 68, 5, 25], synthetic\ndata generation [10, 17, 43], and reinforcement learning [69, 59]. Across these applications, initial\napproaches rely on prompting LLMs [9, 35, 36, 29, 43]. However, these prompt-based simulators\nstruggle to consistently adhere to assigned user goals or profiles, motivating recent methods that train\nLLM-based user simulators with goal-tracking or persona-consistency objectives [31, 1]. In order to\nbuild simulators that can faithfully represent real users, other works train LLMs with response-level\nsimilarity objectives, such as supervised fine-tuning on real user data [33] or aligning latent reasoning\nstates through reinforcement learning [16, 58, 63].\n\n\n**User Simulator Evaluation.** Recent works investigate how LLM-based user simulators compare\nto real users. One direction compares assistant evaluations conducted with simulators against those\nconducted with real users, finding that simulator-based evaluations are poor estimates of agent\nperformance and obscure demographic disparities [13, 48]. A second direction compares simulator\nand human behaviors at the feature level, finding systematic divergence on lexical, syntactic, and\nstylistic metrics [22, 67, 7].\n\n\nAcross both training and evaluation work, simulator fidelity is typically measured at the response or\nfeature level. While some works investigate simulating diverse user populations [28, 2, 17], ours is\nthe first to measure how well user simulators capture the distribution of real user behaviors. We do\nthis by extracting representations of user behavior that go beyond lexical or stylistic features, and\nclustering them to compare the distributions of real and simulated user behaviors.']}}, {'id': '2605.07905v1_chunk_47', 'title': '2605.07905v1_chunk_47', 'snippet': '16\n\n\n**CoCoReviewBench: A Completeness- and Correctness-Oriented Benchmark for AI Reviewers**\n\n\n_Table 4._ Complete taxonomy of CoCoReviewBench categories and subcategories.\n\n\n**Category** **Subcategories and Descriptions**\n\n\n**Quality** **Quality-Method** (Methodological Soundness): Evaluates whether the proposed algorithms, models, or system\narchitectures are technically correct and free of conceptual or implementation errors.\n**Quality-Experiment** (Experimental Design & Evaluation): Assesses the adequacy of the experimental setup:\nchoice of datasets, baselines, evaluation metrics, ablation studies, and statistical tests.\n**Quality-Reproducibility** (Reproducibility & Implementation Details): Considers whether the submission provides\nenough detail (e.g., hyperparameters, code availability, dataset splits) to replicate the work and whether the\nimplementation follows best practices.\n**Quality-Comparisons** (Comparisons to Prior Work): Evaluates whether the paper sufficiently compares against\nrelevant prior work and state-of-the-art methods.\n**Quality-Statistics** (Statistical Rigor & Validation): Evaluates whether statistical analyses (e.g., significance tests,\nconfidence intervals) are properly applied and whether reported improvements are statistically meaningful.\n\n\n**Clarity** **Clarity-Writing** (Writing, Terminology & Algorithm Presentation): Covers overall writing quality and organization, precision of terminology and key concepts, and the clarity of algorithm presentations (code snippets,\npseudocode, workflow diagrams).\n**Clarity-Notation** (Notation & Mathematical Explanation Clarity): Considers whether mathematical notation is\nconsistent, well defined and explained.\n**Clarity-Figure/Table** (Figures & Visual Aids Clarity): Evaluates whether figures, tables, plots, and visualizations\nare legible, properly labeled, and aid understanding.', 'score': None, 'metadata': {'vertex_id': '2605.07905v1_chunk_47', 'snippets': ['16\n\n\n**CoCoReviewBench: A Completeness- and Correctness-Oriented Benchmark for AI Reviewers**\n\n\n_Table 4._ Complete taxonomy of CoCoReviewBench categories and subcategories.\n\n\n**Category** **Subcategories and Descriptions**\n\n\n**Quality** **Quality-Method** (Methodological Soundness): Evaluates whether the proposed algorithms, models, or system\narchitectures are technically correct and free of conceptual or implementation errors.\n**Quality-Experiment** (Experimental Design & Evaluation): Assesses the adequacy of the experimental setup:\nchoice of datasets, baselines, evaluation metrics, ablation studies, and statistical tests.\n**Quality-Reproducibility** (Reproducibility & Implementation Details): Considers whether the submission provides\nenough detail (e.g., hyperparameters, code availability, dataset splits) to replicate the work and whether the\nimplementation follows best practices.\n**Quality-Comparisons** (Comparisons to Prior Work): Evaluates whether the paper sufficiently compares against\nrelevant prior work and state-of-the-art methods.\n**Quality-Statistics** (Statistical Rigor & Validation): Evaluates whether statistical analyses (e.g., significance tests,\nconfidence intervals) are properly applied and whether reported improvements are statistically meaningful.\n\n\n**Clarity** **Clarity-Writing** (Writing, Terminology & Algorithm Presentation): Covers overall writing quality and organization, precision of terminology and key concepts, and the clarity of algorithm presentations (code snippets,\npseudocode, workflow diagrams).\n**Clarity-Notation** (Notation & Mathematical Explanation Clarity): Considers whether mathematical notation is\nconsistent, well defined and explained.\n**Clarity-Figure/Table** (Figures & Visual Aids Clarity): Evaluates whether figures, tables, plots, and visualizations\nare legible, properly labeled, and aid understanding.']}}]","['GraphRAG Candidate', 'GraphRAG Candidate', 'GraphRAG Candidate', 'GraphRAG Candidate', 'GraphRAG Candidate', '2605.07847v1_chunk_35', '2605.07847v1_chunk_3', '2605.07847v1_chunk_2', '2605.07905v1_chunk_45', '2605.07905v1_chunk_46', '2605.07847v1_chunk_33', '2605.07847v1_chunk_17', '2605.07847v1_chunk_34', '2605.07847v1_chunk_19', '2605.07847v1_chunk_1', '2605.07847v1_chunk_18', '2605.07847v1_chunk_16', '2605.07847v1_chunk_20', '2605.07905v1_chunk_47']",11,5932,117,128,50554.661985000166,4.600686999765458,0.0,50559.332953000194,graph,19,0.0,"{'response': ""The paper 2605.07847v1 evaluates simulators and tasks related to user behavior in conversations, particularly focusing on the Gemini 3.1 Pro and Llama-3.1-8B-Instruct simulators. The evaluation is based on how well these simulators capture the distribution of real users' behaviors, including both precision (rarely exhibiting behaviors) and recall (failing to exhibit common behaviors). Additionally, the paper evaluates simulators such as Gemini 3.1 Pro, gpt-oss-120b, and their combinations with other simulators like GPT-5.4, gemma-4-31B-it, and UserLM-8b on tasks including coding and writing. The combination of behaviorally complementary simulators is shown to reduce the distributional gap to real users. The evaluation metrics include Nearest Neighbor Cosine Similarity and MAUVE, which compare real user behaviors with simulated ones across these tasks."", 'retrieved': [{'candidate_answer': ""The paper evaluates simulators and tasks related to user behavior in conversations, particularly focusing on the Gemini 3.1 Pro and Llama-3.1-8B-Instruct simulators. The evaluation is based on how well these simulators capture the distribution of real users' behaviors, including both precision (rarely exhibiting behaviors) and recall (failing to exhibit common behaviors)."", 'score': 95}, {'candidate_answer': 'The paper evaluates simulators and tasks using the `Gemini 3.1 Pro` simulator on a coding task. The analysis focuses on three categories: W-captured, Mi terms, and H-alucinted. W-captured behaviors reflect iterative problem-solving such as requesting alternatives, rejecting proposed solutions, and proactively identifying errors. Mi terms represent behaviors that the simulator fails to reproduce, including terse communication, transactional exchanges, and authoritative directives. H-alucinted terms indicate overly enthusiastic behaviors like excessive positivity, gratitude, frequent greetings, and farewells.', 'score': 95}, {'candidate_answer': 'The paper 2605.07847v1 evaluates user simulators and tasks by comparing the distributions of real and simulated user behaviors at a response or feature level, going beyond lexical or stylistic features.', 'score': 95}, {'candidate_answer': 'The paper evaluates simulators such as `Gemini 3.1 Pro`, `gpt-oss-120b`, and their combinations with other simulators like `GPT-5.4`, `gemma-4-31B-it`, and `UserLM-8b`. The tasks include coding and writing, where the combination of behaviorally complementary simulators is shown to reduce the distributional gap to real users.', 'score': 90}, {'candidate_answer': 'The paper evaluates simulators and tasks related to coding and writing. The evaluation metrics include Nearest Neighbor Cosine Similarity and MAUVE, which compare real user behaviors with simulated ones across these tasks.', 'score': 85}], 'verbose': {'selected_set': [{'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_1', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_35', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_20', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_17', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_19', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07905v1_chunk_47', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_3', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07905v1_chunk_46', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07905v1_chunk_45', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_2', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_16', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_33', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_34', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_18', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}], 'start_set': [{'v': '2605.07905v1_chunk_47', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_3', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_18', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_35', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_20', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}], 'final_retrieval': {'2605.07847v1_chunk_35': ['Figure 13: User simulator system prompt for conversation generation.\n\n\n23\n\n\n**E** **Results for Each User Behavior Facet**\n\n\nIn addition to the metrics defined in Section 3, all results in the Appendix include two complementary\nmetrics:\n\n\n - **Nearest Neighbor Cosine Similarity:** The average cosine similarity between each real user and\nits nearest neighbor in the simulated set. Higher values indicate that simulated behaviors are closer\nto real ones in the embedding space. This metric is computed directly on the embeddings.\n\n\nˆ ˆ\n\n - **MAUVE:** Compares _P_ and _Q_ usingˆ divergence frontiers [41]. The mixture\nf (exp(distribution � _c_ KL( _RQ_ ˆ k _R_ � =)) _,_ exp( _λP_ [ˆ] + (1 � _c_ KL( � _P_ ˆ _λ_ k _R_ ) � _Q_ )))yields _, λ_ (0the _,_ 1) divergence. The MAUVE score is thecurve C ( _P,_ [ˆ] _Q_ [ˆ] ) =\narea under this curve, which captures both failure modes. Higher values indicate better alignment\nbetween real and simulated users. We clarify that we apply the divergence-frontier formulation of\nPillutla et al. [41], not the off-the-shelf text-generation metric.\n\n\nTable 4: Requests facet results. The distributional gap between real and simulated user behaviors\nacross coding and writing tasks. We compare the distribution of user behaviors demonstrated in D real\nwith those in D sim [.] [ ""] [ indicates hi][g][her is better and] [ #] [ indicates lower is better.]\n\n\n**Coding** **Writing**\n\n\n**User Simulator** NN "" KL fwd KL bwd MAU "" JS # NN "" KL KL bwd MAU "" JS #\n\n\nReal U **s** .826 .034 .035 .924 .039 .888 .024 .025 .955 .029\n\n\nd-SurcCl **o** s **e**\n\n\n`GPT-5.4` 0.815 0.164 0.175 0.437 0.163 0.862 0.337 0.355 0.111 0.330\n\n`GPT-5.4 mini` 0.810 0.219 0.245 0.260 0.229 0.863 0.295 0.308 0.151 0.294\n\n`GPT-5.4 nano` 0.804 0.269 0.291 0.198 0.262 0.855 0.396 0.420 0.065 0.392\n\n`Claude Haiku 4.5` 0.798 0.293 0.289 0.171 0.279 0.831 0.513 0.521 0.022 0.512\n\n`Gemini 3.1 Pro` 0.820 0.131 0.134 0.570 0.126 0.858 0.376 0.372 0.090 0.354\n\n`Gemini 3 Flash` 0.808 0.228 0.211 0.308 0.208 0.844 0.466 0.462 0.043 0.436'], '2605.07847v1_chunk_3': ['![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_2)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n||||\n|---|---|---|\n|Qu|a|ntiz|\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_3)\n\nFigure 1: Our method extracts representations of user behavior from real and simulated conversations, then quantizes them via _k_ -means to get discrete behavioral distributions for real ( _P_ [ˆ] ) and\nsimulated users ( _Q_ [ˆ] ). UMAP projections [30] and first principal component histograms illustrate the\ndistributional gap for two simulators on the coding task: `Gemini 3.1 Pro` overlaps real users more\nclosely compared to `Llama-3.1-8B-Instruct` .\n\n\nPreprint.\n\n\n**1** **Introduction**\n\n\nThe role of user simulators is to model the diverse behaviors of real users, providing a scalable\nmeans to train and evaluate AI systems on the interactions that they encounter in real-world settings\n\n[26, 14, 39, 45]. Recent works build user simulators by training Large Language Models (LLMs)\nto generate responses that resemble those of real users [33, 16, 58]. Yet real users exhibit a broad,\nheterogeneous distribution of behaviors [65, 66, 28]. For example, some users tend to underspecify\ntheir requests, while others fully specify every constraint. The extent to which user simulators capture\nthis distribution has not been measured.\n\n\nA user simulator can fail to capture the distribution of real users in two ways: by demonstrating\nbehaviors that real users rarely exhibit (low prec **i** son), or by failing to demonstrate behaviors that real\nusers do exhibit (low reca **l** ), mirroring precision and recall metrics for generative models [ 46, 23, 11].\nThese failure modes bias training and evaluation, and yield assistants that struggle to generalize to\nthe diverse behaviors of real users [52].'], '2605.07847v1_chunk_2': ['**Code** : `[https://github.com/shuhaibm/UserBehavioralDivergence](https://github.com/shuhaibm/UserBehavioralDivergence)`\n\n\n**Abstract**\n\n\nAs user simulators are increasingly used for interactive training and evaluation\nof AI assistants, it is essential that they represent the diverse behaviors of real\nusers. While existing works train user simulators to generate human-like responses,\nwhether they capture the broad and heterogeneous distribution of real user behaviors\nremains an open question. In this work, we introduce a method to measure the\ndistributional gap between real and simulated user behaviors, validated through a\nhuman study and ablations. Given a dataset of real and simulated conversations, our\nmethod extracts representations of user behavior from each conversation, quantizes\nthem into discrete distributions via clustering, then computes divergence metrics.\nWe provide the first systematic evaluation of 24 LLM-based user simulators on\ncoding and writing tasks, and reveal a large distributional gap from real users that\nvaries across model families, scales, and behavioral facets. Pairwise comparisons\nshow that most simulators behave similarly, while a few stand apart. Combining\nbehaviorally complementary simulators brings the resulting distribution closer to\nreal users compared to either simulator on its own. Finally, a TF-IDF analysis of\nthe clusters surfaces interpretable patterns of behaviors that simulators capture,\nmiss, and hallucinate.\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_1)\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_2)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n||||\n|---|---|---|\n|Qu|a|ntiz|\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_3)'], '2605.07905v1_chunk_45': ['**Originality** : Does the work provide new insights, deepen understanding, or highlight important properties of existing\nmethods? Is it clear how this work differs from previous contributions, with relevant citations provided? Does the work\nintroduce novel tasks or methods that advance the field? Does this work offer a novel combination of existing techniques, and\nis the reasoning behind this combination well articulated? As the questions above indicate, originality does not necessarily\nrequire introducing an entirely new method. Rather, work that provides novel insights by evaluating existing methods, or\ndemonstrates improved efficiency, fairness, etc., is also equally valuable.\n\n\n**Policy** : Encompasses policy- or compliance-related concerns such as ethics, data/privacy compliance, anonymity rules,\nplagiarism, licensing, and broader impact. These issues often require checking adherence to conference or legal policies and\nmay involve ethical considerations.\n\n\nTo enable fine-grained evaluation, training, and analysis, we further decompose these 5 dimensions into 23 fine-grained\nsubcategories, forming our hierarchical taxonomy. This granular decomposition supports a more rigorous and systematic\nassessment of review coverage, ensuring that each critical aspect of a scientific manuscript is explicitly evaluated. The\ndetailed definitions are presented in Table 4.\n\n\n**A.2. Detailed Construction Process**'], '2605.07905v1_chunk_46': ['**A.2. Detailed Construction Process**\n\n\nTo construct the subcategories, we primarily rely on data mining via GPT-5 in agent mode to extract subcategories that are\nas comprehensive as possible from large-scale existing data. Concretely, using the reviewer guidelines above as exemplars,\nwe first prompt the model to retrieve reviewer guidelines from venues such as NeurIPS, ICLR, and ACL Rolling Review\nto form an initial taxonomy draft. We generate multiple candidate versions with this procedure. We then evaluate each\nversion on a small development set by asking GPT-5 and Gemini-2.5-Pro to classify review comments under the candidate\ntaxonomy, compute classification consistency (inter-model agreement), and select the version with the highest consistency.\n\n\nNext, we further refine the above taxonomy by having GPT-5 agent mode collect large volumes of OpenReview reviews\nand attempt to categorize them under the current taxonomy. This process helps identify missing and frequently confused\ncategories, prompting further taxonomy refinement and the addition of boundary rules to disambiguate borderline cases. We\nalso feed cases where GPT-5 and Gemini-2.5-Pro disagree on the test set back into the refinement loop as additional signals.\nFinally, we finalize 23 distinct subcategories. After the category set is fixed, we continue refining and adding boundary rules\nto reduce model confusion and produce the final prompt for classification.\n\n\n[1https://neurips.cc/Conferences/2025/ReviewerGuidelines](https://neurips.cc/Conferences/2025/ReviewerGuidelines)\n[2https://aclrollingreview.org/reviewform](https://aclrollingreview.org/reviewform)\n\n\n16\n\n\n**CoCoReviewBench: A Completeness- and Correctness-Oriented Benchmark for AI Reviewers**\n\n\n_Table 4._ Complete taxonomy of CoCoReviewBench categories and subcategories.\n\n\n**Category** **Subcategories and Descriptions**'], '2605.07847v1_chunk_33': ['Through a human study and a series of validation experiments, we confirm that our method captures\nmeaningful behavioral distributions and is robust to the choice of embedding model and clustering\nalgorithm. We would like acknowledge, however, that our approach relies on a capable LLM\n(Qwen3.5-122B-A10B-FP8) to analyze conversations and generate accurate descriptions of user\nbehavior.\n\n\nIn our work, we describe that user simulators can fail to capture the distribution of real users when\nthey either demonstrate behaviors that real users rarely exhibit, or when they don’t demonstrate\nbehaviors that real users do exhibit. However, in some cases this is actually desirable. For example,\nwhen user simulators are used to stress-test assistants against rare or adversarial user inputs that\nthe real-world data does not capture well. We do not distinguish between desirable and undesirable\ndivergence, and leave this for future work. Lastly, our work focuses more on intrinsic analysis, and\ndoes not measure how user simulator distributional gaps affect downstream training or evaluation for\nassistants.\n\n\nUser simulators serve an important role in the development process of AI systems, often being\nused during training or evaluation. When simulators underrepresent the behaviors of certain user\npopulations, these assistant may fail to serve those users well, and the burden of this failure falls on\nthe populations whose behaviors are underrepresented. Closing this distributional gap is therefore\nimportant for building AI systems that work for users all over the world, including different cultures,\nlanguages, and demographics. Beyond this, high-fidelity user simulators raise dual-use concerns and\ncan be misused to impersonate real users or create fake users for unwanted purposes. Addressing\nthese limitations is important for advancing user simulators that faithfully represent real users and\nsupport the responsible development of AI systems.\n\n\n15\n\n\n**B** **User Behavior Representation Prompts**\n\n\n**es** tqu'], '2605.07847v1_chunk_17': ['7\n\n\nTable 3: The distributional gap between real and simulated user behaviors when combining pairs\nof simulators. When generating conversations, we randomly sample which LLM serves as the\nuser simulator. We report forward KL divergence (KL ), backward KL divergence (KL bwd ), and\nJensen–Shannon divergence (JS) across coding and writing tasks. "" indicates higher is better and #\nindicates lower is better. Darker blue indicates closer behavioral distribution to real users. Subscripts\nshow the change relative to the better of the two individual simulators\n\n\n**Coding** **Writing**\n\n\n**User Simulator** KL KL bwd JS # KL KL bwd JS #\n\n\n: : : : : :\n\n\n**el** **s** ed **al** ucinted\n\n\n**el** **s**\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_8)\n\n: : : : : :\n\n\n**el** **s** ed **al** ucinted\n\n\n**el** **s**\n\n\n\n: : : : : :\n\n\n**el** **s** ed **al** ucinted\n\n\n**el** **s**\n\n\n\n`gemma-4-31B-it` + `Claude Haiku 4.5` .364 _↑_ : .345 _↑_ : .346 _↑_ : .562 _↑_ : .568 _↑_ : .572 _↑_ :\n\n\n`gemma-4-26B-A4B-it` (0 _._ 15), `gemma-4-E2B-it` (0 _._ 15), and `Qwen3.5-35B-A3B` (0 _._ 15). A few\nsimulators stand out and demonstrate behaviors that diverge from the rest. These include `UserLM-8b`,\nwhich has the highest mean pairwise JS score of 0 _._ 41, followed by `GPT-5.4 mini` with a score of\n0 _._ 33. Pairwise JS scores are consistently higher for writing than coding, which aligns with our main\nresults, where the divergences from real users were also higher for writing.\n\n\n**7.2** **Can we Combine User Simulators to Reduce the Gap With Real Users?**\n\n\nSince our pairwise analysis shows that some user simulators behave distinctly from each other, we\ntest whether combining pairs can reduce the gap to real users by randomly sampling which simulator\ngenerates each conversation. Table 3 reports the results.'], '2605.07847v1_chunk_34': ['15\n\n\n**B** **User Behavior Representation Prompts**\n\n\n**es** tqu\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_10)\n\n**es** tqu\n\n\n\n**es** tqu\n\n\n\nFigure 5: Prompt for extracting user behavior representations along the R facet. **es** tqu\n\n\n16\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_11)\n\n**es** pon\n\n\n\n**es** pon\n\n\n\n**es** pon\n\n\n\nFigure 6: Prompt for extracting user behavior representations along the R facet. **es** pon\n\n\n17\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_12)\n\n**t**\n\n\n\n**t**\n\n\n\nFigure 7: Prompt for extracting user behavior representations along the Con facet. ex **t**\n\n\n18\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_13)\n\n**niom** u\n\n\n\n**niom** u\n\n\n\nFigure 8: Prompt for extracting user behavior representations along the C **niom** ucat Style facet.\n\n\n19\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_14)\n\n\n\nFigure 9: Prompt for extracting user behavior representations along the DAMSL Dialog Acts facet.\n\n\n20\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_15)\n\n\n\n\n\nFigure 10: Prompt for extracting user behavior representations along the SGD Dialog Acts facet.\n\n\n21\n\n\n**C** **User Goal Classification**\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_16)\n\n\n\nFigure 11: Prompt for classifying user goals.\n\n\n22\n\n\n**D** **Conversation Generation Prompts**\n\n\n\n\n\nFigure 12: Assistant system prompt for conversation generation.\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_17)\n\n\n\n\n\nFigure 13: User simulator system prompt for conversation generation.\n\n\n23\n\n\n**E** **Results for Each User Behavior Facet**\n\n\nIn addition to the metrics defined in Section 3, all results in the Appendix include two complementary\nmetrics:'], '2605.07847v1_chunk_19': ['8\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_9)\n\n: : : : : :\n\n\n**el** **s** ed **al** ucinted\n\n\n**el** **s**\n\n\nif real users dominate, and h **al** ucinted if simulated users dominate. For each category, we extract\ndistinctive terms from the behavior descriptions in the top 100 clusters using TF-IDF over unigrams\nand bigrams. Each term is scored by its TF-IDF in the target category minus the average TF-IDF over\nthe other two. To reduce noise, we filter stopwords and meaningless terms (identified by an LLM),\nand require terms to appear in at least 50 descriptions.\n\n\nWe present our analysis for `Gemini 3.1 Pro` on the coding task. Figure 4 shows the word clouds for\neach category, and Appendix I presents the full table of top 50 terms for each category. We observe\nthe following across the three categories: W-capturd: terms reflect iterative problem-solving **el**\nbehaviors such as requesting alternatives, rejecting proposed solutions, and proactively identifying\nerrors (e.g., ""requesting alternative"", ""rejects proposed"", ""proactively corrects""); Mi terms **s** ed:\nreflect behaviors the simulator fails to reproduce: terse and compressed communication, transactional\nexchanges, authoritative directives (e.g., ""message terse"", ""authoritative"", ""transactional analytical"");\nH **al** ucinted: terms reflect overly enthusiastic behaviors such as excessive positivity and gratitude,\nand frequent greetings and farewells (e.g., ""friendliness"", ""thanks awesome"", ""formal pleasantries"").\n\n\n**8** **Related Work**'], '2605.07847v1_chunk_1': ['```\n             mehri2@illinois.edu\n\n```\n'], '2605.07847v1_chunk_18': ['First, we pair the simulators with the smallest distributional gap to real users: `Gemini 3.1 Pro` with\n`GPT-5.4`, and `gpt-oss-120b` with `gemma-4-31B-it` . Both pairs achieve smaller JS divergence\nthan either individual simulator on coding and writing. Next, we pair simulators that are behaviorally\ndistinct from others, `UserLM-8b` and `GPT-5.4 mini`, with each of `Gemini 3.1 Pro`, `GPT-5.4`,\n`gemma-4-31B-it`, and `gpt-oss-120b` . These improve over the individual simulators on writing\nand remain competitive on coding. Conversely, combining behaviorally similar simulators, such as\n`gemma-4-31B-it` and `Claude Haiku 4.5`, does not help.\n\n\nThese results suggest that combining behaviorally complementary simulators can reduce the distributional gap to real users. This combination strategy is conceptually similar to mixture-of-experts\n\n[49, 15] and assistant-side routing [37, 56, 34], and learning a router that selects the appropriate\nsimulator is a natural extension we leave to future work.\n\n\n**7.3** **Interpreting the Behavioral Clusters**\n\n\nFigure 4: Word clouds of w-capturd (green), **el** mi **s** ed (blue), and h **al** ucinted (red) behaviors for\n`Gemini 3.1 Pro` on coding based on a TF-IDF analysis on behavioral clusters.\n\n\nThe behavioral distributions reveal not only how much simulators diverge from real users, but which\nbehaviors they capture, miss, or hallucinate. We classify each cluster by the ratio of real to simulated\nconversations into three categories: w-capturd if real and simulated are roughly balanced, **el** mi **s**\n\n\n8\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_9)\n\n: : : : : :\n\n\n**el** **s** ed **al** ucinted\n\n\n**el** **s**'], '2605.07847v1_chunk_16': ['**6.3** **Linear Classification**\n\n\nWe validate that our user behavior representation embeddings encode meaningful differences between\nreal and simulated users by training a linear classifier. For each simulator, we construct a dataset\nof 5,000 real and 5,000 simulated embeddings, and then train an L2-regularized logistic regression\nclassifier to classify embeddings as real or simulated. We average results over 5 stratified random\n80/20 train-test splits. The classification accuracies across simulators are consistently high, ranging\nfrom 90.92% to 99.63%, and also correlate strongly with our distributional metrics (Figure 2). This\nconfirms that the embeddings encode meaningful differences between real and simulated users. The\nfull accuracy scores and correlations for all metrics are presented in Appendix H.\n\n\n**7** **Discussion**\n\n\n**7.1** **How Do User Behavior Distributions Compare Among Simulators?**\n\n\nOur main results show that the distributional gap to real users varies across simulators. This raises a\nnatural question: how do the behviorl d **a** rbuon of user **ist** imulator compare to each other? **s** To\ninvestigate this, we pool the user behavior representations across all 24 simulators, quantize them\ninto distributions, and compute the JS divergence between all pairs. Figure 3 reports the results.\n\n\nMany simulators behave similarly to each other: 30% of the 552 pairwise comparisons have JS _<_\n0 _._ 10. Pairs from the same family tend to be the most similar, achieving the lowest scores in the\ndataset. The simulators with the lowest mean pairwise JS scores are `Qwen3.5-122B-A10B` (0 _._ 14),\n\n\n7'], '2605.07847v1_chunk_20': ['**8** **Related Work**\n\n\n**User Simulation.** LLMs have demonstrated the ability to simulate believable human behavior,\nand are increasingly used as user simulators for interactive evaluation [9, 53, 68, 5, 25], synthetic\ndata generation [10, 17, 43], and reinforcement learning [69, 59]. Across these applications, initial\napproaches rely on prompting LLMs [9, 35, 36, 29, 43]. However, these prompt-based simulators\nstruggle to consistently adhere to assigned user goals or profiles, motivating recent methods that train\nLLM-based user simulators with goal-tracking or persona-consistency objectives [31, 1]. In order to\nbuild simulators that can faithfully represent real users, other works train LLMs with response-level\nsimilarity objectives, such as supervised fine-tuning on real user data [33] or aligning latent reasoning\nstates through reinforcement learning [16, 58, 63].\n\n\n**User Simulator Evaluation.** Recent works investigate how LLM-based user simulators compare\nto real users. One direction compares assistant evaluations conducted with simulators against those\nconducted with real users, finding that simulator-based evaluations are poor estimates of agent\nperformance and obscure demographic disparities [13, 48]. A second direction compares simulator\nand human behaviors at the feature level, finding systematic divergence on lexical, syntactic, and\nstylistic metrics [22, 67, 7].\n\n\nAcross both training and evaluation work, simulator fidelity is typically measured at the response or\nfeature level. While some works investigate simulating diverse user populations [28, 2, 17], ours is\nthe first to measure how well user simulators capture the distribution of real user behaviors. We do\nthis by extracting representations of user behavior that go beyond lexical or stylistic features, and\nclustering them to compare the distributions of real and simulated user behaviors.'], '2605.07905v1_chunk_47': ['16\n\n\n**CoCoReviewBench: A Completeness- and Correctness-Oriented Benchmark for AI Reviewers**\n\n\n_Table 4._ Complete taxonomy of CoCoReviewBench categories and subcategories.\n\n\n**Category** **Subcategories and Descriptions**\n\n\n**Quality** **Quality-Method** (Methodological Soundness): Evaluates whether the proposed algorithms, models, or system\narchitectures are technically correct and free of conceptual or implementation errors.\n**Quality-Experiment** (Experimental Design & Evaluation): Assesses the adequacy of the experimental setup:\nchoice of datasets, baselines, evaluation metrics, ablation studies, and statistical tests.\n**Quality-Reproducibility** (Reproducibility & Implementation Details): Considers whether the submission provides\nenough detail (e.g., hyperparameters, code availability, dataset splits) to replicate the work and whether the\nimplementation follows best practices.\n**Quality-Comparisons** (Comparisons to Prior Work): Evaluates whether the paper sufficiently compares against\nrelevant prior work and state-of-the-art methods.\n**Quality-Statistics** (Statistical Rigor & Validation): Evaluates whether statistical analyses (e.g., significance tests,\nconfidence intervals) are properly applied and whether reported improvements are statistically meaningful.\n\n\n**Clarity** **Clarity-Writing** (Writing, Terminology & Algorithm Presentation): Covers overall writing quality and organization, precision of terminology and key concepts, and the clarity of algorithm presentations (code snippets,\npseudocode, workflow diagrams).\n**Clarity-Notation** (Notation & Mathematical Explanation Clarity): Considers whether mathematical notation is\nconsistent, well defined and explained.\n**Clarity-Figure/Table** (Figures & Visual Aids Clarity): Evaluates whether figures, tables, plots, and visualizations\nare legible, properly labeled, and aid understanding.']}}}",,51.33079847908745,0.9140625,0.019723533378287257,539.2727272727273,0.0,False,0.0,0.6666666666666666,0.7894736842105263,0,0.0,0.015625,0.0,0.4960327744483948,0.6412253379821777,0.5593608021736145,-0.043208714574575424,0.2571510076522827,0.09142964333295822,4.0,True,"The candidate answer accurately describes the paper's focus on evaluating user simulators and their tasks, including the evaluation of Gemini 3.1 Pro and Llama-3.1-8B-Instruct simulators. The answer also correctly mentions the use of Nearest Neighbor Cosine Similarity and MAUVE as evaluation metrics. However, it does not fully capture the nuances of the paper's findings, particularly regarding the combination of behaviorally complementary simulators to reduce the distributional gap.",80.0,5.0,4.0,4.0,1.0,5.0
