], a dataset of one million real-world user-assistant interactions.]\nWe use the postprocessed subset from Naous et al. [33], which filters to English-only conversations,\ndeduplicates, and provides GPT-4o generated user goals G for each conversation. Each G is classified\nby task with `Qwen3.5-122B-A10B-FP8` [55] (see Appendix C). We focus on coding, where users\naim to produce functional code, and writing, where users aim to produce a written artifact. We\nsample 5,000 conversations to get D realcoding and D realwriting. To generate D simcoding and D simwriting, we provide\neach user goal G from D realcoding and D realwriting to the simulator and generate the corresponding simulated\nconversation. We use `Qwen3.5-122B-A10B` as the assistant. All prompts are provided in Appendix D.\n\n\nTo establish the lower bound, we measure the divergence between two behavioral distributions of real\nusers. For each conversation in D realcoding and D realwriting, we sample its match from a held-out WildChat\nsubset based on user-goal embedding similarity, giving us a similar conversation with a different user.', 'score': None, 'metadata': {'vertex_id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_10', 'snippets': ['2\n\n\n\n**i** son)\n\n**l** )\n\n\nP c^\n\nc cQ( ^\n\n\ncQ( ^\n\nP c^\n\n\n2\n2 2 [( ˆ] _[P]_ [ + ˆ] _[Q]_ [)][. JS divergence captures both low precision and low recall.]\n\n\n2\n\n\n\n**i** son)\n\n**l** )\n\n\nP c^\n\nc cQ( ^\n\n\ncQ( ^\n\nP c^\n\n\n2\n\n2 2\n\n\n**4** **Experimental Setup**\n\n\nWe evaluate 24 user simulators: 7 closed-source LLMs, 15 open-source LLMs, and 2 trained\nsimulators. For each user simulator, we measure the distributional gap with real users by instantiating\nreal [from real user-assistant conversations and generating the corresponding] [ D] sim [.]\n\n\nreal [is constructed from WildChat [][65][], a dataset of one million real-world user-assistant interactions.]\nWe use the postprocessed subset from Naous et al. [33], which filters to English-only conversations,\ndeduplicates, and provides GPT-4o generated user goals G for each conversation. Each G is classified\nby task with `Qwen3.5-122B-A10B-FP8` [55] (see Appendix C). We focus on coding, where users\naim to produce functional code, and writing, where users aim to produce a written artifact. We\nsample 5,000 conversations to get D realcoding and D realwriting. To generate D simcoding and D simwriting, we provide\neach user goal G from D realcoding and D realwriting to the simulator and generate the corresponding simulated\nconversation. We use `Qwen3.5-122B-A10B` as the assistant. All prompts are provided in Appendix D.\n\n\nTo establish the lower bound, we measure the divergence between two behavioral distributions of real\nusers. For each conversation in D realcoding and D realwriting, we sample its match from a held-out WildChat\nsubset based on user-goal embedding similarity, giving us a similar conversation with a different user.']}}, {'id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_15', 'title': '2605.07847v1_chunk_15', 'snippet': '**Clustering Algorithms.** We obtain discrete distributions of user behavior by clustering our embeddings using _k_ -means with _k_ = 500. To verify that our method is robust to the clustering algorithm,\nwe repeat our experiments using Gaussian Mixture Models and Agglomerative Clustering. Similar\nto the embedding model ablation, we compute the Spearman rank correlations between simulator\nrankings produced by each pair of clustering algorithms. Our results in Table 2 demonstrate that\nsimulator rankings are nearly identical across all pairs ( _ρ_ � 0 _._ 96 ), and scatter plot visualizations are\nprovided in Figure 15 (Appendix G).\n\n\n6\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_6)\n\n�\n\n\n**-en** 3Emb **d** Qwig8B **-l** sma\n\n**-en** 3Emb **d** Qwig8B **-e** 5\n\n**-l** BGEsmaenv1.5 **-e** 5\n\n\nK-Means **a** u **s**\n\nK-Means lom **eg**\n\nG **a** u **s** lom **eg**\n\n\n�\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_7)\n\n**a** **ist** **s**\n\n\n\nFigure 3: Pairwise Jensen–Shannon divergence between the behavior distributions of 24 user simulators across coding (lower triangle) and writing tasks (upper triangle), ordered by descending mean\npairwise JS divergence. Many simulators demonstrate similar behavioral distributions (lighter cells)\nwhile a few stand out (darker cells).\n\n\n**6.3** **Linear Classification**', 'score': None, 'metadata': {'vertex_id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_15', 'snippets': ['**Clustering Algorithms.** We obtain discrete distributions of user behavior by clustering our embeddings using _k_ -means with _k_ = 500. To verify that our method is robust to the clustering algorithm,\nwe repeat our experiments using Gaussian Mixture Models and Agglomerative Clustering. Similar\nto the embedding model ablation, we compute the Spearman rank correlations between simulator\nrankings produced by each pair of clustering algorithms. Our results in Table 2 demonstrate that\nsimulator rankings are nearly identical across all pairs ( _ρ_ � 0 _._ 96 ), and scatter plot visualizations are\nprovided in Figure 15 (Appendix G).\n\n\n6\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_6)\n\n�\n\n\n**-en** 3Emb **d** Qwig8B **-l** sma\n\n**-en** 3Emb **d** Qwig8B **-e** 5\n\n**-l** BGEsmaenv1.5 **-e** 5\n\n\nK-Means **a** u **s**\n\nK-Means lom **eg**\n\nG **a** u **s** lom **eg**\n\n\n�\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_7)\n\n**a** **ist** **s**\n\n\n\nFigure 3: Pairwise Jensen–Shannon divergence between the behavior distributions of 24 user simulators across coding (lower triangle) and writing tasks (upper triangle), ordered by descending mean\npairwise JS divergence. Many simulators demonstrate similar behavioral distributions (lighter cells)\nwhile a few stand out (darker cells).\n\n\n**6.3** **Linear Classification**']}}]","['GraphRAG Candidate', 'GraphRAG Candidate', 'GraphRAG Candidate', 'GraphRAG Candidate', 'GraphRAG Candidate', '2605.07847v1_chunk_3', '2605.07847v1_chunk_35', '2605.07847v1_chunk_17', '2605.07847v1_chunk_33', '2605.07847v1_chunk_9', '2605.07847v1_chunk_5', '2605.07847v1_chunk_18', '2605.07847v1_chunk_4', '2605.07847v1_chunk_16', '2605.07847v1_chunk_8', '2605.07847v1_chunk_34', '2605.07847v1_chunk_10', '2605.07847v1_chunk_15']",10,6349,114,124,54974.19112999978,0.16008600050554378,0.0,54974.3518690002,graph,18,0.0,"{'response': 'Paper 2605.07847v1 states that most LLM-based user simulators behave similarly, while a few stand apart when compared to real users across coding and writing tasks. The pairwise comparisons reveal significant distributional gaps from real users, but combining behaviorally complementary simulators can bring the resulting distribution closer to real users than either simulator on its own. Additionally, the paper notes that some simulators exhibit distinct behaviors from others, with `UserLM-8b` having the highest mean pairwise Jensen–Shannon divergence of 0.41 and `GPT-5.4 mini` following closely with a score of 0.33. The divergences are higher for writing than coding tasks. Furthermore, combining simulators with distinct behaviors improves performance on writing tasks while remaining competitive in coding tasks.', 'retrieved': [{'candidate_answer': 'Paper 2605.07847v1 states that most LLM-based user simulators behave similarly, while a few stand apart when compared to real users across coding and writing tasks. The pairwise comparisons reveal significant distributional gaps from real users, but combining behaviorally complementary simulators can bring the resulting distribution closer to real users than either simulator on its own.', 'score': 100}, {'candidate_answer': ""Paper 2605.07847v1 discusses the similarities among simulator families by comparing their representations of user behavior to real users. The study uses a method that extracts and quantizes behavioral distributions from both real and simulated conversations using k-means clustering. It highlights that 'Gemini 3.1 Pro' simulates behaviors more closely resembling those of real users compared to 'Llama-3.1-8B-Instruct'."", 'score': 95}, {'candidate_answer': 'Paper 2605.07847v1 discusses the similarities among simulator families by analyzing the distributional gap between real and simulated user behaviors when combining pairs of simulators for coding and writing tasks. The paper reports forward KL divergence (KL), backward KL divergence (KL bwd), and Jensen–Shannon divergence (JS) across these tasks, indicating that some simulators exhibit distinct behaviors from others. Specifically, the paper notes that `UserLM-8b` has the highest mean pairwise JS score of 0.41, followed by `GPT-5.4 mini` with a score of 0.33. The divergences are higher for writing than coding tasks.', 'score': 95}, {'candidate_answer': 'Paper 2605.07847v1 suggests that combining behaviorally complementary simulators can reduce the distributional gap to real users, which is conceptually similar to mixture-of-experts and assistant-side routing strategies. The paper also notes that pairing simulators with distinct behaviors improves performance on writing tasks while remaining competitive in coding tasks.', 'score': 95}, {'candidate_answer': 'Paper 2605.07847v1 states that many simulators behave similarly to each other, with 30% of the pairwise comparisons having a JS divergence less than 0.10. Simulators from the same family tend to be the most similar, achieving the lowest scores in the dataset. The simulators with the lowest mean pairwise JS scores are `Qwen3.5-122B-A10B` (0.14).', 'score': 95}], 'verbose': {'selected_set': [{'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_35', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_10', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_16', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_34', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_9', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_33', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_5', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_18', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_17', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_4', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_8', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_15', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_3', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}], 'start_set': [{'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_18', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_10', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_35', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_5', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_17', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}], 'final_retrieval': {'2605.07847v1_chunk_3': ['![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_2)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n||||\n|---|---|---|\n|Qu|a|ntiz|\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_3)\n\nFigure 1: Our method extracts representations of user behavior from real and simulated conversations, then quantizes them via _k_ -means to get discrete behavioral distributions for real ( _P_ [ˆ] ) and\nsimulated users ( _Q_ [ˆ] ). UMAP projections [30] and first principal component histograms illustrate the\ndistributional gap for two simulators on the coding task: `Gemini 3.1 Pro` overlaps real users more\nclosely compared to `Llama-3.1-8B-Instruct` .\n\n\nPreprint.\n\n\n**1** **Introduction**\n\n\nThe role of user simulators is to model the diverse behaviors of real users, providing a scalable\nmeans to train and evaluate AI systems on the interactions that they encounter in real-world settings\n\n[26, 14, 39, 45]. Recent works build user simulators by training Large Language Models (LLMs)\nto generate responses that resemble those of real users [33, 16, 58]. Yet real users exhibit a broad,\nheterogeneous distribution of behaviors [65, 66, 28]. For example, some users tend to underspecify\ntheir requests, while others fully specify every constraint. The extent to which user simulators capture\nthis distribution has not been measured.\n\n\nA user simulator can fail to capture the distribution of real users in two ways: by demonstrating\nbehaviors that real users rarely exhibit (low prec **i** son), or by failing to demonstrate behaviors that real\nusers do exhibit (low reca **l** ), mirroring precision and recall metrics for generative models [ 46, 23, 11].\nThese failure modes bias training and evaluation, and yield assistants that struggle to generalize to\nthe diverse behaviors of real users [52].'], '2605.07847v1_chunk_35': ['Figure 13: User simulator system prompt for conversation generation.\n\n\n23\n\n\n**E** **Results for Each User Behavior Facet**\n\n\nIn addition to the metrics defined in Section 3, all results in the Appendix include two complementary\nmetrics:\n\n\n - **Nearest Neighbor Cosine Similarity:** The average cosine similarity between each real user and\nits nearest neighbor in the simulated set. Higher values indicate that simulated behaviors are closer\nto real ones in the embedding space. This metric is computed directly on the embeddings.\n\n\nˆ ˆ\n\n - **MAUVE:** Compares _P_ and _Q_ usingˆ divergence frontiers [41]. The mixture\nf (exp(distribution � _c_ KL( _RQ_ ˆ k _R_ � =)) _,_ exp( _λP_ [ˆ] + (1 � _c_ KL( � _P_ ˆ _λ_ k _R_ ) � _Q_ )))yields _, λ_ (0the _,_ 1) divergence. The MAUVE score is thecurve C ( _P,_ [ˆ] _Q_ [ˆ] ) =\narea under this curve, which captures both failure modes. Higher values indicate better alignment\nbetween real and simulated users. We clarify that we apply the divergence-frontier formulation of\nPillutla et al. [41], not the off-the-shelf text-generation metric.\n\n\nTable 4: Requests facet results. The distributional gap between real and simulated user behaviors\nacross coding and writing tasks. We compare the distribution of user behaviors demonstrated in D real\nwith those in D sim [.] [ ""] [ indicates hi][g][her is better and] [ #] [ indicates lower is better.]\n\n\n**Coding** **Writing**\n\n\n**User Simulator** NN "" KL fwd KL bwd MAU "" JS # NN "" KL KL bwd MAU "" JS #\n\n\nReal U **s** .826 .034 .035 .924 .039 .888 .024 .025 .955 .029\n\n\nd-SurcCl **o** s **e**\n\n\n`GPT-5.4` 0.815 0.164 0.175 0.437 0.163 0.862 0.337 0.355 0.111 0.330\n\n`GPT-5.4 mini` 0.810 0.219 0.245 0.260 0.229 0.863 0.295 0.308 0.151 0.294\n\n`GPT-5.4 nano` 0.804 0.269 0.291 0.198 0.262 0.855 0.396 0.420 0.065 0.392\n\n`Claude Haiku 4.5` 0.798 0.293 0.289 0.171 0.279 0.831 0.513 0.521 0.022 0.512\n\n`Gemini 3.1 Pro` 0.820 0.131 0.134 0.570 0.126 0.858 0.376 0.372 0.090 0.354\n\n`Gemini 3 Flash` 0.808 0.228 0.211 0.308 0.208 0.844 0.466 0.462 0.043 0.436'], '2605.07847v1_chunk_17': ['7\n\n\nTable 3: The distributional gap between real and simulated user behaviors when combining pairs\nof simulators. When generating conversations, we randomly sample which LLM serves as the\nuser simulator. We report forward KL divergence (KL ), backward KL divergence (KL bwd ), and\nJensen–Shannon divergence (JS) across coding and writing tasks. "" indicates higher is better and #\nindicates lower is better. Darker blue indicates closer behavioral distribution to real users. Subscripts\nshow the change relative to the better of the two individual simulators\n\n\n**Coding** **Writing**\n\n\n**User Simulator** KL KL bwd JS # KL KL bwd JS #\n\n\n: : : : : :\n\n\n**el** **s** ed **al** ucinted\n\n\n**el** **s**\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_8)\n\n: : : : : :\n\n\n**el** **s** ed **al** ucinted\n\n\n**el** **s**\n\n\n\n: : : : : :\n\n\n**el** **s** ed **al** ucinted\n\n\n**el** **s**\n\n\n\n`gemma-4-31B-it` + `Claude Haiku 4.5` .364 _↑_ : .345 _↑_ : .346 _↑_ : .562 _↑_ : .568 _↑_ : .572 _↑_ :\n\n\n`gemma-4-26B-A4B-it` (0 _._ 15), `gemma-4-E2B-it` (0 _._ 15), and `Qwen3.5-35B-A3B` (0 _._ 15). A few\nsimulators stand out and demonstrate behaviors that diverge from the rest. These include `UserLM-8b`,\nwhich has the highest mean pairwise JS score of 0 _._ 41, followed by `GPT-5.4 mini` with a score of\n0 _._ 33. Pairwise JS scores are consistently higher for writing than coding, which aligns with our main\nresults, where the divergences from real users were also higher for writing.\n\n\n**7.2** **Can we Combine User Simulators to Reduce the Gap With Real Users?**\n\n\nSince our pairwise analysis shows that some user simulators behave distinctly from each other, we\ntest whether combining pairs can reduce the gap to real users by randomly sampling which simulator\ngenerates each conversation. Table 3 reports the results.'], '2605.07847v1_chunk_33': ['Through a human study and a series of validation experiments, we confirm that our method captures\nmeaningful behavioral distributions and is robust to the choice of embedding model and clustering\nalgorithm. We would like acknowledge, however, that our approach relies on a capable LLM\n(Qwen3.5-122B-A10B-FP8) to analyze conversations and generate accurate descriptions of user\nbehavior.\n\n\nIn our work, we describe that user simulators can fail to capture the distribution of real users when\nthey either demonstrate behaviors that real users rarely exhibit, or when they don’t demonstrate\nbehaviors that real users do exhibit. However, in some cases this is actually desirable. For example,\nwhen user simulators are used to stress-test assistants against rare or adversarial user inputs that\nthe real-world data does not capture well. We do not distinguish between desirable and undesirable\ndivergence, and leave this for future work. Lastly, our work focuses more on intrinsic analysis, and\ndoes not measure how user simulator distributional gaps affect downstream training or evaluation for\nassistants.\n\n\nUser simulators serve an important role in the development process of AI systems, often being\nused during training or evaluation. When simulators underrepresent the behaviors of certain user\npopulations, these assistant may fail to serve those users well, and the burden of this failure falls on\nthe populations whose behaviors are underrepresented. Closing this distributional gap is therefore\nimportant for building AI systems that work for users all over the world, including different cultures,\nlanguages, and demographics. Beyond this, high-fidelity user simulators raise dual-use concerns and\ncan be misused to impersonate real users or create fake users for unwanted purposes. Addressing\nthese limitations is important for advancing user simulators that faithfully represent real users and\nsupport the responsible development of AI systems.\n\n\n15\n\n\n**B** **User Behavior Representation Prompts**\n\n\n**es** tqu'], '2605.07847v1_chunk_9': ['3\n\n\n**Step 3: Measuring the Distributional Gap**\n\n\nGiven _P_ [ˆ] and _Q_ [ˆ], we measure the gap between the behavioral distributions to understand how well\nthe user simulator represents real users. The simulator can diverge from real users in two ways: by\ndemonstrating behaviors that real users rarely exhibit (low prec **i** son) or by failing to demonstrate\nbehaviors that real users do exhibit (low reca **l** ), mirroring precision and recall metrics in generative\nmodeling [46, 23, 11]. Formally, low precision arises when _Q_ [ˆ] assigns high probability to behaviors\nthat are rare under _P_ [ˆ], while low recall arises when _Q_ [ˆ] assigns low probability to behaviors that are\ncommon under _P_ [ˆ] . This formulation captures the intuitions of bias and variance in simulator behavior:\nreductions in behavioral variance manifest as low recall, and excess variance into behaviors real users\ndo not exhibit manifests as low precision. We report the following metrics:\n\n\n - **Forward KL Divergence:** Defined as KL( _P_ [ˆ] k _Q_ ˆ) = c _[P]_ [ˆ][(] _[c]_ [) log] cQ(P (c^^ . Higher values indicate\n\nlow recall, meaning the simulator fails to demonstrate behaviors that real users exhibit.\n\n - **Backward KL Divergence:** Defined as KL( _Q_ [ˆ] k _P_ ˆ) = _Q_ ˆ( _c_ ) log cQ(P (c^^ . Higher values indicate\n\nlow precision, meaning the simulator demonstrates behaviors that real users do not exhibit.\n\n\n2\n\n2 2\n\n\n2\n\n\n\n**i** son)\n\n**l** )\n\n\nP c^\n\nc cQ( ^\n\n\ncQ( ^\n\nP c^\n\n\n- **Jensen–Shannon Divergence:** A symmetric divergence defined as JS( _P,_ [ˆ] _Q_ [ˆ] ) = 2\n\n\n2 2\n\n\n2\n\n\n\n**i** son)\n\n**l** )\n\n\nP c^\n\nc cQ( ^\n\n\ncQ( ^\n\nP c^\n\n\n**Jensen–Shannon Divergence:** 2 [KL( ˆ] _[Q]_ [ k] _M_ ˆ ), where _M_ [ˆ] = 2 [( ˆ] _[P]_ A symmetric divergence defined as [ + ˆ] _[Q]_ [)][. JS divergence captures both low precision and low recall.] JS( _P,_ [ˆ] _Q_ [ˆ] ) = 2 [KL( ˆ] _[P]_ [ k] _M_ ˆ ) +\n\n\n2\n\n\n\n**i** son)\n\n**l** )\n\n\nP c^\n\nc cQ( ^\n\n\ncQ( ^\n\nP c^'], '2605.07847v1_chunk_5': ['Our work advances toward user simulators that faithfully represent the diversity of real users with the\nfollowing contributions: (1) We introduce a method for measuring the distributional gap between\nreal and simulated user behaviors, validated through a human study and ablations; (2) Our analysis\nof 7 closed-source LLMs, 15 open-source LLMs and 2 trained simulators on coding and writing\ntasks reveals a large distributional gap from real users that varies across model families, scales, and\nbehavioral facets; (3) We show that combining behaviorally complementary simulators brings the\nresulting distribution closer to real users than either simulator on its own; (4) We present a TF-IDF\nanalysis of behavior clusters that surfaces interpretable insights into behaviors that simulators capture,\nmiss, and hallucinate.\n\n\n**2** **Problem Formulation**\n\n\nIn this section, we formalize the problem of evaluating how well a user simulator captures the\ndistribution of real user behaviors. Let _P_ denote the distribution of real user behaviors, and _Q_ denote\nthe distribution of simulated user behaviors. Our objective is to measure the gap between _P_ and _Q_ .\n\n\nIn practice, _P_ and _Q_ are not directly observable. Instead, we access them through datasets of\nconversations, where each conversation is a sequence C n = ( _u_ 1 _, a_ 1 _, . . ., u_ n _, a_ n ), with _u_ i and _a_\ndenoting the user and assistant utterances at turn _i_ . We use D real [, a dataset of real user-assistant]\nconversations, as samples from _P_ .'], '2605.07847v1_chunk_18': ['First, we pair the simulators with the smallest distributional gap to real users: `Gemini 3.1 Pro` with\n`GPT-5.4`, and `gpt-oss-120b` with `gemma-4-31B-it` . Both pairs achieve smaller JS divergence\nthan either individual simulator on coding and writing. Next, we pair simulators that are behaviorally\ndistinct from others, `UserLM-8b` and `GPT-5.4 mini`, with each of `Gemini 3.1 Pro`, `GPT-5.4`,\n`gemma-4-31B-it`, and `gpt-oss-120b` . These improve over the individual simulators on writing\nand remain competitive on coding. Conversely, combining behaviorally similar simulators, such as\n`gemma-4-31B-it` and `Claude Haiku 4.5`, does not help.\n\n\nThese results suggest that combining behaviorally complementary simulators can reduce the distributional gap to real users. This combination strategy is conceptually similar to mixture-of-experts\n\n[49, 15] and assistant-side routing [37, 56, 34], and learning a router that selects the appropriate\nsimulator is a natural extension we leave to future work.\n\n\n**7.3** **Interpreting the Behavioral Clusters**\n\n\nFigure 4: Word clouds of w-capturd (green), **el** mi **s** ed (blue), and h **al** ucinted (red) behaviors for\n`Gemini 3.1 Pro` on coding based on a TF-IDF analysis on behavioral clusters.\n\n\nThe behavioral distributions reveal not only how much simulators diverge from real users, but which\nbehaviors they capture, miss, or hallucinate. We classify each cluster by the ratio of real to simulated\nconversations into three categories: w-capturd if real and simulated are roughly balanced, **el** mi **s**\n\n\n8\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_9)\n\n: : : : : :\n\n\n**el** **s** ed **al** ucinted\n\n\n**el** **s**'], '2605.07847v1_chunk_4': ['We introduce a method to compare the distributions of user behaviors in real and simulated conversations, illustrated in Figure 1. For each conversation, we extract a representation of the user’s\nbehavior by using an LLM to generate a description along six behavioral facets (such as how they\nmake requests or what dialog acts they perform) and then embedding it into a shared semantic space.\nNext, we quantize these representations into discrete distributions over user behavior modes by\nclustering [46, 41]. Finally, we measure the gap between the real and simulated distributions using\ndivergence-based metrics. We confirm that our method captures meaningful behavioral distributions\nand is robust to the choice of embedding model and clustering algorithm through a human study and\nvalidation studies.\n\n\nWe provide the first systematic evaluation of 24 LLM-based user simulators across coding and writing\ntasks, including 7 closed-source LLMs, 15 open-source LLMs, and 2 trained simulators. Our results\nreveal a large distributional gap from real users, and surface insights across model families, scales, and\nbehavioral facets. Pairwise comparisons between simulators show that most behave similarly, while a\nfew stand apart. Combining behaviorally complementary simulators brings the resulting distribution\ncloser to real users than either simulator on its own. Lastly, a TF-IDF analysis of the clusters provides\ninterpretable insights into behaviors that user simulators capture, miss, and hallucinate.'], '2605.07847v1_chunk_16': ['**6.3** **Linear Classification**\n\n\nWe validate that our user behavior representation embeddings encode meaningful differences between\nreal and simulated users by training a linear classifier. For each simulator, we construct a dataset\nof 5,000 real and 5,000 simulated embeddings, and then train an L2-regularized logistic regression\nclassifier to classify embeddings as real or simulated. We average results over 5 stratified random\n80/20 train-test splits. The classification accuracies across simulators are consistently high, ranging\nfrom 90.92% to 99.63%, and also correlate strongly with our distributional metrics (Figure 2). This\nconfirms that the embeddings encode meaningful differences between real and simulated users. The\nfull accuracy scores and correlations for all metrics are presented in Appendix H.\n\n\n**7** **Discussion**\n\n\n**7.1** **How Do User Behavior Distributions Compare Among Simulators?**\n\n\nOur main results show that the distributional gap to real users varies across simulators. This raises a\nnatural question: how do the behviorl d **a** rbuon of user **ist** imulator compare to each other? **s** To\ninvestigate this, we pool the user behavior representations across all 24 simulators, quantize them\ninto distributions, and compute the JS divergence between all pairs. Figure 3 reports the results.\n\n\nMany simulators behave similarly to each other: 30% of the 552 pairwise comparisons have JS _<_\n0 _._ 10. Pairs from the same family tend to be the most similar, achieving the lowest scores in the\ndataset. The simulators with the lowest mean pairwise JS scores are `Qwen3.5-122B-A10B` (0 _._ 14),\n\n\n7'], '2605.07847v1_chunk_8': ['These behavioral facets abstract away irrelevant features, enabling our comparisons to focus on\nbehavioral patterns rather than surface-level signals such as lexical similarity. The full prompts and\ncriteria are provided in Appendix B.\n\n\nFor each conversation, we concatenate descriptions across all six facets into a single textual representation of user behavior. Then, we embed each representation with a text embedding model, mapping\nbehaviors from D real [and] [ D] sim [into a shared semantic space. As Pimentel et al.][ [42]][ show, embeddings]\ncapture discourse- and coherence-level features while ignoring surface-level ones, making them\nwell-suited for representing user behaviors.\n\n\n**Step 2: Quantizing into Behavioral Distributions**\n\n\nThe user behavior representations for D real [and] [ D] sim [are finite sets of continuous, high-dimensional]\nvectors. This makes estimating divergences unreliable. Following the precision and recall framework\nof Sajjadi et al. [46] and the MAUVE methodology of Pillutla et al. [41], we employ a quantization\nstep to map the representations into low-dimensional discrete distributions of behaviors. We apply\n_k_ -means clustering to the set of user behavior representations from D real [and] [ D] sim [. Each of the] _[ k]_\nclusters groups representations with similar behavioral patterns, and thus represents a particular mode\nof user behavior. We obtain probability distributions _P_ [ˆ] and _Q_ [ˆ] over _c_ 2 f 1 _, . . ., k_, where _P_ [ˆ] ( _c_ )\nand _Q_ [ˆ] ( _c_ ) denote the fraction of representations from D real [and] [ D] sim [in cluster] _[ c]_ [. These distributions]\ncapture how frequently different user behavior modes occur in real and simulated conversations, and\nserve as estimates of _P_ and _Q_ .\n\n\n3\n\n\n**Step 3: Measuring the Distributional Gap**'], '2605.07847v1_chunk_34': ['15\n\n\n**B** **User Behavior Representation Prompts**\n\n\n**es** tqu\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_10)\n\n**es** tqu\n\n\n\n**es** tqu\n\n\n\nFigure 5: Prompt for extracting user behavior representations along the R facet. **es** tqu\n\n\n16\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_11)\n\n**es** pon\n\n\n\n**es** pon\n\n\n\n**es** pon\n\n\n\nFigure 6: Prompt for extracting user behavior representations along the R facet. **es** pon\n\n\n17\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_12)\n\n**t**\n\n\n\n**t**\n\n\n\nFigure 7: Prompt for extracting user behavior representations along the Con facet. ex **t**\