favor-006,What does the linear classification experiment in paper 2605.07847v1 show?,"The linear classification experiment shows that the user behavior representation embeddings capture meaningful differences between real and simulated users. Logistic regression classifiers achieve high accuracies, roughly from about 90.9 percent to 99.6 percent, and those accuracies correlate strongly with the paper's distributional metrics.",lookup,medium,['2605.07847v1'],graphrag,"The linear classification experiment in paper 2605.07847v1 shows that there are diminishing returns when increasing the value of K, which represents the number of guidance steps during inference. The largest improvement is observed with _K_ =2, reducing LLaMA-3 8B PPL by 23% relative to no guidance (from 115.9 to 88.7). Each subsequent increase in _K_ yields smaller gains, confirming that _K_ =5 is an effective default.","Yes, the paper fully discloses all the information needed to reproduce the experimental results of the paper throughout Sections 3, 4, 6, and 7, and Appendix B, C, and D. Additionally, our code has been released to ensure our experiments are easily reproducible.

The linear classification experiment in paper 2605.07847v1 shows that there are diminishing returns when increasing the value of K, which represents the number of guidance steps during inference. The largest improvement is observed with _K_ =2, reducing LLaMA-3 8B PPL by 23% relative to no guidance (from 115.9 to 88.7). Each subsequent increase in _K_ yields smaller gains, confirming that _K_ =5 is an effective default.

The linear classification experiment in paper 2605.07847v1 shows that using a time threshold τ = 0.02 instead of τ = 0 ensures that at least approximately 2% of positions carry revealed tokens before the energy compass is invoked, providing a minimal but nonzero signal for candidate comparison while avoiding numerical edge cases related to early flow times where CTMC transition rates can produce numerical instabilities.

The linear classification experiment in paper 2605.07847v1 shows that midpoint diversity decays gradually rather than collapsing abruptly, with independent completions differing at approximately 147 out of 1,024 token positions (14.4% edit distance) when _t_ mid=0.2—the activation threshold used in the main experiments. This means that K =5 candidates generated from the same midpoint will present genuinely different options at around 100–150 positions, providing meaningful material for selection by the energy compass.

The linear classification experiment in paper 2605.07847v1 shows that the TS-DFM (Trajectory Shaping Data-Free Model) method outperforms FS-DFM (Free-Shaped Data-Free Model) as the scale of the student model increases. Specifically, at 1.3B parameters, TS-DFM with just 8 steps achieves a GPT-2 Large PPL reduction of 41% compared to FS-DFM’s 81.5, which is larger than the 36% reduction observed at 170M parameters. Additionally, TS-DFM consistently outperforms the full-step DFM teacher across all step counts and model sizes, being significantly faster while maintaining or improving quality.

