ation accuracies across different simulators indicate that these embeddings effectively capture meaningful differences in user behavior. This process helps in understanding how similar or distinct the behaviors generated by various simulators are compared to each other and to real users.', 'score': 95.0, 'metadata': {'candidate_answer': 'Combining simulators can help by allowing the validation of user behavior representation embeddings. By constructing datasets from both real and simulated embeddings, linear classifiers are trained to distinguish between them. The high classification accuracies across different simulators indicate that these embeddings effectively capture meaningful differences in user behavior. This process helps in understanding how similar or distinct the behaviors generated by various simulators are compared to each other and to real users.', 'score': 95}}, {'id': 'retrieved-4', 'title': 'GraphRAG Candidate', 'snippet': 'Combining simulators, as discussed in paper [28], can help by leveraging multiple user simulators to train task-oriented dialogue systems. This approach allows for a more diverse and realistic interaction experience, which is crucial for improving the performance of such systems.', 'score': 95.0, 'metadata': {'candidate_answer': 'Combining simulators, as discussed in paper [28], can help by leveraging multiple user simulators to train task-oriented dialogue systems. This approach allows for a more diverse and realistic interaction experience, which is crucial for improving the performance of such systems.', 'score': 95}}, {'id': 'retrieved-5', 'title': 'GraphRAG Candidate', 'snippet': 'Combining simulators can help reduce the gap between real and simulated user behaviors according to paper 2605.07847v1. By randomly sampling which LLM serves as the user simulator for generating conversations, the study reports that forward KL divergence (KL), backward KL divergence (KL bwd), and Jensen–Shannon divergence (JS) across coding and writing tasks show improvements when combining certain simulators. For instance, the combination of `gemma-4-31B-it` and `Claude Haiku 4.5` shows significant reductions in JS scores for both coding and writing tasks.', 'score': 90.0, 'metadata': {'candidate_answer': 'Combining simulators can help reduce the gap between real and simulated user behaviors according to paper 2605.07847v1. By randomly sampling which LLM serves as the user simulator for generating conversations, the study reports that forward KL divergence (KL), backward KL divergence (KL bwd), and Jensen–Shannon divergence (JS) across coding and writing tasks show improvements when combining certain simulators. For instance, the combination of `gemma-4-31B-it` and `Claude Haiku 4.5` shows significant reductions in JS scores for both coding and writing tasks.', 'score': 90}}, {'id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_24', 'title': '2605.07847v1_chunk_24', 'snippet': ""10\n\n\n[18] Grosz, B. J. and Sidner, C. L. (1986). Attention, intentions, and the structure of discourse.\ninl lC **ota** mpu **is** tc, 12(3):175–204. ngu\n\n\n[19] Henderson, M., Thomson, B., and Williams, J. D. (2014). The second dialog state tracking\nchallenge. In Georgila, K., Stone, M., Hastie, H., and Nenkova, A., editors, Proc **e** dings of the\n15th A **n** ual M **e** ting of the Special Inrs Group on Di **te** coure and Dialogue (S **s** **I** GDAL), pages\n263–272, Philadelphia, PA, U.S.A. Association for Computational Linguistics.\n\n\n[20] Hoang, N. K., Mehri, S., Hsu, T.-A., Sun, Y.-J., Truong, Q. X. N., Doan, K. D., and Hakkani-Tür,\nD. (2026). Psi-bench: Towards clinically grounded and interpretable evaluation of depression\npatient simulators.\n\n\n[21] Horvitz, E. (1999). Principles of mixed-initiative user interfaces. In Proc **e** dings of the S **I**\nr on Human Factors in Computing Sy **n** f **c** o **e** **s** tem, pages 159–166.\n\n\n[22] Ivey, J., Kumar, S., Liu, J., Shen, H., Rakshit, S., Raju, R., Zhang, H., Ananthasubramaniam