According to paper 2605.07847v1, measuring the distributional gap is important because it directly quantifies how many token positions are affected by stochastic jumps—the 'material' available to the energy compass for candidate selection. This metric complements token agreement by revealing the distribution of disagreement: positions with low agreement are where stochastic jumps are genuinely uncertain, and where the token refinement phase must decide whether to intervene.

