section 4.1 describes the energy compass’s role, training objective, and key design choices. This section
provides the full training specification, including the objective decomposition, negative construction details,
source-distribution handling, and optimization configuration.


We train a separate energy compass for each source family: one for the _uniform_ source distribution ( _x_ 0
sampled uniformly over _V_ ) and one for the _mask_ source distribution ( _x_ 0 = [Mask] _[L]_ ). The two compasses
share identical architecture and training procedure (tables 6 and 8); they differ only in the source tokens that
populate unrevealed positions during positive and negative construction. All validation results in appendix B
are reported for both variants where applicable.


**A.1** **Architecture**



The energy compass is a transformer encoder with attention pooling that maps a token sequence to a scalar energy. It shares the same tokenizer (GPT-2, _|V|_ =50 257)
and block size ( _L_ =1 024) as the velocity model but is
substantially smaller (table 6). The lack of time conditioning is a deliberate design choice: the compass
scores intrinsic sequence quality, not quality-relative-totimestep. In place of a time embedding, the model uses
a learned constant buffer, ensuring the architecture is
identical to a time-conditioned variant (for checkpoint
compatibility) but receives no time information.


