favor-009,What evidence does paper 2605.07847v1 provide that some simulators are closer to real users than others?,"The paper shows through divergence-based metrics and visualization of clustered behavior distributions that the gap to real users varies across simulators. For example, the provided discussion notes that Gemini 3.1 Pro overlaps more closely with real users than Llama-3.1-8B-Instruct on the coding task.",comparison,medium,['2605.07847v1'],basic-rag,"The paper provides evidence through several analyses indicating that some simulators are closer to real users than others. Specifically, it compares simulator-based evaluations against those conducted with real users and finds that simulator-based evaluations are poor estimates of agent performance and obscure demographic disparities [13, 48]. Additionally, the paper analyzes simulator and human behaviors at the feature level, revealing systematic divergence on lexical, syntactic, and stylistic metrics [22, 67, 7]. Furthermore, a distributional gap between real user behaviors and those of simulators is quantified across coding and writing tasks. The authors combine pairs of behaviorally complementary simulators to reduce this gap, suggesting that certain combinations perform better in capturing real user behaviors.

