n one task. However, this similarity is attributed to surface-level features such as lexical and semantic overlap rather than reflecting true behavioral patterns. In contrast, the behavioral descriptions reveal much larger and more meaningful gaps, confirming that this step is necessary for accurately representing user behavior.

Paper 2605.07847v1 provides evidence that some simulators are closer to real users than others by analyzing the behavior descriptions of simulated and real user interactions in a coding task using TF-IDF scores. The analysis reveals distinct categories: W-captured terms reflect iterative problem-solving behaviors, Mi terms indicate behaviors not reproduced by the simulator such as terse communication and authoritative directives, while H-alucinted terms show overly enthusiastic behaviors. This differentiation suggests that simulators with more Mi terms are closer to real users because they better capture nuanced and transactional exchanges.

The paper provides evidence that some simulators are closer to real users than others by revealing a large distributional gap from real users that varies across model families, scales, and behavioral facets. Pairwise comparisons show that most simulators behave similarly, while a few stand apart. Combining behaviorally complementary simulators brings the resulting distribution closer to real users compared to either simulator on its own.

Paper 2605.07847v1 provides evidence that some simulators are closer to real users than others by quantizing representations of user behavior from both real and simulated conversations using k-means clustering. The UMAP projections and first principal component histograms illustrate the distributional gap between two specific simulators: `Gemini 3.1 Pro` overlaps more closely with real users compared to `Llama-3.1-8B-Instruct`. This indicates that `Gemini 3.1 Pro` better captures the diverse behaviors of real users, while `Llama-3.1-8B-Instruct` falls short in this aspect.

The paper provides evidence that some simulators are closer to real users than others by comparing the distributional gaps between user behavior representations of different simulators and real users. Specifically, it uses Jensen-Shannon (JS) divergence to measure the similarity between these distributions. Simulators with lower mean pairwise JS scores indicate a closer match to real user behavior. For instance, `Qwen3.5-122B-A10B` has one of the lowest mean pairwise JS scores at 0.14, suggesting it is more similar to real users compared to other simulators.

We introduce a method to compare the distributions of user behaviors in real and simulated conversations, illustrated in Figure 1. For each conversation, we extract a representation of the user’s
behavior by using an LLM to generate a description along six behavioral facets (such as how they
make requests or what dialog acts they perform) and then embedding it into a shared semantic space.
Next, we quantize these representations into discrete distributions over user behavior modes by
clustering [46, 41]. Finally, we measure the gap between the real and simulated distributions using
divergence-based metrics. We confirm that our method captures meaningful behavioral distributions
and is robust to the choice of embedding model and clustering algorithm through a human study and
validation studies.


We provide the first systematic evaluation of 24 LLM-based user simulators across coding and writing
tasks, including 7 closed-source LLMs, 15 open-source LLMs, and 2 trained simulators. Our results
reveal a large distributional gap from real users, and surface insights across model families, scales, and
behavioral facets. Pairwise comparisons between simulators show that most behave similarly, while a
few stand apart. Combining behaviorally complementary simulators brings the resulting distribution
closer to real users than either simulator on its own. Lastly, a TF-IDF analysis of the clusters provides
interpretable insights into behaviors that user simulators capture, miss, and hallucinate.

**Clustering Algorithms.** We obtain discrete distributions of user behavior by clustering our embeddings using _k_ -means with _k_ = 500. To verify that our method is robust to the clustering algorithm,
we repeat our experiments using Gaussian Mixture Models and Agglomerative Clustering. Similar
to the embedding model ablation, we compute the Spearman rank correlations between simulator
rankings produced by each pair of clustering algorithms. Our results in Table 2 demonstrate that
simulator rankings are nearly identical across all pairs ( _ρ_ � 0 _._ 96 ), and scatter plot visualizations are
provided in Figure 15 (Appendix G).


