 resulting distribution\ncloser to real users than either simulator on its own. Lastly, a TF-IDF analysis of the clusters provides\ninterpretable insights into behaviors that user simulators capture, miss, and hallucinate.', 'score': None, 'metadata': {'vertex_id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_4', 'snippets': ['We introduce a method to compare the distributions of user behaviors in real and simulated conversations, illustrated in Figure 1. For each conversation, we extract a representation of the user’s\nbehavior by using an LLM to generate a description along six behavioral facets (such as how they\nmake requests or what dialog acts they perform) and then embedding it into a shared semantic space.\nNext, we quantize these representations into discrete distributions over user behavior modes by\nclustering [46, 41]. Finally, we measure the gap between the real and simulated distributions using\ndivergence-based metrics. We confirm that our method captures meaningful behavioral distributions\nand is robust to the choice of embedding model and clustering algorithm through a human study and\nvalidation studies.\n\n\nWe provide the first systematic evaluation of 24 LLM-based user simulators across coding and writing\ntasks, including 7 closed-source LLMs, 15 open-source LLMs, and 2 trained simulators. Our results\nreveal a large distributional gap from real users, and surface insights across model families, scales, and\nbehavioral facets. Pairwise comparisons between simulators show that most behave similarly, while a\nfew stand apart. Combining behaviorally complementary simulators brings the resulting distribution\ncloser to real users than either simulator on its own. Lastly, a TF-IDF analysis of the clusters provides\ninterpretable insights into behaviors that user simulators capture, miss, and hallucinate.']}}, {'id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_15', 'title': '2605.07847v1_chunk_15', 'snippet': '**Clustering Algorithms.** We obtain discrete distributions of user behavior by clustering our embeddings using _k_ -means with _k_ = 500. To verify that our method is robust to the clustering algorithm,\nwe repeat our experiments using Gaussian Mixture Models and Agglomerative Clustering. Similar\nto the embedding model ablation, we compute the Spearman rank correlations between simulator\nrankings produced by each pair of clustering algorithms. Our results in Table 2 demonstrate that\nsimulator rankings are nearly identical across all pairs ( _ρ_ � 0 _._ 96 ), and scatter plot visualizations are\nprovided in Figure 15 (Appendix G).\n\n\n6\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_6)\n\n�\n\n\n**-en** 3Emb **d** Qwig8B **-l** sma\n\n**-en** 3Emb **d** Qwig8B **-e** 5\n\n**-l** BGEsmaenv1.5 **-e** 5\n\n\nK-Means **a** u **s**\n\nK-Means lom **eg**\n\nG **a** u **s** lom **eg**\n\n\n�\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_7)\n\n**a** **ist** **s**\n\n\n\nFigure 3: Pairwise Jensen–Shannon divergence between the behavior distributions of 24 user simulators across coding (lower triangle) and writing tasks (upper triangle), ordered by descending mean\npairwise JS divergence. Many simulators demonstrate similar behavioral distributions (lighter cells)\nwhile a few stand out (darker cells).\n\n\n**6.3** **Linear Classification**', 'score': None, 'metadata': {'vertex_id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_15', 'snippets': ['**Clustering Algorithms.** We obtain discrete distributions of user behavior by clustering our embeddings using _k_ -means with _k_ = 500. To verify that our method is robust to the clustering algorithm,\nwe repeat our experiments using Gaussian Mixture Models and Agglomerative Clustering. Similar\nto the embedding model ablation, we compute the Spearman rank correlations between simulator\nrankings produced by each pair of clustering algorithms. Our results in Table 2 demonstrate that\nsimulator rankings are nearly identical across all pairs ( _ρ_ � 0 _._ 96 ), and scatter plot visualizations are\nprovided in Figure 15 (Appendix G).\n\n\n6\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_6)\n\n�\n\n\n**-en** 3Emb **d** Qwig8B **-l** sma\n\n**-en** 3Emb **d** Qwig8B **-e** 5\n\n**-l** BGEsmaenv1.5 **-e** 5\n\n\nK-Means **a** u **s**\n\nK-Means lom **eg**\n\nG **a** u **s** lom **eg**\n\n\n�\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_7)\n\n**a** **ist** **s**\n\n\n\nFigure 3: Pairwise Jensen–Shannon divergence between the behavior distributions of 24 user simulators across coding (lower triangle) and writing tasks (upper triangle), ordered by descending mean\npairwise JS divergence. Many simulators demonstrate similar behavioral distributions (lighter cells)\nwhile a few stand out (darker cells).\n\n\n**6.3** **Linear Classification**']}}, {'id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_0', 'title': '2605.07847v1_chunk_0', 'snippet': '**Shuhaib Mehri** _[♠]_ **Philippe Laban** _[♢]_ **Sumuk Shashidhar** _[♠]_ **Marwa Abdulhai** [⋆]\n\n**Sergey Levine** [⋆] **Michel Galley** _[♢]_ **Dilek Hakkani-Tür** _[♠]_\n\n_♠_ University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign _♢_ Microsoft Research\n⋆University of California, Berkeley', 'score': None, 'metadata': {'vertex_id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_0', 'snippets': ['\n**Shuhaib Mehri** _[♠]_ **Philippe Laban** _[♢]_ **Sumuk Shashidhar** _[♠]_ **Marwa Abdulhai** [⋆]\n\n**Sergey Levine** [⋆] **Michel Galley** _[♢]_ **Dilek Hakkani-Tür** _[♠]_\n\n_♠_ University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign _♢_ Microsoft Research\n⋆University of California, Berkeley\n\n']}}, {'id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_1', 'title': '2605.07847v1_chunk_1', 'snippet': '```\n             mehri2@illinois.edu\n\n```', 'score': None, 'metadata': {'vertex_id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_1', 'snippets': ['```\n             mehri2@illinois.edu\n\n```\n']}}, {'id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_5', 'title': '2605.07847v1_chunk_5', 'snippet': 'Our work advances toward user simulators that faithfully represent the diversity of real users with the\nfollowing contributions: (1) We introduce a method for measuring the distributional gap between\nreal and simulated user behaviors, validated through a human study and ablations; (2) Our analysis\nof 7 closed-source LLMs, 15 open-source LLMs and 2 trained simulators on coding and writing\ntasks reveals a large distributional gap from real users that varies across model families, scales, and\nbehavioral facets; (3) We show that combining behaviorally complementary simulators brings the\nresulting distribution closer to real users than either simulator on its own; (4) We present a TF-IDF\nanalysis of behavior clusters that surfaces interpretable insights into behaviors that simulators capture,\nmiss, and hallucinate.\n\n\n**2** **Problem Formulation**\n\n\nIn this section, we formalize the problem of evaluating how well a user simulator captures the\ndistribution of real user behaviors. Let _P_ denote the distribution of real user behaviors, and _Q_ denote\nthe distribution of simulated user behaviors. Our objective is to measure the gap between _P_ and _Q_ .\n\n\nIn practice, _P_ and _Q_ are not directly observable. Instead, we access them through datasets of\nconversations, where each conversation is a sequence C n = ( _u_ 1 _, a_ 1 _, . . ., u_ n _, a_ n ), with _u_ i and _a_\ndenoting the user and assistant utterances at turn _i_ . We use D real [, a dataset of real user-assistant]\nconversations, as samples from _P_ .', 'score': None, 'metadata': {'vertex_id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_5', 'snippets': ['Our work advances toward user simulators that faithfully represent the diversity of real users with the\nfollowing contributions: (1) We introduce a method for measuring the distributional gap between\nreal and simulated user behaviors, validated through a human study and ablations; (2) Our analysis\nof 7 closed-source LLMs, 15 open-source LLMs and 2 trained simulators on coding and writing\ntasks reveals a large distributional gap from real users that varies across model families, scales, and\nbehavioral facets; (3) We show that combining behaviorally complementary simulators brings the\nresulting distribution closer to real users than either simulator on its own; (4) We present a TF-IDF\nanalysis of behavior clusters that surfaces interpretable insights into behaviors that simulators capture,\nmiss, and hallucinate.\n\n\n**2** **Problem Formulation**\n\n\nIn this section, we formalize the problem of evaluating how well a user simulator captures the\ndistribution of real user behaviors. Let _P_ denote the distribution of real user behaviors, and _Q_ denote\nthe distribution of simulated user behaviors. Our objective is to measure the gap between _P_ and _Q_ .\n\n\nIn practice, _P_ and _Q_ are not directly observable. Instead, we access them through datasets of\nconversations, where each conversation is a sequence C n = ( _u_ 1 _, a_ 1 _, . . ., u_ n _, a_ n ), with _u_ i and _a_\ndenoting the user and assistant utterances at turn _i_ . We use D real [, a dataset of real user-assistant]\nconversations, as samples from _P_ .']}}, {'id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_14', 'title': '2605.07847v1_chunk_14', 'snippet': '**User Behavior Descriptions.** We use an LLM to generate\nuser behavior descriptions for each conversation to isolate user\nbehavioral patterns and abstract away irrelevant surface-level\nfeatures from the raw conversation history. To validate that\nthis step is necessary, we compare against two simpler rep\nFigure 2: Scatter plot of classifica\nresentations: the raw conversations and user utterances only.\n\ntion accuracy and Jensen–Shannon\n\nTable 10 (Appendix G) reports the full results for all simulators\n\nDivergence (JS) for all simulators\n\nacross both tasks. These simpler representations produce low\n\nacross coding and writing tasks.\n\ndivergences across all simulators, which would suggest that\n\nEach point represents one simulator\n\nsimulators closely match real users. However, this similarity is on one task.\nan artifact of surface-level features such as lexical and semantic\noverlap, rather than reflecting behavioral patterns. Our behavioral descriptions, by contrast, reveal\nmuch larger and more meaningful gaps, confirming that this step is necessary.\n\n\n**Embedding Models.** User behavior descriptions are embedded using `Qwen3-Embedding-8B` . To\nverify that our results are robust across embedding models, we repeat our experiments using two\nother embedding models: `e5-large-v2` [57] and `BGE-small-en-v1.5` [60]. We apply z-score\nnormalization to metric values within each dataset and then compute the Spearman rank correlation\nbetween simulator rankings produced by each pair of embedding models. Table 2 report the results,\nand Figure 15 (Appendix G) provide scatter plot visualizations. Simulator rankings are largely\npreserved across different embedding models.', 'score': None, 'metadata': {'vertex_id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_14', 'snippets': ['**User Behavior Descriptions.** We use an LLM to generate\nuser behavior descriptions for each conversation to isolate user\nbehavioral patterns and abstract away irrelevant surface-level\nfeatures from the raw conversation history. To validate that\nthis step is necessary, we compare against two simpler rep\nFigure 2: Scatter plot of classifica\nresentations: the raw conversations and user utterances only.\n\ntion accuracy and Jensen–Shannon\n\nTable 10 (Appendix G) reports the full results for all simulators\n\nDivergence (JS) for all simulators\n\nacross both tasks. These simpler representations produce low\n\nacross coding and writing tasks.\n\ndivergences across all simulators, which would suggest that\n\nEach point represents one simulator\n\nsimulators closely match real users. However, this similarity is on one task.\nan artifact of surface-level features such as lexical and semantic\noverlap, rather than reflecting behavioral patterns. Our behavioral descriptions, by contrast, reveal\nmuch larger and more meaningful gaps, confirming that this step is necessary.\n\n\n**Embedding Models.** User behavior descriptions are embedded using `Qwen3-Embedding-8B` . To\nverify that our results are robust across embedding models, we repeat our experiments using two\nother embedding models: `e5-large-v2` [57] and `BGE-small-en-v1.5` [60]. We apply z-score\nnormalization to metric values within each dataset and then compute the Spearman rank correlation\nbetween simulator rankings produced by each pair of embedding models. Table 2 report the results,\nand Figure 15 (Appendix G) provide scatter plot visualizations. Simulator rankings are largely\npreserved across different embedding models.']}}, {'id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_19', 'title': '2605.07847v1_chunk_19', 'snippet': '8\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_9)\n\n: : : : : :\n\n\n**el** **s** ed **al** ucinted\n\n\n**el** **s**\n\n\nif real users dominate, and h **al** ucinted if simulated users dominate. For each category, we extract\ndistinctive terms from the behavior descriptions in the top 100 clusters using TF-IDF over unigrams\nand bigrams. Each term is scored by its TF-IDF in the target category minus the average TF-IDF over\nthe other two. To reduce noise, we filter stopwords and meaningless terms (identified by an LLM),\nand require terms to appear in at least 50 descriptions.\n\n\nWe present our analysis for `Gemini 3.1 Pro` on the coding task. Figure 4 shows the word clouds for\neach category, and Appendix I presents the full table of top 50 terms for each category. We observe\nthe following across the three categories: W-capturd: terms reflect iterative problem-solving **el**\nbehaviors such as requesting alternatives, rejecting proposed solutions, and proactively identifying\nerrors (e.g., ""requesting alternative"", ""rejects proposed"", ""proactively corrects""); Mi terms **s** ed:\nreflect behaviors the simulator fails to reproduce: terse and compressed communication, transactional\nexchanges, authoritative directives (e.g., ""message terse"", ""authoritative"", ""transactional analytical"");\nH **al** ucinted: terms reflect overly enthusiastic behaviors such as excessive positivity and gratitude,\nand frequent greetings and farewells (e.g., ""friendliness"", ""thanks awesome"", ""formal pleasantries"").\n\n\n**8** **Related Work**', 'score': None, 'metadata': {'vertex_id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_19', 'snippets': ['8\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_9)\n\n: : : : : :\n\n\n**el** **s** ed **al** ucinted\n\n\n**el** **s**\n\n\nif real users dominate, and h **al** ucinted if simulated users dominate. For each category, we extract\ndistinctive terms from the behavior descriptions in the top 100 clusters using TF-IDF over unigrams\nand bigrams. Each term is scored by its TF-IDF in the target category minus the average TF-IDF over\nthe other two. To reduce noise, we filter stopwords and meaningless terms (identified by an LLM),\nand require terms to appear in at least 50 descriptions.\n\n\nWe present our analysis for `Gemini 3.1 Pro` on the coding task. Figure 4 shows the word clouds for\neach category, and Appendix I presents the full table of top 50 terms for each category. We observe\nthe following across the three categories: W-capturd: terms reflect iterative problem-solving **el**\nbehaviors such as requesting alternatives, rejecting proposed solutions, and proactively identifying\nerrors (e.g., ""requesting alternative"", ""rejects proposed"", ""proactively corrects""); Mi terms **s** ed:\nreflect behaviors the simulator fails to reproduce: terse and compressed communication, transactional\nexchanges, authoritative directives (e.g., ""message terse"", ""authoritative"", ""transactional analytical"");\nH **al** ucinted: terms reflect overly enthusiastic behaviors such as excessive positivity and gratitude,\nand frequent greetings and farewells (e.g., ""friendliness"", ""thanks awesome"", ""formal pleasantries"").\n\n\n**8** **Related Work**']}}, {'id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_2', 'title': '2605.07847v1_chunk_2', 'snippet': '**Code** : `[https://github.com/shuhaibm/UserBehavioralDivergence](https://github.com/shuhaibm/UserBehavioralDivergence)`\n\n\n**Abstract**\n\n\nAs user simulators are increasingly used for interactive training and evaluation\nof AI assistants, it is essential that they represent the diverse behaviors of real\nusers. While existing works train user simulators to generate human-like responses,\nwhether they capture the broad and heterogeneous distribution of real user behaviors\nremains an open question. In this work, we introduce a method to measure the\ndistributional gap between real and simulated user behaviors, validated through a\nhuman study and ablations. Given a dataset of real and simulated conversations, our\nmethod extracts representations of user behavior from each conversation, quantizes\nthem into discrete distributions via clustering, then computes divergence metrics.\nWe provide the first systematic evaluation of 24 LLM-based user simulators on\ncoding and writing tasks, and reveal a large distributional gap from real users that\nvaries across model families, scales, and behavioral facets. Pairwise comparisons\nshow that most simulators behave similarly, while a few stand apart. Combining\nbehaviorally complementary simulators brings the resulting distribution closer to\nreal users compared to either simulator on its own. Finally, a TF-IDF analysis of\nthe clusters surfaces interpretable patterns of behaviors that simulators capture,\nmiss, and hallucinate.\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_1)\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_2)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n||||\n|---|---|---|\n|Qu|a|ntiz|\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_3)', 'score': None, 'metadata': {'vertex_id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_2', 'snippets': ['**Code** : `[https://github.com/shuhaibm/UserBehavioralDivergence](https://github.com/shuhaibm/UserBehavioralDivergence)`\n\n\n**Abstract**\n\n\nAs user simulators are increasingly used for interactive training and evaluation\nof AI assistants, it is essential that they represent the diverse behaviors of real\nusers. While existing works train user simulators to generate human-like responses,\nwhether they capture the broad and heterogeneous distribution of real user behaviors\nremains an open question. In this work, we introduce a method to measure the\ndistributional gap between real and simulated user behaviors, validated through a\nhuman study and ablations. Given a dataset of real and simulated conversations, our\nmethod extracts representations of user behavior from each conversation, quantizes\nthem into discrete distributions via clustering, then computes divergence metrics.\nWe provide the first systematic evaluation of 24 LLM-based user simulators on\ncoding and writing tasks, and reveal a large distributional gap from real users that\nvaries across model families, scales, and behavioral facets. Pairwise comparisons\nshow that most simulators behave similarly, while a few stand apart. Combining\nbehaviorally complementary simulators brings the resulting distribution closer to\nreal users compared to either simulator on its own. Finally, a TF-IDF analysis of\nthe clusters surfaces interpretable patterns of behaviors that simulators capture,\nmiss, and hallucinate.\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_1)\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_2)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n||||\n|---|---|---|\n|Qu|a|ntiz|\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_3)']}}, {'id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_3', 'title': '2605.07847v1_chunk_3', 'snippet': '![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_2)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n||||\n|---|---|---|\n|Qu|a|ntiz|\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_3)\n\nFigure 1: Our method extracts representations of user behavior from real and simulated conversations, then quantizes them via _k_ -means to get discrete behavioral distributions for real ( _P_ [ˆ] ) and\nsimulated users ( _Q_ [ˆ] ). UMAP projections [30] and first principal component histograms illustrate the\ndistributional gap for two simulators on the coding task: `Gemini 3.1 Pro` overlaps real users more\nclosely compared to `Llama-3.1-8B-Instruct` .\n\n\nPreprint.\n\n\n**1** **Introduction**\n\n\nThe role of user simulators is to model the diverse behaviors of real users, providing a scalable\nmeans to train and evaluate AI systems on the interactions that they encounter in real-world settings\n\n[26, 14, 39, 45]. Recent works build user simulators by training Large Language Models (LLMs)\nto generate responses that resemble those of real users [33, 16, 58]. Yet real users exhibit a broad,\nheterogeneous distribution of behaviors [65, 66, 28]. For example, some users tend to underspecify\ntheir requests, while others fully specify every constraint. The extent to which user simulators capture\nthis distribution has not been measured.\n\n\nA user simulator can fail to capture the distribution of real users in two ways: by demonstrating\nbehaviors that real users rarely exhibit (low prec **i** son), or by failing to demonstrate behaviors that real\nusers do exhibit (low reca **l** ), mirroring precision and recall metrics for generative models [ 46, 23, 11].\nThese failure modes bias training and evaluation, and yield assistants that struggle to generalize to\nthe diverse behaviors of real users [52].', 'score': None, 'metadata': {'vertex_id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_3', 'snippets': ['![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_2)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n||||\n|---|---|---|\n|Qu|a|ntiz|\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_3)\n\nFigure 1: Our method extracts representations of user behavior from real and simulated conversations, then quantizes them via _k_ -means to get discrete behavioral distributions for real ( _P_ [ˆ] ) and\nsimulated users ( _Q_ [ˆ] ). UMAP projections [30] and first principal component histograms illustrate the\ndistributional gap for two simulators on the coding task: `Gemini 3.1 Pro` overlaps real users more\nclosely compared to `Llama-3.1-8B-Instruct` .\n\n\nPreprint.\n\n\n**1** **Introduction**\n\n\nThe role of user simulators is to model the diverse behaviors of real users, providing a scalable\nmeans to train and evaluate AI systems on the interactions that they encounter in real-world settings\n\n[26, 14, 39, 45]. Recent works build user simulators by training Large Language Models (LLMs)\nto generate responses that resemble those of real users [33, 16, 58]. Yet real users exhibit a broad,\nheterogeneous distribution of behaviors [65, 66, 28]. For example, some users tend to underspecify\ntheir requests, while others fully specify every constraint. The extent to which user simulators capture\nthis distribution has not been measured.\n\n\nA user simulator can fail to capture the distribution of real users in two ways: by demonstrating\nbehaviors that real users rarely exhibit (low prec **i** son), or by failing to demonstrate behaviors that real\nusers do exhibit (low reca **l** ), mirroring precision and recall metrics for generative models [ 46, 23, 11].\nThese failure modes bias training and evaluation, and yield assistants that struggle to generalize to\nthe diverse behaviors of real users [52].']}}, {'id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_16', 'title': '2605.07847v1_chunk_16', 'snippet': '**6.3** **Linear Classification**\n\n\nWe validate that our user behavior representation embeddings encode meaningful differences between\nreal and simulated users by training a linear classifier. For each simulator, we construct a dataset\nof 5,000 real and 5,000 simulated embeddings, and then train an L2-regularized logistic regression\nclassifier to classify embeddings as real or simulated. We average results over 5 stratified random\n80/20 train-test splits. The classification accuracies across simulators are consistently high, ranging\nfrom 90.92% to 99.63%, and also correlate strongly with our distributional metrics (Figure 2). This\nconfirms that the embeddings encode meaningful differences between real and simulated users. The\nfull accuracy scores and correlations for all metrics are presented in Appendix H.\n\n\n**7** **Discussion**\n\n\n**7.1** **How Do User Behavior Distributions Compare Among Simulators?**\n\n\nOur main results show that the distributional gap to real users varies across simulators. This raises a\nnatural question: how do the behviorl d **a** rbuon of user **ist** imulator compare to each other? **s** To\ninvestigate this, we pool the user behavior representations across all 24 simulators, quantize them\ninto distributions, and compute the JS divergence between all pairs. Figure 3 reports the results.\n\n\nMany simulators behave similarly to each other: 30% of the 552 pairwise comparisons have JS _<_\n0 _._ 10. Pairs from the same family tend to be the most similar, achieving the lowest scores in the\ndataset. The simulators with the lowest mean pairwise JS scores are `Qwen3.5-122B-A10B` (0 _._ 14),\n\n\n7', 'score': None, 'metadata': {'vertex_id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_16', 'snippets': ['**6.3** **Linear Classification**\n\n\nWe validate that our user behavior representation embeddings encode meaningful differences between\nreal and simulated users by training a linear classifier. For each simulator, we construct a dataset\nof 5,000 real and 5,000 simulated embeddings, and then train an L2-regularized logistic regression\nclassifier to classify embeddings as real or simulated. We average results over 5 stratified random\n80/20 train-test splits. The classification accuracies across simulators are consistently high, ranging\nfrom 90.92% to 99.63%, and also correlate strongly with our distributional metrics (Figure 2). This\nconfirms that the embeddings encode meaningful differences between real and simulated users. The\nfull accuracy scores and correlations for all metrics are presented in Appendix H.\n\n\n**7** **Discussion**\n\n\n**7.1** **How Do User Behavior Distributions Compare Among Simulators?**\n\n\nOur main results show that the distributional gap to real users varies across simulators. This raises a\nnatural question: how do the behviorl d **a** rbuon of user **ist** imulator compare to each other? **s** To\ninvestigate this, we pool the user behavior representations across all 24 simulators, quantize them\ninto distributions, and compute the JS divergence between all pairs. Figure 3 reports the results.\n\n\nMany simulators behave similarly to each other: 30% of the 552 pairwise comparisons have JS _<_\n0 _._ 10. Pairs from the same family tend to be the most similar, achieving the lowest scores in the\ndataset. The simulators with the lowest mean pairwise JS scores are `Qwen3.5-122B-A10B` (0 _._ 14),\n\n\n7']}}, {'id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_20', 'title': '2605.07847v1_chunk_20', 'snippet': '**8** **Related Work**\n\n\n**User Simulation.** LLMs have demonstrated the ability to simulate believable human behavior,\nand are increasingly used as user simulators for interactive evaluation [9, 53, 68, 5, 25], synthetic\ndata generation [10, 17, 43], and reinforcement learning [69, 59]. Across these applications, initial\napproaches rely on prompting LLMs [9, 35, 36, 29, 43]. However, these prompt-based simulators\nstruggle to consistently adhere to assigned user goals or profiles, motivating recent methods that train\nLLM-based user simulators with goal-tracking or persona-consistency objectives [31, 1]. In order to\nbuild simulators that can faithfully represent real users, other works train LLMs with response-level\nsimilarity objectives, such as supervised fine-tuning on real user data [33] or aligning latent reasoning\nstates through reinforcement learning [16, 58, 63].\n\n\n**User Simulator Evaluation.** Recent works investigate how LLM-based user simulators compare\nto real users. One direction compares assistant evaluations conducted with simulators against those\nconducted with real users, finding that simulator-based evaluations are poor estimates of agent\nperformance and obscure demographic disparities [13, 48]. A second direction compares simulator\nand human behaviors at the feature level, finding systematic divergence on lexical, syntactic, and\nstylistic metrics [22, 67, 7].\n\n\nAcross both training and evaluation work, simulator fidelity is typically measured at the response or\nfeature level. While some works investigate simulating diverse user populations [28, 2, 17], ours is\nthe first to measure how well user simulators capture the distribution of real user behaviors. We do\nthis by extracting representations of user behavior that go beyond lexical or stylistic features, and\nclustering them to compare the distributions of real and simulated user behaviors.', 'score': None, 'metadata': {'vertex_id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_20', 'snippets': ['**8** **Related Work**\n\n\n**User Simulation.** LLMs have demonstrated the ability to simulate believable human behavior,\nand are increasingly used as user simulators for interactive evaluation [9, 53, 68, 5, 25], synthetic\ndata generation [10, 17, 43], and reinforcement learning [69, 59]. Across these applications, initial\napproaches rely on prompting LLMs [9, 35, 36, 29, 43]. However, these prompt-based simulators\nstruggle to consistently adhere to assigned user goals or profiles, motivating recent methods that train\nLLM-based user simulators with goal-tracking or persona-consistency objectives [31, 1]. In order to\nbuild simulators that can faithfully represent real users, other works train LLMs with response-level\nsimilarity objectives, such as supervised fine-tuning on real user data [33] or aligning latent reasoning\nstates through reinforcement learning [16, 58, 63].\n\n\n**User Simulator Evaluation.** Recent works investigate how LLM-based user simulators compare\nto real users. One direction compares assistant evaluations conducted with simulators against those\nconducted with real users, finding that simulator-based evaluations are poor estimates of agent\nperformance and obscure demographic disparities [13, 48]. A second direction compares simulator\nand human behaviors at the feature level, finding systematic divergence on lexical, syntactic, and\nstylistic metrics [22, 67, 7].\n\n\nAcross both training and evaluation work, simulator fidelity is typically measured at the response or\nfeature level. While some works investigate simulating diverse user populations [28, 2, 17], ours is\nthe first to measure how well user simulators capture the distribution of real user behaviors. We do\nthis by extracting representations of user behavior that go beyond lexical or stylistic features, and\nclustering them to compare the distributions of real and simulated user behaviors.']}}, {'id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_18', 'title': '2605.07847v1_chunk_18', 'snippet': 'First, we pair the simulators with the smallest distributional gap to real users: `Gemini 3.1 Pro` with\n`GPT-5.4`, and `gpt-oss-120b` with `gemma-4-31B-it` . Both pairs achieve smaller JS divergence\nthan either individual simulator on coding and writing. Next, we pair simulators that are behaviorally\ndistinct from others, `UserLM-8b` and `GPT-5.4 mini`, with each of `Gemini 3.1 Pro`, `GPT-5.4`,\n`gemma-4-31B-it`, and `gpt-oss-120b` . These improve over the individual simulators on writing\nand remain competitive on coding. Conversely, combining behaviorally similar simulators, such as\n`gemma-4-31B-it` and `Claude Haiku 4.5`, does not help.\n\n\nThese results suggest that combining behaviorally complementary simulators can reduce the distributional gap to real users. This combination strategy is conceptually similar to mixture-of-experts\n\n[49, 15] and assistant-side routing [37, 56, 34], and learning a router that selects the appropriate\nsimulator is a natural extension we leave to future work.\n\n\n**7.3** **Interpreting the Behavioral Clusters**\n\n\nFigure 4: Word clouds of w-capturd (green), **el** mi **s** ed (blue), and h **al** ucinted (red) behaviors for\n`Gemini 3.1 Pro` on coding based on a TF-IDF analysis on behavioral clusters.\n\n\nThe behavioral distributions reveal not only how much simulators diverge from real users, but which\nbehaviors they capture, miss, or hallucinate. We classify each cluster by the ratio of real to simulated\nconversations into three categories: w-capturd if real and simulated are roughly balanced, **el** mi **s**\n\n\n8\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_9)\n\n: : : : : :\n\n\n**el** **s** ed **al** ucinted\n\n\n**el** **s**', 'score': None, 'metadata': {'vertex_id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_18', 'snippets': ['First, we pair the simulators with the smallest distributional gap to real users: `Gemini 3.1 Pro` with\n`GPT-5.4`, and `gpt-oss-120b` with `gemma-4-31B-it` . Both pairs achieve smaller JS divergence\nthan either individual simulator on coding and writing. Next, we pair simulators that are behaviorally\ndistinct from others, `UserLM-8b` and `GPT-5.4 mini`, with each of `Gemini 3.1 Pro`, `GPT-5.4`,\n`gemma-4-31B-it`, and `gpt-oss-120b` . These improve over the individual simulators on writing\nand remain competitive on coding. Conversely, combining behaviorally similar simulators, such as\n`gemma-4-31B-it` and `Claude Haiku 4.5`, does not help.\n\n\nThese results suggest that combining behaviorally complementary simulators can reduce the distributional gap to real users. This combination strategy is conceptually similar to mixture-of-experts\n\n[49, 15] and assistant-side routing [37, 56, 34], and learning a router that selects the appropriate\nsimulator is a natural extension we leave to future work.\n\n\n**7.3** **Interpreting the Behavioral Clusters**\n\n\nFigure 4: Word clouds of w-capturd (green), **el** mi **s** ed (blue), and h **al** ucinted (red) behaviors for\n`Gemini 3.1 Pro` on coding based on a TF-IDF analysis on behavioral clusters.\n\n\nThe behavioral distributions reveal not only how much simulators diverge from real users, but which\nbehaviors they capture, miss, or hallucinate. We classify each cluster by the ratio of real to simulated\nconversations into three categories: w-capturd if real and simulated are roughly balanced, **el** mi **s**\n\n\n8\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_9)\n\n: : : : : :\n\n\n**el** **s** ed **al** ucinted\n\n\n**el** **s**']}}, {'id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_17', 'title': '2605.07847v1_chunk_17', 'snippet': '7\n\n\nTable 3: The distributional gap between real and simulated user behaviors when combining pairs\nof simulators. When generating conversations, we randomly sample which LLM serves as the\nuser simulator. We report forward KL divergence (KL ), backward KL divergence (KL bwd ), and\nJensen–Shannon divergence (JS) across coding and writing tasks. "" indicates higher is better and #\nindicates lower is better. Darker blue indicates closer behavioral distribution to real users. Subscripts\nshow the change relative to the better of the two individual simulators\n\n\n**Coding** **Writing**\n\n\n**User Simulator** KL KL bwd JS # KL KL bwd JS #\n\n\n: : : : : :\n\n\n**el** **s** ed **al** ucinted\n\n\n**el** **s**\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_8)\n\n: : : : : :\n\n\n**el** **s** ed **al** ucinted\n\n\n**el** **s**\n\n\n\n: : : : : :\n\n\n**el** **s** ed **al** ucinted\n\n\n**el** **s**\n\n\n\n`gemma-4-31B-it` + `Claude Haiku 4.5` .364 _↑_ : .345 _↑_ : .346 _↑_ : .562 _↑_ : .568 _↑_ : .572 _↑_ :\n\n\n`gemma-4-26B-A4B-it` (0 _._ 15), `gemma-4-E2B-it` (0 _._ 15), and `Qwen3.5-35B-A3B` (0 _._ 15). A few\nsimulators stand out and demonstrate behaviors that diverge from the rest. These include `UserLM-8b`,\nwhich has the highest mean pairwise JS score of 0 _._ 41, followed by `GPT-5.4 mini` with a score of\n0 _._ 33. Pairwise JS scores are consistently higher for writing than coding, which aligns with our main\nresults, where the divergences from real users were also higher for writing.\n\n\n**7.2** **Can we Combine User Simulators to Reduce the Gap With Real Users?**\n\n\nSince our pairwise analysis shows that some user simulators behave distinctly from each other, we\ntest whether combining pairs can reduce the gap to real users by randomly sampling which simulator\ngenerates each conversation. Table 3 reports the results.', 'score': None, 'metadata': {'vertex_id': '2605.07847v1_chunk_17', 'snippets': ['7\n\n\nTable 3: The distributional gap between real and simulated user behaviors when combining pairs\nof simulators. When generating conversations, we randomly sample which LLM serves as the\nuser simulator. We report forward KL divergence (KL ), backward KL divergence (KL bwd ), and\nJensen–Shannon divergence (JS) across coding and writing tasks. "" indicates higher is better and #\nindicates lower is better. Darker blue indicates closer behavioral distribution to real users. Subscripts\nshow the change relative to the better of the two individual simulators\n\n\n**Coding** **Writing**\n\n\n**User Simulator** KL KL bwd JS # KL KL bwd JS #\n\n\n: : : : : :\n\n\n**el** **s** ed **al** ucinted\n\n\n**el** **s**\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_8)\n\n: : : : : :\n\n\n**el** **s** ed **al** ucinted\n\n\n**el** **s**\n\n\n\n: : : : : :\n\n\n**el** **s** ed **al** ucinted\n\n\n**el** **s**\n\n\n\n`gemma-4-31B-it` + `Claude Haiku 4.5` .364 _↑_ : .345 _↑_ : .346 _↑_ : .562 _↑_ : .568 _↑_ : .572 _↑_ :\n\n\n`gemma-4-26B-A4B-it` (0 _._ 15), `gemma-4-E2B-it` (0 _._ 15), and `Qwen3.5-35B-A3B` (0 _._ 15). A few\nsimulators stand out and demonstrate behaviors that diverge from the rest. These include `UserLM-8b`,\nwhich has the highest mean pairwise JS score of 0 _._ 41, followed by `GPT-5.4 mini` with a score of\n0 _._ 33. Pairwise JS scores are consistently higher for writing than coding, which aligns with our main\nresults, where the divergences from real users were also higher for writing.\n\n\n**7.2** **Can we Combine User Simulators to Reduce the Gap With Real Users?**\n\n\nSince our pairwise analysis shows that some user simulators behave distinctly from each other, we\ntest whether combining pairs can reduce the gap to real users by randomly sampling which simulator\ngenerates each conversation. Table 3 reports the results.']}}]","['GraphRAG Candidate', 'GraphRAG Candidate', 'GraphRAG Candidate', 'GraphRAG Candidate', 'GraphRAG Candidate', '2605.07847v1_chunk_4', '2605.07847v1_chunk_15', '2605.07847v1_chunk_0', '2605.07847v1_chunk_1', '2605.07847v1_chunk_5', '2605.07847v1_chunk_14', '2605.07847v1_chunk_19', '2605.07847v1_chunk_2', '2605.07847v1_chunk_3', '2605.07847v1_chunk_16', '2605.07847v1_chunk_20', '2605.07847v1_chunk_18', '2605.07847v1_chunk_17']",16,4984,163,179,55212.443524000264,0.07431799986079568,0.0,55212.51851000034,graph,18,0.0,"{'response': 'Paper 2605.07847v1 provides evidence that some simulators are closer to real users than others by comparing the accuracy of classifying user behavior using raw conversations, user utterances only, and behavioral descriptions generated by an LLM. The results show that simpler representations produce low divergences across all simulators, suggesting they closely match real users on one task. However, this similarity is attributed to surface-level features such as lexical and semantic overlap rather than reflecting true behavioral patterns. In contrast, the behavioral descriptions reveal much larger and more meaningful gaps, confirming that this step is necessary for accurately representing user behavior. Additionally, the paper uses Jensen-Shannon (JS) divergence to measure the similarity between distributions of user behavior representations from different simulators and real users. Simulators with lower mean pairwise JS scores indicate a closer match to real user behavior. For instance, `Qwen3.5-122B-A10B` has one of the lowest mean pairwise JS scores at 0.14, suggesting it is more similar to real users compared to other simulators.', 'retrieved': [{'candidate_answer': 'Paper 2605.07847v1 provides evidence that some simulators are closer to real users than others by comparing the accuracy of classifying user behavior using raw conversations, user utterances only, and behavioral descriptions generated by an LLM. The results show that simpler representations produce low divergences across all simulators, suggesting they closely match real users on one task. However, this similarity is attributed to surface-level features such as lexical and semantic overlap rather than reflecting true behavioral patterns. In contrast, the behavioral descriptions reveal much larger and more meaningful gaps, confirming that this step is necessary for accurately representing user behavior.', 'score': 95}, {'candidate_answer': 'Paper 2605.07847v1 provides evidence that some simulators are closer to real users than others by analyzing the behavior descriptions of simulated and real user interactions in a coding task using TF-IDF scores. The analysis reveals distinct categories: W-captured terms reflect iterative problem-solving behaviors, Mi terms indicate behaviors not reproduced by the simulator such as terse communication and authoritative directives, while H-alucinted terms show overly enthusiastic behaviors. This differentiation suggests that simulators with more Mi terms are closer to real users because they better capture nuanced and transactional exchanges.', 'score': 95}, {'candidate_answer': 'The paper provides evidence that some simulators are closer to real users than others by revealing a large distributional gap from real users that varies across model families, scales, and behavioral facets. Pairwise comparisons show that most simulators behave similarly, while a few stand apart. Combining behaviorally complementary simulators brings the resulting distribution closer to real users compared to either simulator on its own.', 'score': 95}, {'candidate_answer': 'Paper 2605.07847v1 provides evidence that some simulators are closer to real users than others by quantizing representations of user behavior from both real and simulated conversations using k-means clustering. The UMAP projections and first principal component histograms illustrate the distributional gap between two specific simulators: `Gemini 3.1 Pro` overlaps more closely with real users compared to `Llama-3.1-8B-Instruct`. This indicates that `Gemini 3.1 Pro` better captures the diverse behaviors of real users, while `Llama-3.1-8B-Instruct` falls short in this aspect.', 'score': 95}, {'candidate_answer': 'The paper provides evidence that some simulators are closer to real users than others by comparing the distributional gaps between user behavior representations of different simulators and real users. Specifically, it uses Jensen-Shannon (JS) divergence to measure the similarity between these distributions. Simulators with lower mean pairwise JS scores indicate a closer match to real user behavior. For instance, `Qwen3.5-122B-A10B` has one of the lowest mean pairwise JS scores at 0.14, suggesting it is more similar to real users compared to other simulators.', 'score': 95}], 'verbose': {'selected_set': [{'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_16', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_0', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_2', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_20', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_18', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_5', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_15', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_3', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_19', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_17', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_4', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_1', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_14', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}], 'start_set': [{'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_2', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_16', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_17', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_20', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}, {'v': '2605.07847v1_chunk_5', 't': 'DocumentChunk'}], 'final_retrieval': {'2605.07847v1_chunk_4': ['We introduce a method to compare the distributions of user behaviors in real and simulated conversations, illustrated in Figure 1. For each conversation, we extract a representation of the user’s\nbehavior by using an LLM to generate a description along six behavioral facets (such as how they\nmake requests or what dialog acts they perform) and then embedding it into a shared semantic space.\nNext, we quantize these representations into discrete distributions over user behavior modes by\nclustering [46, 41]. Finally, we measure the gap between the real and simulated distributions using\ndivergence-based metrics. We confirm that our method captures meaningful behavioral distributions\nand is robust to the choice of embedding model and clustering algorithm through a human study and\nvalidation studies.\n\n\nWe provide the first systematic evaluation of 24 LLM-based user simulators across coding and writing\ntasks, including 7 closed-source LLMs, 15 open-source LLMs, and 2 trained simulators. Our results\nreveal a large distributional gap from real users, and surface insights across model families, scales, and\nbehavioral facets. Pairwise comparisons between simulators show that most behave similarly, while a\nfew stand apart. Combining behaviorally complementary simulators brings the resulting distribution\ncloser to real users than either simulator on its own. Lastly, a TF-IDF analysis of the clusters provides\ninterpretable insights into behaviors that user simulators capture, miss, and hallucinate.'], '2605.07847v1_chunk_15': ['**Clustering Algorithms.** We obtain discrete distributions of user behavior by clustering our embeddings using _k_ -means with _k_ = 500. To verify that our method is robust to the clustering algorithm,\nwe repeat our experiments using Gaussian Mixture Models and Agglomerative Clustering. Similar\nto the embedding model ablation, we compute the Spearman rank correlations between simulator\nrankings produced by each pair of clustering algorithms. Our results in Table 2 demonstrate that\nsimulator rankings are nearly identical across all pairs ( _ρ_ � 0 _._ 96 ), and scatter plot visualizations are\nprovided in Figure 15 (Appendix G).\n\n\n6\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_6)\n\n�\n\n\n**-en** 3Emb **d** Qwig8B **-l** sma\n\n**-en** 3Emb **d** Qwig8B **-e** 5\n\n**-l** BGEsmaenv1.5 **-e** 5\n\n\nK-Means **a** u **s**\n\nK-Means lom **eg**\n\nG **a** u **s** lom **eg**\n\n\n�\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_7)\n\n**a** **ist** **s**\n\n\n\nFigure 3: Pairwise Jensen–Shannon divergence between the behavior distributions of 24 user simulators across coding (lower triangle) and writing tasks (upper triangle), ordered by descending mean\npairwise JS divergence. Many simulators demonstrate similar behavioral distributions (lighter cells)\nwhile a few stand out (darker cells).\n\n\n**6.3** **Linear Classification**'], '2605.07847v1_chunk_0': ['\n**Shuhaib Mehri** _[♠]_ **Philippe Laban** _[♢]_ **Sumuk Shashidhar** _[♠]_ **Marwa Abdulhai** [⋆]\n\n**Sergey Levine** [⋆] **Michel Galley** _[♢]_ **Dilek Hakkani-Tür** _[♠]_\n\n_♠_ University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign _♢_ Microsoft Research\n⋆University of California, Berkeley\n\n'], '2605.07847v1_chunk_1': ['```\n             mehri2@illinois.edu\n\n```\n'], '2605.07847v1_chunk_5': ['Our work advances toward user simulators that faithfully represent the diversity of real users with the\nfollowing contributions: (1) We introduce a method for measuring the distributional gap between\nreal and simulated user behaviors, validated through a human study and ablations; (2) Our analysis\nof 7 closed-source LLMs, 15 open-source LLMs and 2 trained simulators on coding and writing\ntasks reveals a large distributional gap from real users that varies across model families, scales, and\nbehavioral facets; (3) We show that combining behaviorally complementary simulators brings the\nresulting distribution closer to real users than either simulator on its own; (4) We present a TF-IDF\nanalysis of behavior clusters that surfaces interpretable insights into behaviors that simulators capture,\nmiss, and hallucinate.\n\n\n**2** **Problem Formulation**\n\n\nIn this section, we formalize the problem of evaluating how well a user simulator captures the\ndistribution of real user behaviors. Let _P_ denote the distribution of real user behaviors, and _Q_ denote\nthe distribution of simulated user behaviors. Our objective is to measure the gap between _P_ and _Q_ .\n\n\nIn practice, _P_ and _Q_ are not directly observable. Instead, we access them through datasets of\nconversations, where each conversation is a sequence C n = ( _u_ 1 _, a_ 1 _, . . ., u_ n _, a_ n ), with _u_ i and _a_\ndenoting the user and assistant utterances at turn _i_ . We use D real [, a dataset of real user-assistant]\nconversations, as samples from _P_ .'], '2605.07847v1_chunk_14': ['**User Behavior Descriptions.** We use an LLM to generate\nuser behavior descriptions for each conversation to isolate user\nbehavioral patterns and abstract away irrelevant surface-level\nfeatures from the raw conversation history. To validate that\nthis step is necessary, we compare against two simpler rep\nFigure 2: Scatter plot of classifica\nresentations: the raw conversations and user utterances only.\n\ntion accuracy and Jensen–Shannon\n\nTable 10 (Appendix G) reports the full results for all simulators\n\nDivergence (JS) for all simulators\n\nacross both tasks. These simpler representations produce low\n\nacross coding and writing tasks.\n\ndivergences across all simulators, which would suggest that\n\nEach point represents one simulator\n\nsimulators closely match real users. However, this similarity is on one task.\nan artifact of surface-level features such as lexical and semantic\noverlap, rather than reflecting behavioral patterns. Our behavioral descriptions, by contrast, reveal\nmuch larger and more meaningful gaps, confirming that this step is necessary.\n\n\n**Embedding Models.** User behavior descriptions are embedded using `Qwen3-Embedding-8B` . To\nverify that our results are robust across embedding models, we repeat our experiments using two\nother embedding models: `e5-large-v2` [57] and `BGE-small-en-v1.5` [60]. We apply z-score\nnormalization to metric values within each dataset and then compute the Spearman rank correlation\nbetween simulator rankings produced by each pair of embedding models. Table 2 report the results,\nand Figure 15 (Appendix G) provide scatter plot visualizations. Simulator rankings are largely\npreserved across different embedding models.'], '2605.07847v1_chunk_19': ['8\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_9)\n\n: : : : : :\n\n\n**el** **s** ed **al** ucinted\n\n\n**el** **s**\n\n\nif real users dominate, and h **al** ucinted if simulated users dominate. For each category, we extract\ndistinctive terms from the behavior descriptions in the top 100 clusters using TF-IDF over unigrams\nand bigrams. Each term is scored by its TF-IDF in the target category minus the average TF-IDF over\nthe other two. To reduce noise, we filter stopwords and meaningless terms (identified by an LLM),\nand require terms to appear in at least 50 descriptions.\n\n\nWe present our analysis for `Gemini 3.1 Pro` on the coding task. Figure 4 shows the word clouds for\neach category, and Appendix I presents the full table of top 50 terms for each category. We observe\nthe following across the three categories: W-capturd: terms reflect iterative problem-solving **el**\nbehaviors such as requesting alternatives, rejecting proposed solutions, and proactively identifying\nerrors (e.g., ""requesting alternative"", ""rejects proposed"", ""proactively corrects""); Mi terms **s** ed:\nreflect behaviors the simulator fails to reproduce: terse and compressed communication, transactional\nexchanges, authoritative directives (e.g., ""message terse"", ""authoritative"", ""transactional analytical"");\nH **al** ucinted: terms reflect overly enthusiastic behaviors such as excessive positivity and gratitude,\nand frequent greetings and farewells (e.g., ""friendliness"", ""thanks awesome"", ""formal pleasantries"").\n\n\n**8** **Related Work**'], '2605.07847v1_chunk_2': ['**Code** : `[https://github.com/shuhaibm/UserBehavioralDivergence](https://github.com/shuhaibm/UserBehavioralDivergence)`\n\n\n**Abstract**\n\n\nAs user simulators are increasingly used for interactive training and evaluation\nof AI assistants, it is essential that they represent the diverse behaviors of real\nusers. While existing works train user simulators to generate human-like responses,\nwhether they capture the broad and heterogeneous distribution of real user behaviors\nremains an open question. In this work, we introduce a method to measure the\ndistributional gap between real and simulated user behaviors, validated through a\nhuman study and ablations. Given a dataset of real and simulated conversations, our\nmethod extracts representations of user behavior from each conversation, quantizes\nthem into discrete distributions via clustering, then computes divergence metrics.\nWe provide the first systematic evaluation of 24 LLM-based user simulators on\ncoding and writing tasks, and reveal a large distributional gap from real users that\nvaries across model families, scales, and behavioral facets. Pairwise comparisons\nshow that most simulators behave similarly, while a few stand apart. Combining\nbehaviorally complementary simulators brings the resulting distribution closer to\nreal users compared to either simulator on its own. Finally, a TF-IDF analysis of\nthe clusters surfaces interpretable patterns of behaviors that simulators capture,\nmiss, and hallucinate.\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_1)\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_2)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n||||\n|---|---|---|\n|Qu|a|ntiz|\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_3)'], '2605.07847v1_chunk_3': ['![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_2)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n||||\n|---|---|---|\n|Qu|a|ntiz|\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_3)\n\nFigure 1: Our method extracts representations of user behavior from real and simulated conversations, then quantizes them via _k_ -means to get discrete behavioral distributions for real ( _P_ [ˆ] ) and\nsimulated users ( _Q_ [ˆ] ). UMAP projections [30] and first principal component histograms illustrate the\ndistributional gap for two simulators on the coding task: `Gemini 3.1 Pro` overlaps real users more\nclosely compared to `Llama-3.1-8B-Instruct` .\n\n\nPreprint.\n\n\n**1** **Introduction**\n\n\nThe role of user simulators is to model the diverse behaviors of real users, providing a scalable\nmeans to train and evaluate AI systems on the interactions that they encounter in real-world settings\n\n[26, 14, 39, 45]. Recent works build user simulators by training Large Language Models (LLMs)\nto generate responses that resemble those of real users [33, 16, 58]. Yet real users exhibit a broad,\nheterogeneous distribution of behaviors [65, 66, 28]. For example, some users tend to underspecify\ntheir requests, while others fully specify every constraint. The extent to which user simulators capture\nthis distribution has not been measured.\n\n\nA user simulator can fail to capture the distribution of real users in two ways: by demonstrating\nbehaviors that real users rarely exhibit (low prec **i** son), or by failing to demonstrate behaviors that real\nusers do exhibit (low reca **l** ), mirroring precision and recall metrics for generative models [ 46, 23, 11].\nThese failure modes bias training and evaluation, and yield assistants that struggle to generalize to\nthe diverse behaviors of real users [52].'], '2605.07847v1_chunk_16': ['**6.3** **Linear Classification**\n\n\nWe validate that our user behavior representation embeddings encode meaningful differences between\nreal and simulated users by training a linear classifier. For each simulator, we construct a dataset\nof 5,000 real and 5,000 simulated embeddings, and then train an L2-regularized logistic regression\nclassifier to classify embeddings as real or simulated. We average results over 5 stratified random\n80/20 train-test splits. The classification accuracies across simulators are consistently high, ranging\nfrom 90.92% to 99.63%, and also correlate strongly with our distributional metrics (Figure 2). This\nconfirms that the embeddings encode meaningful differences between real and simulated users. The\nfull accuracy scores and correlations for all metrics are presented in Appendix H.\n\n\n**7** **Discussion**\n\n\n**7.1** **How Do User Behavior Distributions Compare Among Simulators?**\n\n\nOur main results show that the distributional gap to real users varies across simulators. This raises a\nnatural question: how do the behviorl d **a** rbuon of user **ist** imulator compare to each other? **s** To\ninvestigate this, we pool the user behavior representations across all 24 simulators, quantize them\ninto distributions, and compute the JS divergence between all pairs. Figure 3 reports the results.\n\n\nMany simulators behave similarly to each other: 30% of the 552 pairwise comparisons have JS _<_\n0 _._ 10. Pairs from the same family tend to be the most similar, achieving the lowest scores in the\ndataset. The simulators with the lowest mean pairwise JS scores are `Qwen3.5-122B-A10B` (0 _._ 14),\n\n\n7'], '2605.07847v1_chunk_20': ['**8** **Related Work**\n\n\n**User Simulation.** LLMs have demonstrated the ability to simulate believable human behavior,\nand are increasingly used as user simulators for interactive evaluation [9, 53, 68, 5, 25], synthetic\ndata generation [10, 17, 43], and reinforcement learning [69, 59]. Across these applications, initial\napproaches rely on prompting LLMs [9, 35, 36, 29, 43]. However, these prompt-based simulators\nstruggle to consistently adhere to assigned user goals or profiles, motivating recent methods that train\nLLM-based user simulators with goal-tracking or persona-consistency objectives [31, 1]. In order to\nbuild simulators that can faithfully represent real users, other works train LLMs with response-level\nsimilarity objectives, such as supervised fine-tuning on real user data [33] or aligning latent reasoning\nstates through reinforcement learning [16, 58, 63].\n\n\n**User Simulator Evaluation.** Recent works investigate how LLM-based user simulators compare\nto real users. One direction compares assistant evaluations conducted with simulators against those\nconducted with real users, finding that simulator-based evaluations are poor estimates of agent\nperformance and obscure demographic disparities [13, 48]. A second direction compares simulator\nand human behaviors at the feature level, finding systematic divergence on lexical, syntactic, and\nstylistic metrics [22, 67, 7].\n\n\nAcross both training and evaluation work, simulator fidelity is typically measured at the response or\nfeature level. While some works investigate simulating diverse user populations [28, 2, 17], ours is\nthe first to measure how well user simulators capture the distribution of real user behaviors. We do\nthis by extracting representations of user behavior that go beyond lexical or stylistic features, and\nclustering them to compare the distributions of real and simulated user behaviors.'], '2605.07847v1_chunk_18': ['First, we pair the simulators with the smallest distributional gap to real users: `Gemini 3.1 Pro` with\n`GPT-5.4`, and `gpt-oss-120b` with `gemma-4-31B-it` . Both pairs achieve smaller JS divergence\nthan either individual simulator on coding and writing. Next, we pair simulators that are behaviorally\ndistinct from others, `UserLM-8b` and `GPT-5.4 mini`, with each of `Gemini 3.1 Pro`, `GPT-5.4`,\n`gemma-4-31B-it`, and `gpt-oss-120b` . These improve over the individual simulators on writing\nand remain competitive on coding. Conversely, combining behaviorally similar simulators, such as\n`gemma-4-31B-it` and `Claude Haiku 4.5`, does not help.\n\n\nThese results suggest that combining behaviorally complementary simulators can reduce the distributional gap to real users. This combination strategy is conceptually similar to mixture-of-experts\n\n[49, 15] and assistant-side routing [37, 56, 34], and learning a router that selects the appropriate\nsimulator is a natural extension we leave to future work.\n\n\n**7.3** **Interpreting the Behavioral Clusters**\n\n\nFigure 4: Word clouds of w-capturd (green), **el** mi **s** ed (blue), and h **al** ucinted (red) behaviors for\n`Gemini 3.1 Pro` on coding based on a TF-IDF analysis on behavioral clusters.\n\n\nThe behavioral distributions reveal not only how much simulators diverge from real users, but which\nbehaviors they capture, miss, or hallucinate. We classify each cluster by the ratio of real to simulated\nconversations into three categories: w-capturd if real and simulated are roughly balanced, **el** mi **s**\n\n\n8\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_9)\n\n: : : : : :\n\n\n**el** **s** ed **al** ucinted\n\n\n**el** **s**'], '2605.07847v1_chunk_17': ['7\n\n\nTable 3: The distributional gap between real and simulated user behaviors when combining pairs\nof simulators. When generating conversations, we randomly sample which LLM serves as the\nuser simulator. We report forward KL divergence (KL ), backward KL divergence (KL bwd ), and\nJensen–Shannon divergence (JS) across coding and writing tasks. "" indicates higher is better and #\nindicates lower is better. Darker blue indicates closer behavioral distribution to real users. Subscripts\nshow the change relative to the better of the two individual simulators\n\n\n**Coding** **Writing**\n\n\n**User Simulator** KL KL bwd JS # KL KL bwd JS #\n\n\n: : : : : :\n\n\n**el** **s** ed **al** ucinted\n\n\n**el** **s**\n\n\n\n![Image: Error processing image description](tg://2605.07847v1_image_8)\n\n: : : : : :\n\n\n**el** **s** ed **al** ucinted\n\n\n**el** **s**\n\n\n\n: : : : : :\n\n\n**el** **s** ed **al** ucinted\n\n\n**el** **s**\n\n\n\n`gemma-4-31B-it` + `Claude Haiku 4.5` .364 _↑_ : .345 _↑_ : .346 _↑_ : .562 _↑_ : .568 _↑_ : .572 _↑_ :\n\n\n`gemma-4-26B-A4B-it` (0 _._ 15), `gemma-4-E2B-it` (0 _._ 15), and `Qwen3.5-35B-A3B` (0 _._ 15). A few\nsimulators stand out and demonstrate behaviors that diverge from the rest. These include `UserLM-8b`,\nwhich has the highest mean pairwise JS score of 0 _._ 41, followed by `GPT-5.4 mini` with a score of\n0 _._ 33. Pairwise JS scores are consistently higher for writing than coding, which aligns with our main\nresults, where the divergences from real users were also higher for writing.\n\n\n**7.2** **Can we Combine User Simulators to Reduce the Gap With Real Users?**\n\n\nSince our pairwise analysis shows that some user simulators behave distinctly from each other, we\ntest whether combining pairs can reduce the gap to real users by randomly sampling which simulator\ngenerates each conversation. Table 3 reports the results.']}}}",,33.457249070631974,0.9106145251396648,0.03270465489566613,311.5,0.0,False,0.0,1